<HEAD>Victim Wakes Screaming from Dreams of Torture</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-Philippines-Rights, Bjt ^By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAGAWE, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Her own screams wake <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Aniban </PERSON> from nightmares about military captors connecting wires to her thumbs, toes and breasts and sending jolts of electricity through her naked body. Miss Aniban, 26, a volunteer for the church-affiliated Task Force Detainees, said she and a male colleague were arrested in November and accused of being couriers for communist rebels. She denies it. She said she was interrogated at three military camps in the <LOCATION> Baguio </LOCATION> area, where they were arrested, and her captors tried to rape her three times. `` They tied my toes, thumbs and nipples with electric wires and then they plugged it into a socket,'' she said. `` They did it to me repeatedly and I fainted so many times. `` They took off my clothes and made me sit on a wet bed. I had my hands tied in the back and a pillow over my mouth. I screamed, and I felt like a chicken being butchered.'' After three days, Miss Aniban and her colleague were released. She said they had signed statements saying they were rebels and agreeing to serve as military informants. She said she did not file charges against her captors because whe felt it would be useless. Last year, she convinced her younger brother <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> to leave the rebels and he was shot to death five months later. As she cradled her dying brother in her arms, <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Aniban </PERSON> said, he told her his assailants were pro-government militiamen. The family filed charges with the government <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> and a civil court, but no hearings have been held. Her experiences made her bitter. Although she works for a human rights group organized to monitor abuses under <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, the exiled former president, she now opposes <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>, his successor. `` I expected my work to be risky, but I did not expect it could still happen under the new government,'' she said. `` Now, she is no longer my president.''
