<HEAD>Government Banning TV Ads That Show Only Non-Malaysians</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government is banning racy television advertisements and commercials that show only non-Malaysian models, the information minister said in an interview published today. Beginning July 1, Caucasian and other non-Malaysian models can continue to appear in commercials only if the ads also include Malays, Chinese, Indians or other races that predominate in <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>, said Information Minister <PERSON> Mohamed </PERSON> <PERSON> Rahmat </PERSON>. `` We have told advertisers that if the cast is a mix of Caucasian, Pan-Asian and some of the multi-racial groups in <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>, we will allow the commercials to appear,'' <PERSON> Rahmat </PERSON> said in an interview published in the New Straits Times daily. Commercials with women in swimsuits and scanty clothing will also be banned in this country Islam where is the official religion. Of the country's three TV channels, two are owned by the government and the other belongs to the ruling party. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Tang </PERSON>, Association of Accredited Advertising Agents of <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION> President, said the ban was `` a little too harsh and debatable'' and called for the review of the ban. <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>'s 17 million population is 55 percent Malay and 37 percent Chinese, with the remainder mainly Indian.
