<SECOND>PM-Nuke-Sleeping,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nuke Plant Shut for Sleeping Operators Set to Reopen</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: meeting late afternoon EDT; top prospects uncertain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The only nuclear plant ever shut down because control room operators slept on duty is ready to resume operations, amid signs that the <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> will give its assent. An <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> order has kept the Peach Bottom plant in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> dormant for two years, but the commission planned a meeting for this afternoon along with a `` possible'' vote on reopening. Privately, commission officials said last week that all signs pointed to the plant gaining permission _ if not today, then shortly afterward _ to begin a slow ascension that would take it back to full power. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Murley </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION>'s top reactor licensing official, declined to make a prediction Friday on the outcome of the meeting. But he said in an interview that the commission has seen significant progress in the management of the plant by <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` Clearly there have been big changes in the company, and it's a new company as far as <ORGANIZATION> Peach </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bottom </ORGANIZATION> is concerned,'' <PERSON> Murley </PERSON> said. `` The operators have been retrained and there appears to be a new attitude.'' As the only plant ever shut down because of operator negligence, <ORGANIZATION> Peach </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bottom </ORGANIZATION> is unique in the industry. Dealing with operators _ with people _ is vastly different than replacing equipment, and the shutdown has meant a review of the plant's entire management structure. The plant, located on the <LOCATION> Susquehanna </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> near the <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> border, was ordered to stop producing power on March 31, 1987, by the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION>, which said continued operation posed a public safety threat. A year later, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Everett </PERSON> stepped down as the utility's chairman and chief executive officer following criticism of the handling of Peach Bottom <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> has spent about $ 250 million in shutdown-related costs. The figure includes modifications to the plant, purchases of replacement power, and the company's share of a $ 1.25 million fine, the largest in <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> history. While the utility has shuffled its personnel, the changes at the plant have included more than just new faces. The company said management will play a broader role in day-to-day plant affairs than before. To end catnaps by operators, plant officials replaced comfortable, high-backed chairs in the control room with low-backed models. Operators' rotations have been changed so that workers do a week of days, followed by a week of an afternoon-evening shift, and then work the overnight. The rotation, which includes days off, used to go in the reverse order. The sleeping problems at Peach Bottom were not confined to a few workers. Last August, 33 present or former operators were fined $ 500 to $ 1,000 for `` sleeping and-or other acts of inattention to duty.'' `` We did n't set out to pick somebody and make an example of them,'' <PERSON> Murley </PERSON> said. `` It's just that the behavior we saw at Peach Bottom was so egregious that we felt we had no choice but to order them shut down. INPO -LRB- the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Operations </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- came to same conclusion and put more pressure on the top management.'' INPO, an Atlanta-based nuclear watchdog group, termed the plant `` an embarrassment to the industry and the nation'' in 1988. But this year, the group said <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION>'s corrective actions at Peach Bottom have been `` responsive and effective.'' The utility said it would propose restarting one of its two working reactors, then seek permission to fire up the other one later this year. It would take a few months for either of the units to reach full power once approval is granted.
</TEXT>
