<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Echoes of a Speakers' Scandal Followed Blaine for
Life</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 On the morning of June 5, 1876, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blaine </PERSON>, the speaker of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION>, stood in the well of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and waved a packet of letters in the air. <PERSON> Blaine </PERSON>, one of the nation's foremost politicians, was in serious trouble. And he was about to confound his accusers. Nearly 113 years later another speaker of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> _ <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> _ faces accusations of unethical behavior in office. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> adamantly denies any wrongdoing. But he has been the subject of the most prolonged and intense of the several investigations conducted over the decades into the private and public affairs of a speaker of the House. Speaker <PERSON> Blaine </PERSON> rode out his scandal, but echoes of it were to follow him for the rest of his career. In the spring of 1876, <PERSON> Blaine </PERSON> was a frontrunner for the Republican presidential nomination in the election that would replace President <PERSON> Ulysses </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>'s corruption-ridden administration. Three years earlier Reps. <PERSON> Oakes </PERSON> <PERSON> Ames </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Mass </LOCATION>., and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON>, D-Mass., had been censured by the House for involvement in the so-called Credit Mobilier scandal in which railroad construction stock had been given to selected members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, allegedly for favors Now <PERSON> Blaine </PERSON> became embroiled in the scandal, facing accusations that the <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION> had paid the speaker an inflated price for stock of a defunct and bankrupt rail line. An investigation was launched by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> but it was sputtering when new evidence emerged. It took the form of a set of letters between <PERSON> Blaine </PERSON> and a business partner which had come into the possession of a third man, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulligan </PERSON>. <PERSON> Mulligan </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to testify before the committee, encountered an unexpected visitor at his hotel _ Speaker <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blaine </PERSON>. According to <PERSON> Mulligan </PERSON>, an emotional session followed in which <PERSON> Blaine </PERSON> fell to his hands and knees and begged for the letters, threatening suicide if he did not receive them. <PERSON> Mulligan </PERSON> claimed <PERSON> Blaine </PERSON> obtained the letters by a pretext and left the hotel. An uproar followed and <PERSON> Blaine </PERSON> came under intense pressure to make the <PERSON> Mulligan </PERSON> letters public. He refused, claiming they were private property. Instead, he obtained a statement from two lawyers who said they had examined the letters and found nothing relevant to the investigation. The uproar continued and <PERSON> Blaine </PERSON> set about to defuse it. On June 5 he appeared on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor and waved the packet exclaiming, `` There they are. ... There are the original letters.'' <PERSON> Blaine </PERSON> then read aloud what he said were the contents of each of the letters. He said he had handed over `` every solitary scrap and scrimption'' for inclusion in the Congressional Record. They had, he declared, `` no more to do with that investigation than the North Pole.'' But no one was ever shown the originals of the letters to verify <PERSON> Blaine </PERSON>'s reading of them. Events moved rapidly. <PERSON> Blaine </PERSON> collapsed outside his church suffering from a possible heat stroke. The investigation was postponed for two weeks to await his recovery. But before the committee could reconvene, the governor of <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> appointed <PERSON> Blaine </PERSON> to fill a vacancy in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. The investigation was postponed again, and eventually died. <PERSON> Blaine </PERSON>'s political backers proceeded, in classical <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> fashion, to make the best of a bad situation. In the 20th century it's called making lemonade out of a lemon. <PERSON> Blaine </PERSON>'s name was placed in nomination at the Republican National Convention by <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ingersoll </PERSON> on June 15, 1876, with words that gave <PERSON> Blaine </PERSON> an enduring nickname: `` The plumed knight from the state of <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>.'' `` Like an armed warrior, like a plumed knight, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blaine </PERSON> marched down the halls of the American <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and threw his shining lance full and fair against the brazen forehead of every traitor to his country and every maligner of his fair reputation.'' <PERSON> Blaine </PERSON> never obtained the presidency. But he twice was appointed secretary of state. No House speaker has ever been ousted. But several have been singed during the 200-year history of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Clay </PERSON>, who was elected speaker six times, drew accusations of `` corrupt bargain'' when the close election of 1824 was thrown into the House of Representatives. The choice was between <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Quincy </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>. <PERSON> Clay </PERSON> and other members of the <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> delegation tipped the balance in favor of <P