<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Leave the kids at home, skip the <ORGANIZATION> Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> and take a `` scandal tour'' of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, a raunchy romp through the ruins of political careers that takes ogling grownups from the Watergate to <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON>'s old townhouse. With a <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> impersonator acting as host, the 75-minute bus tour leaving on weekends from the posh Ritz-Carlton Hotel is just the tonic for bored tourists willing to spend 20 bucks to indulge their taste for the trashy. Careening through city streets in a red, white and blue bus, a satirical comedy troupe called Gross National Product entertains customers with a bawdy commentary on passing landmarks where some of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s most prominent residents fell prey to sex, booze, greed or lust for power. Mostly sex. Outside the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, a <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON> look-alike croons a song to <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, the gentleman who supposedly preferred blondes. `` In my eight years in office, there will be no sex in the White House,'' vowed <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, seizing the microphone. Past the Executive Office Building, where mock secretary <PERSON> Fawn </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> sobs her admiration for Col. <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> _ `` the most patriotic man in the universe'' _ and recalls their Iran-Contra shredding parties. Passengers are given small plastic bags filled with shredded paper and signed `` Love, Fawn.'' On to the <LOCATION> Tidal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basin </LOCATION>, where an inebriated <PERSON> Wilbur </PERSON> <PERSON> Mills </PERSON> saw both his congressional career and his companion, stripper <PERSON> Fanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Foxe </PERSON>, sink beneath the 