<HEAD>Voters Reject Move To Deny Amnesty To Rights Offenders During Dictatorship</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with amnesty opponent conceding
defeat, newer figures. PickS up 5th pvs, `Shortly after...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTEVIDEO, Uruguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Uruguayans on Sunday voted not to end an amnesty for soldiers and police accused of human rights abuses during the 1973-85 military dictatorship. With 6,360 of 7,072 districts reporting in the referendum on the 1986 amnesty, supporters tallied 922,185 votes, or 53.32 percent, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, and while opponents numbered 678,087, or 39.21 percent. About 128,969 votes, or 7.47 percent, were blank, annulled or ruled questionable for technical reasons. Early today, a co-president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> for a Referendum conceded defeat. `` The law has been confirmed,'' <PERSON> Matilde </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> <PERSON> Larreta </PERSON> told reporters. `` Without doubt, the pronouncement of the popular will should be adhered to.'' However, she called for a `` national compromise'' on the issue, and said, `` about 40 percent voted to annul the law. ... The country and all its institutions can not be insensitive to the circumstances that nearly one-half of the population disagrees radically'' with the amnesty. Unofficial tallies indicated that voters in the capital narrowly rejected the amnesty while voters in the countryside heavily favored it. Shortly after polls closed at 7:30 p.m -LRB- 6:30 p.m. EDT -RRB- and before any results were known, President <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanguinetti </PERSON> called for national unity in an address carried on national radio and television. `` Until a short while ago, some of us were ` yellows,' others ` greens,''' he said. `` That has just ended. ... We are all Uruguayan citizens and now we have to listen to the voice of the people.'' Supporters of the amnesty cast yellow ballots; opponents cast green ones. The government, including <PERSON> Sanguinetti </PERSON>, supported the 1986 law giving amnesty to scores of police and soldiers accused of human rights abuses in a campaign against leftist guerrillas during 12 years of military rule. Leftist political parties and human rights groups, which mounted a huge petition drive to put the issue to a vote, say trials of those accused of human rights abuses are necessary before democracy can be considered fully restored. After campaigning ended on Thursday, both sides pledged to respect the outcome. By late Sunday night, neither side had claimed victory or conceded defeat. `` We're still gathering information and making our own computations,'' said <PERSON> Alberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> for a Referendum. The <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> estimated that about 65 percent of the 2.3 million Uruguayans eligible to vote had cast ballots. Voting is mandatory in <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> and turnout usually tops 80 percent. Turnout apparently was lower than usual Sunday because of gray skies and rain. But lines were long from the moment schools, cultural centers, movie theaters and other places used as polling stations opened. Many voters waited for an hour or longer huddled under umbrellas or building overhangs. `` A country that forgets its past has no future,'' said a well-dressed woman standing in line to vote in a neighborhood along the estuary of the River Plate. `` A future of peace and justice depend on overturning'' the amnesty, said the woman, who refused to give her name. If voters rejected the amnesty, trials would not start immediately. Vice President <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Tarigo </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> then would have to decide whether the amnesty would be annulled _ meaning a ruling that it never legally existed _ or merely overturned. If the law were just overturned, the change could not be applied retroactively. The amnesty freed security forces from the possibility of prosecution in connection with a 1970s crackdown on leftist subversion. About 150 Uruguayans were killed and 200 were arrested and never seen again. Thousands suffered physical and psychological torture under detention. The military maintains it was fighting a war against urban guerrillas, particularly the leftist <ORGANIZATION> Tupamaros </ORGANIZATION>, whose bombings, kidnappings and assassinations had convulsed the country for years. The military took control in February 1973 by setting up a security council with the authority to veto government decisions. Four months later, it forced President <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bordaberry </PERSON> to dissolve congress. The Tupamaro urban guerrillas by that time had been quelled as a military threat, and the armed forces began to crack down on leftist subversion in general. <PERSON> Sanguinetti </PERSON> was elected in November 1984 after democracy was restored. By 1986, about 50 cases had been filed accusing about 180 soldiers and police of kidnapping, murder and torture. The military high command said it would not require soldiers to answer charges in civilian courts. <PERSON> Sanguinetti </PERSON> broke the impasse by pressing for an amnesty, which <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> passed on Dec. 22, 1986. Human rights and leftist political groups vowed to challenge the amnesty in a vote. The <ORGANIZATION> Electoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> last year affirmed that the required 555,701 voters, or 25 percent of the electorate, had signed petitions for a referendum.
