<HEAD>Two More Bodies Found Buried At Ranch</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 5-9, `Acting on ...' with five grafs to UPDATE with
funeral home saying new victims killed by machete blows; CORRECT age of
man in 5th and 9th grafs to 72, sted 77.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MATAMOROS, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Authorities discovered two more bodies Sunday buried on a collective farm two miles south of a ranch where 13 victims of a cult of human sacrifice were found last week. Investigators said they have evidence the male victims were killed by the same drug smuggling cult suspected of performing human sacrifices on the 13 males discovered Tuesday at <LOCATION> Rancho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Elena </LOCATION>, about 20 miles west of <LOCATION> Matamoros </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Cameron </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Sheriff <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> said the victims found Sunday were connected to the drug smuggling operations of the cult, but were not victims of the cult's rites as were the other 13. Unlike the bodies uncovered at <ORGANIZATION> Rancho </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Santa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elena </ORGANIZATION>, the bodies found on the farm were not mutilated, said Mexican federal police group chief <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Elias </PERSON> <PERSON> Salazar </PERSON>. Acting on a tip from some children, a 72-year-old man led police Sunday to the common grave in a clearing in an orchard on the farm, <LOCATION> Ejido </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Librada </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Salazar </PERSON> told reporters. The dead were identified as <PERSON> Moises </PERSON> <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON> <PERSON> Vasquez </PERSON>, the son of the man who led police to the site, and <PERSON> Hector </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuente </PERSON>, also known as `` El Guero'', or `` The Blond.'' Both were killed by machete chops to the back of the head, said <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Degadillo </PERSON>, an employee at <LOCATION> Funerales </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rosario </LOCATION>. Some of the victims found on the ranch last week also were killed by machete chops. `` It was a revenge type killing. It was a drug deal gone sour,'' <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> said. The sheriff said the men apparently died in May. He said he knew about the men because of an ongoing investigation into the drug smuggling ring. However, a spokeswoman for the federal judicial police in <LOCATION> Matamoros </LOCATION> said the two men were farmhands who had been missing since last May. The children told the 72-year-old man, <PERSON> Hidalgo </PERSON> <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON>, that they had seen some people burying a body in an orchard last October, <PERSON> Salazar </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON>'s son, <PERSON> Moises </PERSON>, 52, disappeared last May. <PERSON> Salazar </PERSON> said <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON> had discounted the children's tale until the 13 bodies were dug up. The two bodies were stacked and appeared to be those of adults, investigators said. Neither had been positively identified as of Sunday night. Officials disinterred the second body just before sunset Sunday. <PERSON> Salazar </PERSON> searched through the pockets of a pair of black pants found on the second body and discovered 3,000 Mexican pesos and a $ 5 bill. Four suspects arrested in the slayings of the 13 discovered on <LOCATION> Rancho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Elena </LOCATION> have told police they killed 13 or 14 people in bizarre rites intended to protect a marijuana smuggling ring. Among the victims were a 16-year-old boy and <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Kilroy </PERSON>, missing since March when he came here during spring break from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION>. Police said the suspects have been cooperative in pointing out the bodies and had not mentioned burying anybody on Ejido <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Librada </LOCATION>. Ejido means collective farm in Spanish. Officials said the group trafficked in drugs and believed the human sacrifice would protect them from police. In <LOCATION> Matamoros </LOCATION>, authorities found altars covered with black chicken feathers, burned turtles, cigars and other occult offerings. The bodies had been mutilated, some with their hearts or brains ripped out. Police in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> are seeking alleged ringleader <PERSON> Adolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Constanzo </PERSON> and three others, including <PERSON> Sara </PERSON> <PERSON> Aldrete </PERSON>, a college student identified as the `` godmother'' of the cult. In a related development, <ORGANIZATION> Notimex </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> Mexican </LOCATION> government news agency, reported Saturday that a woman identifying herself as <PERSON> Sara </PERSON> <PERSON> Aldrete </PERSON> <PERSON> Villareal </PERSON> called a local radio station threatening to kidnap children as hostages and burn them if the four prisoners were not released. The news agency said local police in <LOCATION> Matamoros </LOCATION> dismissed the report as a hoax.
