<HEAD>Beijing, Shanghai Students Hold Marches To Honor Hu Yaobang</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of students in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> marched today to mourn the death of former <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Hu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yaobang </PERSON>, an outspoken reformist toppled by conservatives two years ago. `` Long live <PERSON> Hu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yaobang </PERSON>, long live democracy, long live freedom, long live the rule of law!'' chanted more than 600 students from <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s Political Science and <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>. Marching behind a huge red flag bearing their school's name, the students laid wreaths in Hu's honor at the base of a monument to Communist martyrs in <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>, the symbolic seat of power in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hu </PERSON>, who died Saturday at age 73 after suffering a heart attack, was regarded by intellectuals as favoring greater artistic and scholarly freedoms than other Chinese leaders. While a crowd of several thousand looked on, the students sang the Internationale and chanted slogans for about half an hour before dispersing. `` We just want to express our grief over <PERSON> Hu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yaobang </PERSON>'s death because he was a great leader and his death is a loss to the nation,'' said one student. `` We are n't making any political statement.'' But another student, <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> <PERSON> Zhixun </PERSON>, said the students were expressing `` an attitude'' of dissatisfaction with the failure of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s leaders to institute democratic reforms. `` <PERSON> Hu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yaobang </PERSON> dared to speak out, and he said things we students supported,'' <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> said. In <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, more than 1,000 students marched late Sunday from <ORGANIZATION> Fudan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Univ