<DATELINE>LAGUNA BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A group of dolphin-loving environmentalists recline on the sand with eyes closed and meditate, opening their minds to receive telepathic messages they say the playful marine mammals send them. `` We're offering a true and profound experience with nature,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON>, 28, who directs Project Delphinus Internaional from his rented seaside home 50 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. As a group of the intelligent sea mammals surfaces near kelp beds visible from his window, <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> lifts an 8-inch conch shell and blows, sending a deep bellow across the water. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> says the unorthodox group set up shop to document communication between dolphins and humans in hopes the information will further their environmental goals. He said if people truly believe they can communicate with dolphins they will treat the animals with greater respect. `` Once you do that, how can you throw a beer can on the beach, or shoot a dolphin because he's eating your squid?'' <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> asked. The project was founded in 1987 by <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurley </PERSON> with the goal of filming a documentary on dolphins to help end their slaughter by fishermen. Group activities include meditation sessions on the beach, wilderness excursions and dolphin-watching boat trips and environmental talks. They also send a quarterly newsletter to about 3,000 people statewide. Project members believe the rituals of Australian aborigines, Polynesian natives and other ancient cultures can help modern man reunite with nature. To honor those rites and pay homage to dolphins during boating trips, group members sound the conch shell horns and beat drums lined with goat bellies to duplicate the way some ancient tribes called the seagoing mammals that are renowned for the grace and intelligence.
