<HEAD>Dollar Falls on Signs U.S. Economy Slowing, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar fell against all major currencies in early European trading today on growing signs that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic growth is slowing, dealers said. Gold prices were also lower. `` The dollar is low and calm,'' said one Italian trader, attributing the dollar's steep decline over the weekend to the market's perception that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest rates have peaked. Last week's figures showing the growth rate in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> producer prices slowed in March and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit widened in February were interpreted as a signal for slower economic growth and perhaps lower <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest rates, dealers said. `` Major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic indicators released last week were within the market's anticipated range, but now dollar-denominated interest rates such as -LRB- <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> -RRB- Treasury bonds will be in a downward direction in the long-term perspective,'' said a dealer at the Bank of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> in the Japanese capital. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar fell 0.62 yen to a closing 131.83. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted higher at 132.15 yen. Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Friday: _ 1.8595 West German marks, down from 1.8725 _ 1.6405 Swiss francs, down from 1.6510 _ 6.2910 French francs, down from 6.3350 _ 2.09625 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1145 _ 1,363.90 Italian lire, down from 1,374.25 _ 1.1855 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1875 In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the British pound rose to $ 1.7080, compared with $ 1.7000 Friday. Bullion dealers said gold failed to get support from the weaker dollar. `` Gold is in a bearish mood at the moment,'' one <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> dealer commented. `` There is a lack of faith in the market after its recent dismal performance.'' Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 385.50 a troy ounce, down from $ 386.50 bid late Friday. At midmorning today, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $ 385.15 In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, gold was selling at a bid $ 385.20, down from $ 387.00 late Friday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold rose 71 cents to close at a bid $ 386.74. Silver was quoted in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> today at a bid price of $ 5.81 a troy ounce, down from Friday's $ 5.87.
