 <PERSON> Toni </PERSON> <PERSON> Matt </PERSON> is a former Austrian ski champion and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> national downhill champion, but he says he is remembered most for one legendary mad dash down <PERSON> Tuckerman </PERSON> <PERSON> Ravine </PERSON> 50 years ago. `` I got more mileage out of that race than all the rest of them put together,'' he said Sunday on a nostalgic return to the mountain on the 50th anniversary of his famous schuss in the Inferno Race. <PERSON> Matt </PERSON> said he `` never skied anything like it and I do n't think anyone else has either ... because it drops off so fast.'' <PERSON> Tuckerman </PERSON> <PERSON> Ravine </PERSON>, on 6,288-foot <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, is only a small portion of the four-mile race. Its most notable feature is the headwall, with a 1,000-foot drop at angles that reach 65 degrees. <PERSON> Matt </PERSON> made a straight run down the ravine. <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, the late broadcaster who witnessed the event along with 2,000 spectators, described it this way: `` The first racers took a good three or four swinging, high-speed turns on the headwall to check their speed. But when <PERSON> Matt </PERSON> came bolting over the edge, because it was so steep, he knew a turn would n't slow him down _ he schussed the wall like a lead plummet hitting 85 miles per hour as he came streaming off the bottom, his skis shattering the icy snow.'' <PERSON> Matt </PERSON> reeled through the bottom of the trail, just missing a tree before finishing the run in 6 minutes, 29.4 seconds. That was a full minute faster than runner-up <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Durrance </PERSON> and smashed the previous record of more than 13 minutes. World Cup downhill races last about two minutes, and racers average about 75 mph. `` I do n't remember anything about it,'' said the 69-year-old <PERSON> Matt </PERSON>, who lives in <LOCATION> Pawling </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION> `` It goes so fast. It only takes a few seconds from time you see the headwall and you're halfway down, and before you know it, it's all over. `` I was n't frightened. I was used to speed, although not that fast, and I was in good shape,'' he said. The race was discontinued after <PERSON> Matt </PERSON>'s 1939 feat because of unpredictable weather.
