<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Tax     04-17 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Tax,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Accepts California Tax Case on Multinationals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed to settle some key questions involving the ability of multinational corporations to challenge state taxes in federal court. What the justices decide sometime next year in a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> case could carry big-money significance for most states and many big businesses. The court, granting an appeal by <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> officials, said they will review a ruling that allowed two multinational corporations to challenge a state tax in federal court. In a 1984 ruling seen as a major victory for states, the justices ruled that <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> may tax multinational corporations based on the businesses' worldwide income. But that decision applied only to multinationals whose parent company is located in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The case acted on today involves multinationals whose parent company is based in a foreign country. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s business tax _ the same levy upheld in the 1984 ruling _ was challenged by <ORGANIZATION> Alcan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aluminium </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Limited </ORGANIZATION>, a Canadian corporation, and <ORGANIZATION> Imperial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, a British corporation. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> taxed subsidiaries of the multinationals doing business in the state. The <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> tax employs what is known as the unitary system. The method bases the tax on a share of worldwide earnings, payroll and property value of each multinational and its subsidiaries. At issue in the appeal acted on today is whether multinationals based abroad have legal standing to challenge such unitary state taxes in federal courts in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Alcan </ORGANIZATION> and Imperial challenged the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> tax in a federal court in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, where the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Franchise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> has an office. A federal judge threw out the suits on grounds that the parent companies claimed they were injured only in their capacity as shareholders of their subsidiaries _ and therefore lacked legal standing. Generally, shareholders are barred from suing in such cases unless they can demonstrate `` a direct and independent injury'' from the corporation. The 7th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> last October overturned the judge's decision againt <ORGANIZATION> Alcan </ORGANIZATION> and Imperial, reinstating their suits. The appeals court said there is grounds for the parent companies to assert a direct and independent injury. `` Shareholders with direct, personal interests in a cause of action can bring suit even if the corporation's legal rights and obligations are also implicated,'' the appeals court said. The asserted injuries to <ORGANIZATION> Alcan </ORGANIZATION> and Imperial are direct and independent, the appeals court said, because `` the unitary tax diminishes the attractiveness of owning <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> subsidiaries in comparison with entering into contracts with independent companies as a means of engaging in foreign commerce.'' The appeals court added: `` The potential for the unitary tax to penalize foreign ownership of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> assets distinguishes'' it from other forms of state regulation _ environmental or safety rules, for example _ that `` would presumably affect foreign and domestically owned operations fairly equally.'' The appeals court said taxes like the one imposed by <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> `` have fueled a simmering trade controversy which has raised concerns about foreign retaliation and the -LRB- <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' -RRB- ability to speak with one voice on matters of foreign commerce.'' Most states and the <ORGANIZATION> Multistate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> joined in supporting <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s appeal. The commission said the 7th Circuit court ruling's effect is to permit multinational corporations to `` forum shop'' around the country for a sympathetic federal judge who will permit the businesses to challenge the state taxes. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Franchise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Alcan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aluminium </ORGANIZATION>, 88-1400.
</TEXT>
