<HEAD>Court Asks Administration for View in Banking Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, in an important banking industry case, today asked the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration for its view on whether <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks with branch offices overseas must pay depositors after foreign governments seize or freeze those accounts. The court invited <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyers to comment on rulings that required <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> to pay depositors. The justices are not expected to say whether they will grant full review to the case until hearing from the government lawyers, which could take months. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bork </PERSON>, a former federal judge whose <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> nomination was defeated by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in 1987, is representing <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION>. If the court were to grant review, <PERSON> Bork </PERSON> might become the first defeated nominee in the court's history to later argue a case before the justices. In the appeal acted on today, <PERSON> Bork </PERSON> said billions of dollars are at stake. There are more than 900 branches of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks operating in 73 countries, with some $ 225 billion in deposits. The cases acted on today stem from the fall of <LOCATION> Saigon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, to the <LOCATION> Vietcong </LOCATION> in 1975 and economic troubles in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> in 1983. The Vietnamese case involves an account at <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Saigon </LOCATION> office opened in 1974 by <PERSON> Quang </PERSON> <PERSON> Quy </PERSON> <PERSON> Trinh </PERSON>, a retired South Vietnamese government official. The account, which paid annual interest of 19 percent compounded daily, was for <PERSON> Trinh </PERSON>'s son, <PERSON> Ngoc </PERSON> <PERSON> Quang </PERSON> <PERSON> Trinh </PERSON>, a student in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> at the time. The deposit agreement between <PERSON> Trinh </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> said the bank did not accept responsibility for any loss due to `` government orders, laws ... or from any other cause beyond its control.'' <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> closed its <LOCATION> Saigon </LOCATION> branch on April 24, 1975, on the eve of the city's fall to communist troops. The elder <PERSON> Trinh </PERSON> was placed in a re-education camp by the new regime, and after he was released in 1980 sent the <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> passbook to his son in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>. The younger <PERSON> Trinh </PERSON> sued the bank to recover the deposits. The 6th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> last July upheld a ruling that <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> must pay Trinh $ 3,196.36, including $ 1,792.69 in interest. The appeals court rejected <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION>'s argument that its deposit agreement excused it from paying deposits lost because of political revolution. The agreement the elder <PERSON> Trinh </PERSON> signed did not mean he was `` aware that he had given up his right to proceed against the home office -LRB- of <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- in the event the branch was no longer in existence and could not pay its depositors,'' the appeals court said. It added that both <PERSON> Trinh </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> are innocent parties in the case, but one must suffer a loss. In the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> case, <ORGANIZATION> Wells </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fargo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Asia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Limited </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> deposited $ 2 million with the <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> branch in <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> in June 1983. The money was to be repaid with interest six months later. But on Oct. 15, 1983, the <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> government of <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> _ who was deposed and fled to <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> in 1986 _ froze the accounts of foreign banks. The move prevented <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> from repaying the <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> deposits to <LOCATION> Wells </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fargo </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Wells </PERSON> <PERSON> Fargo </PERSON> sued to recover the money, and <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> later paid it $ 934,000. <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> withheld the balance of the original deposit. A federal judge in 1987 ordered <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> to repay the balance in 1987, and the 2nd <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> upheld the ruling last July. The appeals court relied on an agreement between the two banks that suggested <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION>'s home office in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> had the duty to pay the money. The cases are <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> vs. Trinh, 88-1031, and <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> Wells </PERSON> <PERSON> Fargo </PERSON>, 88-1260.
