<HEAD>Court to Rule on Washington Lawyer Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed to study a `` strike'' by lawyers in the nation's capital who sought higher pay to represent penniless criminal defendants. The court said it will hear an appeal by federal officials who say the lawyers violated antitrust law. The <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lawyers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> here organized a boycott in 1983 to pressure the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> government to increase hourly compensation the city pays attorneys who represent indigent criminal defendants. Some 100 lawyers who represent most of the city's poor criminal defendants had been receiving $ 30 an hour for time in court and $ 20 an hour for out-of-court work. They won a $ 25 per hour increase after a two-week boycott in which nearly all them refused to accept new cases. The boycott created a crisis for the city, swamping the the city public defender's office with criminal cases. The city government agreed to the higher hourly rate at an annual cost to taxpayers of more than $ 4 million. The private lawyers who boycotted represent 85 percent of the poor defendants. The remaining defendants are represented by the public defender service, third-year law students or, in a small number of cases, lawyers volunteering to work without pay. After the so-called strike, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> ruled that the lawyers engaged in price-fixing and an illegal boycott. The <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> ordered the lawyers not to engage in similar conduct in the future. The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> here set aside the <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> decision and ordered the agency to restudy the case to determine whether the lawyers had exerted `` market power'' in their boycott. Alleged antitrust violators are considered to be exerting market power if they are capable of exercising economic control over a relevant market. The appeals court here said it was unclear whether the boycott succeeded because the lawyers exercised market power or political clout. `` Power of some sort was surely exercised,'' the appeals court said. `` The city council approved a rate increase it had long refused two weeks into a boycott that disrupted the court system and generated significant publicity.'' The appeals court said the lawyers may have succeeded, even though they lacked market power, by changing public attitudes and making it politically safe for the city council to raise their pay. The boycott may have succeeded because it was persuasive rather than coercive, the appeals court added. Also, the appeals court said, the <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> must judge the lawyers `` with a special solicitude'' because free-expression rights protected by the Constitution are involved. The lawyers said the boycott was an exercise of their First Amendment rights to petition the government for a redress of grievances. In appealing to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> said the appeals court ruling sets a dangerous precedent. The ruling `` erects formidable new barriers against antitrust challenges to publicly conducted price-fixing boycotts,'' the <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> said. `` The tax-paying public, no less than private parties, is entitled to have its monies spent in markets in which all participants obey the laws of competition.'' The cases are <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lawyers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, 88-1198, and <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lawyers </ORGANIZATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION>, 88-1393.
</TEXT>
