<SECOND>PM-Scotus-National Guard,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Upholds Federal National Guard Training in Massachusetts
Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today refused to bar the federal government from requiring certain peacetime training for any state's <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> troops without first getting the governor's consent. The justices, without comment, left intact a 1986 federal law prohibiting governors from withholding permission for such training missions. The law had been challenged by <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> officials. Today's action does not preclude the possibility that the issue could some day return to the nation's highest court. Since 1933, each person joining the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> simultaneously enlists in two distinct organizations _ the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> or <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> of a particular state and the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> or <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The first organization serves as the state's militia; the second as a reserve component of the national armed forces. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1986 passed the so-called Montgomery Amendment after several governors voiced opposition to the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's Central American policy and said they would withhold their consent to <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> training missions in that region The 1986 law prohibits any governor from withholding consent to a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> unit's active duty outside the country because of an objection to the location, purpose or schedule of such duty. A <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> unit in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> was designated to participate in a <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> training mission in mid-1988, but Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> objected. State officials sued the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> in federal court, alleging that the 1986 law is unconstitutional. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Keeton </PERSON> upheld the law, and the 1st U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> agreed last Oct. 25. The dispute centered on seemingly competing provisions in the Constitution. One enpowers <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> `` to raise and support armies,'' including `` calling forth the miltia.'' The other leaves to individual states the `` training of the militia.'' Judge <PERSON> Keeton </PERSON> ruled that a state's authority to train <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> members must yield to `` the legitimately exercised power of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to raise and support armies.'' <PERSON> Keeton </PERSON>'s ruling relied, in part, on a 1918 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision that upheld <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' authority to draft members of a state militia into the national armed forces during World War I. The judge discounted arguments by <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> authorities that a state's authority to supervise the training of <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> members is absolute during peacetime, and can be taken over by the federal government only in times of national emergency. A three-judge panel of the 8th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> declared the Montgomery Amendment unconstitutional after the law was challenged by <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Rudy </PERSON> <PERSON> Perpich </PERSON>. That ruling currently is under review by the entire 8th Circuit court. Urging the justices to reject <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>' appeal, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration lawyers said, `` It would be incongruous to hold that the Constitution gives <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> the power to establish these reserves as components of the national armed forces but ... withholds -LRB- federal -RRB- authority ... to conduct their training.'' The administration lawyers added, `` Such a view would not only undercut the effectiveness of the national defense but would also inject the states into matters of foreign policy that the Constitution reserves to the federal government.'' As of 1986, <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> members provided 46 percent of the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s combat units and 28 percent of its support forces. For fiscal year 1987, the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> members provided 73 percent of the nation's air defense interceptor forces and 25 percent of its tactical fighter forces. The case is <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION>, 88-1223.
