<HEAD>Supreme Court Rejects Challenge to California English-Only Rule</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today ordered the dismissal of a challenge to a rule that generally requires <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> city court employees to speak only English while at work. The justices instructed the 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> to take such action after being told that the woman who challenged the rule no longer works for the city court. The rule was adopted by the southeast judicial district of the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Municipal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1984. The rule bars court employees from speaking any language other than English, except when acting as translators or during breaks and lunchtime. The regulation was challenged by <PERSON> Alva </PERSON> <PERSON> Gutierrez </PERSON>, a Hispanic-American who was a deputy court clerk. Ms. <PERSON> Gutierrez </PERSON> is bilingual, and one of her duties was to translate for Spanish-speaking members of the public that have business before the city court. She said the English-only rule discriminates against her and other minority group members based on their race and national origin. The 9th Circuit court last year upheld a federal judge's injunction barring enforcement of the rule pending further developments in Ms. <PERSON> Guitierrez </PERSON>' suit The appeals court also rejected arguments that the city judges who adopted the rule are immune from being sued. The appeals court said while some employees who speak only English may feel threatened by conversations in Spanish between other workers, that is no legitimate basis for a discriminatory policy. `` Existing racial fears or prejudices and their effects can not justify a racial classification,'' the appeals court said. The fears of people who do not understand Spanish do not amount to a `` business necessity'' warranting the ban, the appeals court said. It noted that the federal <ORGANIZATION> Equal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opportunity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> properly has warned that barring workers from speaking their native tongue on the job may contribute to racial tension. Acknowledging that the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Constitution has been amended to recognize English as the state's official language, the appeals court said the amendment is primarily symbolic and does not mandate that English be the only language spoken by public employees. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Municipal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> Gutierrez </PERSON>, 88-1395.
