<HEAD>Jailhouse Lawyer Who Transformed Prison Set Free</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A jailhouse lawyer whose litigation helped transform the <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> State </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penitentiary </LOCATION> is free after 21 years behind bars. <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> `` Bud'' <PERSON> Balla </PERSON> was released from the prison south of <LOCATION> Boise </LOCATION> on Friday. He was not scheduled for release until August, but Corrections Director <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> said <PERSON> Balla </PERSON> had found a job and a place to live, so officials let him go. In 1984, <PERSON> Balla </PERSON>, who had only a high school education, and fellow inmate <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwartzmiller </PERSON> won a federal court victory declaring the 680-inmate prison overcrowded and lacking in basic services. The suit brought about improvements at the prison and construction of a new maximum-security facility. <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> lawyer <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Pevar </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> called the court-mandated reforms `` the single most important thing that has happened'' to <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> prisons. Corrections officials reluctantly agree, although they dismiss most of <PERSON> Balla </PERSON>'s prison-rights suits as frivolous. `` Every state has their <LOCATION> Balla </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> said. `` He just happened to be <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>'s.'' <PERSON> Balla </PERSON>, 44, was sent to the penitentiary in 1968 for robbery. He escaped and was recaptured three times and was serving time for slashing a guard's throat during a breakout in 1978. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Kodiak </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, contractor who knew <PERSON> Balla </PERSON> when they were teen-agers in <LOCATION> Medford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, told officials that the inmate would have a job and a place to live if he came to <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Balla </PERSON> was granted early release. <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> said he had forgotten <PERSON> Balla </PERSON> until a few months ago when he read about an inmate complaining about the prison cable TV system failing during the Super Bowl. `` He's got capabilities,'' <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> said. `` It's too bad he's spent so much of his life wasting away in prison.'' Between connecting flights in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Balla </PERSON> called The <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Statesman </LOCATION> to say, `` I'm free and I do n't know how to act.'' `` I've got an opportunity and I'm going to make it work,'' he said.
