up 8th graf pvs ``The envoy's wife...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fires burned out of control in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s devastated streets today after artillery and rocket exchanges between Christian and Moslem fighters killed 41 people in less than 48 hours Police said 156 people were wounded in the bombardments that began at dusk Saturday between army commander Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s largely Christian army units and his Syrian and Druse adversaries Police said the bombardment was the heaviest since the battles broke out March 8, plunging <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> into a fierce round of fighting some fear may be the `` final battle'' in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s 14-year-old civil war. <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s foreign minister, <PERSON> Sheik </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabah </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Ahmed </PERSON> <PERSON> Al-Sabah </PERSON>, called for an emergency meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> council to take `` urgent measures ... to stop the massacre in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>.'' The sheik, who heads an <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> mediation committee on <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, called the meeting after three cease-fire appeals by his six-man panel failed to curb the hostilities. The latest casualties raised the overall toll from 41 days of almost non-stop bombardment by both sides to 258 killed and 913 wounded, by police count. <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> was without electricity and the water-pumping system came to a standstill after the capital's main power plants were shut down at noon Sunday when they ran out of fuel. Among those killed during the weekend was <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s ambassador, <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Aristegui </PERSON>. The 61-year-old diplomat died Sunday along with his wife's Lebanese father and sister and a bodyguard when his villa suffered a direct hit. The envoy's wife, <PERSON> Jomana </PERSON>, suffered severe head wounds when the 240mm shell struck their home in the <PERSON> Hadath </PERSON> suburb of Christian east <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. She was hospitalized in critical condition. <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> residents had hardly emerged from basements and bunkers during a brief lull this morning when the guns and rocket launchers thundered into action again, sending people scurrying back to their shelters. A few bakeries opened today, but there was not enough bread for residents who ventured out to replenish food supplies. Hundreds of burned-out cars lay smoldering on streets littered with broken glass and severed power cables. Hundreds of shops and other buildings were gutted. Fires burned out of control in several residential districts of <LOCATION> Christian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> east </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, where police said more than 1,200 autos were destroyed by shellfire in the latest blitz. Many buildings burned down because fire engines had no water to battle the fires. The nine-story <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> building, which also houses the state-run Radio <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> station, was gutted by a barrage of 30 artillery shells. The station remained off the air for a second day. The smoke-blackened building is next door to the office of acting Prime Minister <PERSON> Salim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON>, who heads a mostly Moslem Cabinet that is vying for legitimacy with a <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> military <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> headed by <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>. <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON> met today with <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s visiting Minister for Humanitarian Assistance, <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kouchner </PERSON>, who is trying to arrange a mercy mission to evacuate casualties and bring in fuel and medical supplies. A source close to <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON>, sp