<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> biologist took over today as general-secretary of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> for the Exploration of the Sea, becoming the first American to head the world's oldest intergovernmental organization. <PERSON> Emory </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kenmare </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.D. </LOCATION>, was elected to head the 18-nation organization for a six-year term. He previously was the council's fisheries officer and statistician. The council was set up in 1902 to carry out marine and fishery science, and advise European nations on fish stocks, quotas and marine pollution. `` We try to keep out of politics and fisheries management,'' <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said. `` But we're sometimes the source of controversy.'' He said the council's greatest challenge was `` making people recognize their responsibility for common resources.'' Prior to the mid-1970s, when countries extended their national jurisdictions to 200 miles, there was virtual anarchy among fishing nations, <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said. Nothing changed until fish stocks were decimated, he said. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>, where cod and haddock are severely depleted, was the most over-fished ocean in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. He said fishing in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> waters should be cut by 80 percent to replenish stocks to a sufficient level. Council members are <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>,