<HEAD>S&amp;Ls, Wright, Base Closings at Top of Congressional Agenda</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Subs grafs 4-6, The House ethics, with two grafs on release
of report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s slightly altered plan to protect deposits in failed savings and loans will consume the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s attention this week, while Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s troubles and the recommended closing of 86 military bases dominate House action. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s plan would cost a minimum of $ 157 billion, two-thirds of it from taxpayers, over the next 10 years to shore up the government's deposit insurance funds after raids on it by often-fraudulent savings and loan operators. The S & amp; L insurance fund is at least $ 25 billion in the hole because of overly speculative loans, insider deals and in some cases outright thievery by thrift operators using federally protected deposits. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> ethics committee charged today that <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> violated official rules of conduct 69 times by not disclosing thousands of dollars in alleged gifts and by skirting rules on speaking fees through bulk book sales. The committee also cleared <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> of several allegations, including one that he improperly intervened with <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L regulators on behalf of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> thrift operators and friends. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> also is scheduled to vote Tuesday on a resolution by <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> lawmakers to reject a federal commission's recommendation last year to close 86 military bases. Among the base closings that would begin in 1990 unless the resolution is approved are the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dix </LOCATION> and Presidio bases in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Chanute </LOCATION> training base in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. Lawmakers hope to make this a shortened work week, taking off on Thursday to mark Passover. But with the S & amp; L deficit growing by an estimated $ 600 million to $ 1 billion a month, <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Maine </LOCATION>, has vowed to bring them back on Friday if they do not complete action on <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s package before the holiday. Lawmakers and presidential candidates in both parties closed their eyes to the problem during last year's election campaign while the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> was committing some $ 38 billion to close or merge more than 200 insolvent S & amp; Ls, half of them in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. The bailout package before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> would come up with the balance needed to pay for that, $ 50 billion more needed to handle another 350 institutions now or near insolvency plus another $ 33 billion to cover losses of additional thrifts expected to go under by 1999. Together, the costs _ none of which will ever be recovered _ are more than double the amount of aid, repaid loans and loan guarantees that the government put up for the <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> Plan to rebuild <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> after World War II and the <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Penn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> bailouts combined. Toward <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s stated goal of `` never again,'' the president's plan