<HEAD>Court to Decide Whether U.S. Officials Need Warrant for Foreign Searches</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 6th graf pvs with 5 grafs new material to insert other
actions, picks up 7th graf pvs: Verdugo was xxx</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, in a case involving a notorious Mexican drug-smuggling operation, today agreed to decide whether <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> law enforcement agents need a warrant before searching on foreign soil someone who is not an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> citizen. The court said it will hear <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration arguments that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agents did not violate the Constitution when, without a warrant, they searched the home of a suspected Mexican drug smuggler. <PERSON> Rene </PERSON> <PERSON> Verdugo </PERSON> <PERSON> Urquidez </PERSON> was convicted in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> last year of taking part in the 1985 kidnapping, torture and murder of Drug Enforcement Administration Agent <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> and his pilot, <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Zavala </PERSON> <PERSON> Avelar </PERSON>. <PERSON> Verdugo </PERSON>, identified as a top lieutenant to Mexican drug kingpin <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Caro </PERSON> <PERSON> Quintero </PERSON>, is serving a sentence of 240 years plus life. He is not eligible for parole for 59 years, when he would be 96. <PERSON> Verdugo </PERSON>'s conviction and sentence in the murders is not at issue in the case the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> acted on today. His appeal centered on a separate drug-smuggling conviction. In other cases acted on the court: _ Agreed to decide whether states may tax television evangelists' sales of religious books, tapes and other The justices said they will review rulings that forced the Louisiana-based <ORGANIZATION> Jimmy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Swaggart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministries </ORGANIZATION> to pay <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> $ 183,000 in back taxes and interest for the years 1974 through 1981. - Refused to bar the federal government from requiring certain peacetime training for any state's <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> troops without first getting the governor's consent The justices left intact a 1986 federal law prohibiting governors from withholding permission for such training missions. The law had been challenged by <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> officials. - Asked the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration for its view on whether <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks with branch offices overseas must pay depositors after foreign governments seize or freeze those accounts The court invited <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyers to comment on rulings that required <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> to pay depositors. At issue in the Verdugo case is whether the 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> properly suppressed evidence obtained by the <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> in its search of <LOCATION> Verdugo </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Mexicali </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, home in 1988. <PERSON> Verdugo </PERSON> was arrested by Mexican police in 1986 and was turned over to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> authorities in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. While he was awaiting trial, the <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> got permission from <LOCATION> Mexican </LOCATION> authorities to search the home. The agents seized a tally sheet they said shows the quantities of marijuana smuggled into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> by <LOCATION> Verdugo </LOCATION>. A federal judge in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> ruled that the evidence is inadmissible because the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agents failed to obtain a warrant in a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> court. The judge also said the search was unreasonable because it was too general, occurred after midnight and the <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> failed to leave an inventory in <LOCATION> Verdugo </LOCATION>'s home of the evidence seized. The 9th Circuit court upheld the judge's ruling. The appeals court said the agents had a legitimate goal and praised them for `` aggressive and laudable pursuit'' of drug smugglers. But the appeals court said the agents are not free to ignore the Constitution's Fourth Amendment, which generally requires a court warrant before any government search of a home is conducted. While <PERSON> Verdugo </PERSON> is a foreign citizen who lived outside the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` he is being prosecuted for alleged violations of <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> law in a <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> court,'' the appeals court said. `` We can discern no conceivable reason why he should be denied the protection of the Fourth Amendment.'' The appeals court acknowledged that a search warrant issued by a judge in this country has no legal authority in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. Nonetheless, the appeals court said, `` We can not relieve the government from its obligation to obtain a search warrant simply because the place to be searched ... is outside this country.'' A search warrant issued by a judge in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> demonstrates that an impartial magistrate believed there was probable cause to conduct the search, the appeals court said. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyers said the <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> agents received assurances from <LOCATION> Mexican </LOCATION> government officials that the search was lawful there without a warrant. The government's appeal said the 9th Circuit court ruling could have serious consequences for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> law enforcement efforts on foreign soil. The <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> has offices in 45 nations, and last year helped in investigations that led to 1,200 arrests of suspected drug smugglers in foreign countries. The case is <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> vs. Verdugo-Urquidez, 88-1353.
