<HEAD>President-Elect Says Democracy Is Inevitable</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LJUBLJANA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President-elect <PERSON> Janez </PERSON> <PERSON> Drnovsek </PERSON> said today the spread of democracy in this communist nation can not be stopped and suggested the country could join a west European trade organization within five years. <PERSON> Drnovsek </PERSON>, a 38-year-old economist elected in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s first Western-style election, said a suggestion <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> join the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> was `` not realistic'' now. The call came from the official <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> youth union last week. But he said he could envisage membership in the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, whose members are <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> could adapt its terms of trade to those of the six-nation grouping over a five-year period, said <PERSON> Drnovsek </PERSON>. In a 90-minute meeting with reporters, <PERSON> Drnovsek </PERSON> took a largely conciliatory but anti-Serbian stance when answering questions about how to solve ethnic tensions and an economic and political crisis. <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>, under its communist leader <PERSON> Slobodan </PERSON> <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON>, wants to maintain a centralized, one-party system, measures it says will bring down the 400 percent inflation and a $ 21 billion foreign debt. In contrast, <PERSON> Drnovsek </PERSON> stressed that `` the concentration of economic power ... should not be confused with political centralization.'' He also spoke out against `` nationalist tendenices'' complicating the situation in the <LOCATION> Serbian </LOCATION> province of <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>, where riots killed at least 24 people last month. <PERSON> Drnovsek </PERSON> said his direct election as <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION>'s representative to the nine-member collective presidency shows democratization `` has begun and will not stop.'' The spread of democracy `` may stop for a short while in one place or another ... but it can not be halted altogether,'' he emphasized. `` I am convinced that very soon we will arrive at a more liberal development in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>. Anything else is unacceptable and could have tragic consequences.'' <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> hopes new liberal laws will encourage foreign investment, but <PERSON> Drnovsek </PERSON> said the country will continue trying to reschedule or write off debt repayments. He blamed the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> budget deficit for high interest rates that he said complicate repayments. <PERSON> Drnovsek </PERSON> and the new representative from <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s smallest republic, <LOCATION> Montenegro </LOCATION>, were the only people directly elected to the collective presidency in Western-style elections. In <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Croatia </LOCATION>, representatives were named by the party and approved in rubber-stamp legislatures. The country's other two republics, <LOCATION> Bosnia-Herzegovina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Macedonia </LOCATION>, still are considering how to elect their representatives, who sit for five years. <PERSON> Drnovsek </PERSON> will serve one year as president.
