<HEAD>Supreme Court Bars New York Man from Pauper Appeals in Ohio Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For only the second time in its history, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today permanently barred someone from appealing to it as a pauper after ruling that he failed to prove he can not afford the filing fees. The justices, by a 6-3 vote, ruled that <PERSON> Curtis </PERSON> <PERSON> Wrenn </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Drum </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, may never again submit a so-called pauper's petition _ unless he can show his financial circumstances have changed significantly for the worse. Unless granted pauper status, anyone who appeals to the high court must pay $ 200 in filing fees plus significant printing costs. The court, in a four-page, unsigned opinion, noted that <PERSON> Wrenn </PERSON> has filed 22 appeals to the court since 1986 and the court has denied him pauper's status 19 times. One one occasion, <PERSON> Wrenn </PERSON> paid the $ 200 fee. <PERSON> Wrenn </PERSON>, who is black and works in the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Wilcox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clinic </ORGANIZATION>, said he was a victim of racial discrimination by the <LOCATION> Toledo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Mental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Wrenn </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> officials first refused to hire him as an assistant programs superintendent in 1978. Later, he was hired but said he then was fired in 1980 because of racial bias. In legal papers accompanying his appeal to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Wrenn </PERSON> said his yearly salary is $ 27,700 and he is $ 60,000 in debt. The court once before issued a similar previous opinion, on Feb. 21 denying pauper status to a man who had appealed to the justices 73 times since 1971. The justices said today they have a responsibility to allocate the court's limited resources in the interest of justice for all. `` We do not think justice is served if the court continues to process -LRB- <PERSON> Wrenn </PERSON>'s -RRB- requests to proceed -LRB- as a pauper -RRB- when his financial condition has not changed from that reflected in a previous filing,'' the court said. In a dissenting opinion, Justice <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> said the court was wasting more time by preparing and enforcing the order resticting <PERSON> Wrenn </PERSON>'s ability to appeal than would be `` consumed by the routine denial of frivolous'' appeals. Also dissenting were Justices <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>. They repeated past concerns that denying pauper status could be a dangerous precedent that cuts off worthy appeals. The court receives some 2,300 appeals a year by people who say they are too poor to afford the filing fees. The cases are <PERSON> Wrenn </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Benson </PERSON>, 88-6494, and <PERSON> Wrenn </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>, 88-6497.
