 Text of Monday's decision from the provincial court panel legalizing the Solidarity trade union, as translated by The Associated Press: On April 17, 1989, the <ORGANIZATION> Eighth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> panel composed of provincial court Judge <PERSON> Danuta </PERSON> <PERSON> Widawska </PERSON>, provincial court Judge <PERSON> Anna </PERSON> <PERSON> Borowska </PERSON>, provincial court Judge <PERSON> Jadwiga </PERSON> <PERSON> Siwek </PERSON> and protocol clerk <PERSON> Irmina </PERSON> <PERSON> Fila </PERSON>, after the recognition on April 17, 1989 in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> of a motion of the registering committee of the Independent, <ORGANIZATION> Self-Governed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Solidarity </ORGANIZATION> to enter it into the register of trade unions, decides: To enter into the register of trade unions, in part B, the Independent, <ORGANIZATION> Self-Governed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Solidarity </ORGANIZATION>, with its headquarters in <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION>, uniting workers employed on the basis of contract -LRB- at state enterprises -RRB- or contract with cooperatives, employed on the basis of membership or nomination at rural cooperatives, as well as students of factories' vocational schools working for the factories or being taught a profession, those in cottage industries, people working on basis of an agency contract, old age pensioners and invalids, functioning on the territory of the Polish People's Republic on the basis of the -LRB- union's -RRB- statute together with the annex adopted on April 8, 1989, and being its integral part.
