<HEAD>Radio Bomb Kills One, Injures Another at Police Headquarters</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs with death of one officer. Picks up 3rd graf
pvs ``Brunhilde Spies-Mohr...'' SUBS 6th graf pvs ``The blast occurred...''
to conform.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WIESBADEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A radio bomb confiscated from suspected <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> terrorists exploded at federal police headquarters today as experts tried to defuse it, killing one officer and critically injuring another. A similar bomb disguised as a radio is believed to have caused the explosion that blew <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103 out of the sky Dec. 21 over <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, killing 270 people. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> initially reported two officers were critically injured in today's explosion. Bundeskriminalamt spokesman <PERSON> Arno </PERSON> <PERSON> Falk </PERSON> said later that one of policemen had died. <PERSON> Brunhilde </PERSON> <PERSON> Spies-Mohr </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the federal police bureau or Bundeskriminalamt, said in <LOCATION> Wiesbaden </LOCATION>: `` During investigation of a suspicious device suspected of containing explosives, a detonation occurred. `` The material that exploded was a device obtained during investigation of Palestinian terrorists.'' The explosives were hidden in a radio receiver, she added. The blast occurred in a basement room of the federal police headquarters, Ms. <PERSON> Spies-Mohr </PERSON> said. Part of the Bundeskriminalamt building was evacuated after the explosion while bomb disposal experts disarmed a second device, she said. An identical radio-bomb containing plastic explosives and an air pressure-sensitive detonator was seized during an Oct. 26 raid on an apartment used by suspected Paletinian terrorists in the city of <LOCATION> Neuss </LOCATION>. It was not immediately clear where the bomb that exploded in the federal police headquarters came from. One unofficial source who did not want to be identified said it was the same bomb confiscated in the <LOCATION> Neuss </LOCATION> raid. But that device has been handled repeatedly by West German and foreign investigators in their probe of the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> crash, and was presumed disarmed long ago.
