<HEAD>Despite Fame &amp; Victories, Walesa Remains a Modest Person</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> still gives the impression that he could be spending his days repairing electric carts at the <ORGANIZATION> Lenin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipyard </ORGANIZATION>. Instead, he is usually to be found negotiating with the interior minister, meeting with foreign heads of state and leading the Solidarity movement that has changed his country's course. The story of <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> scaling the shipyard fence to inspire strikers in forming the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc's first independent trade union is often repeated, but should not lose its significance: <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> has not been the same since that day in August 1980. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, 45, has never lost the authenticity with which he drew millions to his vision of workers' solidarity. On Monday, he chalked up his latest victory, leading Solidarity through seven years of repressions to regain its legal status, just as he vowed to do. The winner of the Nobel Peace Prize, a man of deep Roman Catholic faith, intended to travel to <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> on Wednesday to thank Polish-born Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> II for the church's role in helping to bring about the agreement with authorities. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> wears a suit and tie these days, but always with a picture of the <PERSON> Black </PERSON> <PERSON> Madonna </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Czestochowa </LOCATION> icon and a Solidarity pin on his lapel. He usually also sports a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> vice-presidential tie pin given him by <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in 1987. But he remains a modest person, often answering his home telephone himself and riding the early morning train from <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION> on his frequent trips to <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> for high-level meetings with Polish authorities. When in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>, he stays in a small cloister cell at the church episcopate. After a long night of negotiations, he sometimes travels the four hours back to <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION> to sleep in his own bed. Complaining of a bad cold, he decided to stay in <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION> on Monday when a court in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> formally registered Solidarity again as a legal trade union independent of the government. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>'s autocratic leadership style bothers some in the union. And although he is a spell-binding orator, his statements to reporters can sometimes be as cryptic as an oracle's pronouncements. A natural politician who goes with his gut, <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> ignored warnings that he was giving in too easily in September when he put his reputation with workers on the line by ending a series of strikes nationwide in return for a vague promise of talks from the government. Although some youthful militants chanted `` Down with <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>!'' in the months that followed, he never seemed to doubt the decision. Many Solidarity activists point to <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>'s convincing showing in a nationwide TV debate in October as the turning point that brought about the talks which won Solidarity its legalization. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> apologized for his poor performance. Much has changed in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> during the eight months since the August strikes, but not <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>. He marked his conclusion of an historic accord with the government on April 5 not at the celebratory cocktail party at a government palace, but by eating dinner in a nearly deserted hotel dining room with an aide. `` I am exhausted and I do n't like eating standing,'' he said.
