<HEAD>Key Dates in Solidarity History</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Key events in the history of Solidarity:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1980</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Aug. 14 _ Electrician <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> leads occupation strike at <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Lenin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipyard </ORGANIZATION> and starts worker revolt against communist state. Aug. 31 _ Authorities agree to make Solidarity the Soviet bloc's only legal independent union During its 16 months of legal activity, Solidarity membership grows to an estimated 10 million and a sense of renewal sweeps the nation.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1981</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Dec. 13 _ With a general strike threatened, Gen. <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> declares martial law, suppressing Solidarity activities and interning thousands of members, including <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1982</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Oct. 8 _ Solidarity is banned and an official trade union alliance created to take its place. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> expands economic sanctions against <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. Nov. 11 _ <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> freed.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1983</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 July 22 _ <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> lifts martial law but leaves many restrictive edicts. Oct. 5 _ <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> wins Nobel Peace Prize.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1984</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 July 21 _ Amnesty is approved for political prisoners, including 11 prominent Solidarity leaders jailed after martial law. Oct. 19 _ Popular pro-Solidarity priest, the Rev. <PERSON> Jerzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Popieluszko </PERSON>, is slain. Four state security police will be tried and convicted.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1985</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Aug. 31 _ <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> accuses government of presiding over a political, economic and cultural disaster as supporters nationwide mark fifth anniversary of Solidarity's birth.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1986</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Sept. 11 _ The government releases 225 political prisoners, including all senior Solidarity leaders.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1987</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Feb. 19 _ Last of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sanctions against <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> lifted. Nov. 29 _ Poles vote in first referendum in 41 years, but deny government support for economic reform package.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1988</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 April 24-May 10 _ Strikes hit steel mills, shipyards and other plants across <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. Police break up one strike, others gradually die out. Aug. 16 _ Workers declare a strike at July Manifesto coal mine. Strikes spread, creating <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s worst labor strife in seven years. Aug. 26 _ Interior Minister Gen. <PERSON> Czeslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> proposes negotiations between the communist government and the Solidarity-led opposition. Aug. 31 _ <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> holds first meeting with government officials in six years and appeals to workers to end strikes. Sept. 3 _ Strikes end as <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> asks for time to talk with the government. Oct. 25 _ Talks postponed as government objects to opposition participants. Nov. 30 _ <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> and <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Miodowicz </PERSON>, head of the official union alliance, hold live television debate. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>'s convincing performance rekindles plans for talks.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1989</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Jan. 17 _ <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leadership decides Solidarity can be legalized under certain conditions, meeting Solidarity's prerequisite for talks Feb. 6 _ The `` round-table'' negotiations begin with the government seeking opposition participation in the communist-dominated political system in exchange for trade union freedoms. April 5 _ <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> conclude the historic deliberations by endorsing a new `` social contract'' for <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s future The political and economic reforms include a new senate, which will be the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc's first freely elected legislative body, and the post of president, the right to have more than one union at a workplace, opposition access to the printed and electronic media, and price-wage indexation. April 13 _ First elections to include opposition candidates are set for June 4. Monday _ Solidarity is formally registered again as a trade union operating independently of the Polish government.
</TEXT>
