<HEAD>Supreme Court Actions at a Glance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here, at a glance, is a rundown of Monday's major actions by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> DRUG SEARCH WARRANT The court, in a case involving a notorious Mexican drug-smuggling operation, agreed to decide whether <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> law enforcement agents need a warrant before searching on foreign soil someone who is not an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> citizen. The court said it will hear <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration arguments that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agents did not violate the Constitution when, without a warrant, they searched the home of a suspected Mexican drug smuggler. <PERSON> Rene </PERSON> <PERSON> Verdugo </PERSON> <PERSON> Urquidez </PERSON> was convicted in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> last year of taking part in the 1985 kidnapping, torture and murder of Drug Enforcement Administration Agent <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> and his pilot, <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Zavala </PERSON> <PERSON> Avelar </PERSON>. <PERSON> Verdugo </PERSON>'s conviction and sentence in the murders is not at issue in the case the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> acted on Monday. His appeal centered on a separate drug-smuggling conviction. The case is <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> vs. Verdugo-Urquidez, 88-1353. NATIONAL GUARD - GOVERNORS The court refused to bar the federal government from requiring certain peacetime training for any state's <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> troops without first getting the governor's consent. The justices, without comment, left intact a 1986 federal law prohibiting governors from withholding permission for such training missions. The law had been challenged by <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> officials. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1986 passed the so-called Montgomery Amendment after several governors voiced opposition to the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's Central American policy and said they would withhold their consent to <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> training missions in that region The case is <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION>, 88-1223. EVANGELISTS - TAXES The court agreed to decide whether states may tax television evangelists' sales of religious books, tapes and other merchandise. The justices said they will review rulings that forced the Louisiana-based <ORGANIZATION> Jimmy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Swaggart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministries </ORGANIZATION> to pay <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> $ 183,000 in back taxes and interest for the years 1974 through 1981. Lawyers for <PERSON> Swaggart </PERSON>'s organization argue that the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> tax, as applied, violates religious freedom. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Jimmy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Swaggart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> vs. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equalization </ORGANIZATION>, 88-1374. MURDER CONFESSION The court agreed to consider reinstating the murder conviction of a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> man who confessed to killing his former girlfriend after police illegally arrested him at his home. The court said it will review a ruling that threw out <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>' conviction because his confession was used as evidence against him. The ruling is being appealed by <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION> prosecutors. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> last October ruled that <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> is entitled to a new trial on charges stemming from the stabbing death of <PERSON> Thelma </PERSON> <PERSON> Staton </PERSON>. The case is <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> vs. <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, 88-1000. PAUPER APPEAL For only the second time in its history, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> permanently barred someone from appealing to it as a pauper after ruling that he failed to prove he can not afford the filing fees. The justices, by a 6-3 vote, ruled that <PERSON> Curtis </PERSON> <PERSON> Wrenn </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Drum </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, may never again submit a so-called pauper's petition _ unless he can show his financial circumstances have changed significantly for the worse. Unless granted pauper status, anyone who appeals to the high court must pay $ 200 in filing fees plus significant printing costs. The court, in a four-page, unsigned opinion, noted that <PERSON> Wrenn </PERSON> has filed 22 appeals to the court since 1986 and the court has denied him pauper's status 19 times. One one occasion, <PERSON> Wrenn </PERSON> paid the $ 200 fee. The cases are <PERSON> Wrenn </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Benson </PERSON>, 88-6494, and <PERSON> Wrenn </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>, 88-6497.
