<HEAD>Gatekeeper Says Police Overruled Him, Allowed Fans Into Stadium</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New grafs 12-23, beginning, ``Paul Middup...'' to UPDATE with
police defense, Hurd announcing inquiry, CORRECT one victim's age, royals
visiting, editing to tighten. Pickup 23rd graf pvs, ``South Yorkshire...''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
'
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By ROBERT BARR</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SHEFFIELD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A gatekeeper said today he refused police orders to open an outer gate and allow thousands of late arrivals to pour into a soccer stadium where 94 fans were crushed to death. Fans and officials said police opened the barrier. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yorkshire </LOCATION> police, who were in charge of Saturday's club semifinal at <LOCATION> Hillsborough </LOCATION> stadium, came under mounting attack as <ORGANIZATION> Liverpool </ORGANIZATION> ordered a week of mourning for victims who came to watch the city's team play play <ORGANIZATION> Nottingham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION>. Fans and officials said officers responded inadequately and far too slowly when spectators were crushed against a steel anti-riot fence in a standing-room-only area. <PERSON> Gatekeeper </PERSON> <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Stone </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Yorkshire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> he refused police orders to open a 16-foot-wide outer gate. Survivors said about 4,000 fans outside were pushing at turnstiles. Stone would not confirm survivors' reports that police officers opened the concertina gate. But he told the newspaper: `` You know as well as anyone whose fault it was.'' <ORGANIZATION> Liverpool </ORGANIZATION> fan <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitton </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> television: `` The steward put his hand on the gate and said, ` Do n't open it. The police said, ` Open the gate. There's going to be a crush.' Then two police officers opened the gate.'' New arrivals poured in, pressing those inside against the 10-foot fence. Mounted police herded them into the overcrowded center terrace, some fans said today. The crush was so great, <PERSON> Mitton </PERSON> said, that fans fell on the floor and people climbed over them. `` All the police were doing was standing up saying ` get back, get back.' There was already people dead then. I climbed on them to get over the fence.'' <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yorkshire </LOCATION>'s Chief Constable <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said Saturday a senior officer decided to open the gates `` to save people's lives and to relieve the crush outside.'' He said he was not aware of any connection between the gate being opened and the surge on the standing section, where many victims died. One of those being trapped in the front of the terrace, <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Hendry </PERSON>, 19, said: `` People were screaming at the police to open the gate -LRB- at the front of the terrace -RRB- and three fans managed to climb over the fence, but no sooner had they got out than one of them was thrown back over by a copper.'' <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Middup </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> representative, said today the growing public criticism of police actions was `` grossly unfair.'' `` They were faced with a situation for which no amount of training could prepare them,'' he said. In Parliament today, Home Secretary <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurd </PERSON> announced an independent inquiry to determine the cause of what Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> called `` a disaster of immense proportions.'' <PERSON> Hurd </PERSON> said major soccer clubs may be told to replace standing-room terraces with seats _ as lawmakers and sports officials are demanding. `` We owe a duty to these passionate supporters of football -LRB- soccer -RRB- to examine urgently and thoroughly the causes and background and to do all in our power to prevent such a thing happening again,'' <PERSON> Hurd </PERSON> said. `` We have to set our sights high and find a better way for British football.'' Lord Justice <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> will lead the inquiry starting Tuesday, he said. Police released the names of all 94 victims today, ranging from a 10-year-old boy who was trampled and the 67-year-old brother of a former <ORGANIZATION> Liverpool </ORGANIZATION> soccer player to two sisters who died before their father's eyes. Businessman <PERSON> Trevor </PERSON> <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON>, 43, tried to resuscitate his two daughters, <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON>, 19, and <LOCATION> Victoria </LOCATION>, 15, after they were pulled from the crush of bodies. `` Football was the one thing we did as a family and now we are not a family anymore,'' he said. All the victims were British. Thirty-four were teen-agers and 33 were in their 20s. Seven were women. Of the 170 injured, 47 remained hospitalized today, including 17 in intensive care. <ORGANIZATION> Liverpool </ORGANIZATION> soccer team members visited some of the injured fans, as did <PERSON> Prince </PERSON> <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> and his wife, Princess <PERSON> Diana </PERSON>. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yorkshire </LOCATION> police, whose crowd-control measures will be at the core of the inquiry, handed over the police investigation to neighboring <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Midlands </LOCATION> police. Authorities will want to determine why thousands of fans still were outside as the match began and examine charges that many entered the sold-out stadium, which has a capacity of 54,000, with forged tickets or no tickets at all. Sir <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Livermore </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Liverpool </ORGANIZATION> lawyer and former Lord Mayor of <LOCATION> Liverpool </LOCATION>, released a statement from a policeman whom he refused to identify calling the police operation disorganized, `` pathetic'' and `` amateurish.'' The <LOCATION> Liverpool </LOCATION> city council today called an official week of mourning and discussed ways of helping the bereaved and injured. It was the third major soccer tragedy in four years involving English teams, which have been barred from <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> soccer competition since a May 29, 1985, rampage by <ORGANIZATION> Liverpool </ORGANIZATION> fans at <LOCATION> Heysel </LOCATION> stadium in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> that killed 39 people. <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s soccer authority last week lifted the ban on English clubs playing in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> in the 1990-91 season, pending a review next April.
