<HEAD>Amnesty Report Revives Questions About Gibraltar Killings</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release 8:01 p.m. EDT _ Time Set By Source</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The inquest jury that exonerated British soldiers in the killing of three alleged Irish terrorists in <LOCATION> Gibraltar </LOCATION> was acting on incomplete evidence and sometimes conflicting testimony, <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> says. In a report published Tuesday that is likely to refuel the controversy over the killings on March 6, 1988, the human rights movement renewed its demand for a judicial inquiry, saying the inquest failed to allay suspicions of `` an official policy of deliberate planned killings of suspected members of armed opposition groups.'' It said the inquest was conducted properly, but believed that the verdict, although reached fairly, was based on `` evidence which from the outset was incomplete.'' Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s office said it had seen the report. `` As far as we are concerned the whole matter has been fully considered -LRB- by the inquest -RRB- and we see no grounds for opening up a fresh inquiry,'' said a spokesman, requesting anonymity. The government has faced persistent questions over the killing of <PERSON> Mairead </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrell </PERSON>, <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> McCann </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sean </PERSON> <PERSON> Savage </PERSON> by a secrecy-shrouded military unit believed to have been flown in from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. The government said it acted on intelligence the three were armed and plotting to detonate a car bomb in the tourist-packed center of the British colony on the southern Spanish coast. The Irish <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> acknowledged the three were members sent to <LOCATION> Gibraltar </LOCATION> `` on active service.'' But it quickly emerged the three were unarmed and that their car contained no bomb, and witnesses later said at least two of the suspects appeared to be trying to surrender to the plainclothes officers confronting them. The government said it feared they might have remote-control devices to detonate the explosives if they were given too much time to surrender. Angrily rejecting <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>'s call for an inquiry, Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> said an inquest would answer the questions. Seven months later, the inquest jury ruled 9-2 that the killings were lawful. <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> sent three observers to the inquest, led by <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Owen </PERSON>, a lawyer and ombudsman of the <LOCATION> Canadian </LOCATION> province of <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>. Its report comes two weeks after a British trial lawyer, <PERSON> Hilary </PERSON> <PERSON> Kitchin </PERSON>, who also observed the inquest, wrote that it fell short of international legal standards and raised questions about the legality of the killings. <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>'s report said: `` Details about government policy, the planning of the operation, and the quality of the intelligence were not revealed.'' It said <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> police, who had been involved in tracking the three to the <LOCATION> Gibraltar </LOCATION> border, did not testify. Spanish testimony could have helped establish whether they were known to be without guns or explosives. The absence of this testimony also made the evidence incomplete, the report said. It said much forensic evidence was destroyed `` because standard procedures were not followed,'' while the state pathologist was denied adequate post-mortem facilities and ballistics reports. `` Most of the key independent civilian eye witnesses were discovered by media journalists and not by the police,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>. `` The organization is also concerned that discrepancies between witnesses' testimonies had not been resolved and that many questions remained unanswered such as, for example, from what exact position the soldiers had fired, and whether the suspects had made attempts to surrender,'' the report said. Recalling past shootings in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> in which police were accused of killing when they could have made arrests, it said: `` The inquest has again failed to alleviate public concern that these suspects were killed rather than arrested.'' In an interview, <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> faced the challenge of `` keeping its composure in the face of sometimes intolerable violence.'' He said he was not accusing the British of stepping beyond the law. `` I'm saying doubt remains that has to be resolved ... and doubt is potentially very damaging to a representative democracy.'' The <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> is fighting to rid <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> of British rule and unite it with the <LOCATION> Irish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>.
