<FIRST>r w AM-FDA-ColdDrug     04-17 0600</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FDA-Cold Drug,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Says Drug Linked to Sudden Death Syndrome Shouldn't be Sold
without Prescription</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A drug commonly prescribed for sedation and relief of cold symptoms is linked to sudden infant death syndrome and should not be sold without a prescription, a public interest research group said Monday. <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> urged the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> to reverse its decision allowing over-the-counter sales of the drug known by the trade name Phenergan. `` Over-the-counter availability implies <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> designation of a margin of safety which, in this case, is not justified,'' said <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sidney </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON>, physicians with the health research group, in a letter to the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>. The group filed a petition with the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> four months ago to block over-the-counter sales of the drug, but no action has been taken. The group said the matter now deserves `` urgent attention'' because nonprescription doses of the drug are scheduled to reach pharmacy shelves in June. <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Cruzan </PERSON> said the group's petition is under review. The agency has 180 days to review such petitions, she said. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> last August decided that promethazine hydrochloride, the active ingredient in Phenergan, could be used in over-the-counter cough-cold products `` based on the fact there has n't been a safety problem to justify keeping it under prescription when used as labeled and it is labeled not for use in children under 6,'' <PERSON> Cruzan </PERSON> said. The drug is a phenothiazine, a class of major tranquilizers, with antihistamine properties that offer some relief from cold symptoms by drying the upper airways. It is manufactured by <ORGANIZATION> Wyeth-Ayerst </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION>. Company spokeswoman <PERSON> Audrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashby </PERSON> said `` the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> carefully reviewed all data'' before making its decision and `` was satisfied the products are suitable for over-the-counter sales.'' She added that `` in their 35 years of marketing, these syrups have been remarkably problem-free.'' But the health group noted that although Phenergan is not recommended for children under 2 years old, doctors wrote 175,000 prescriptions for the drug for that age group in 1985. It is often prescribed for children with colic, <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> said. A study in <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, where the drug is available without a prescription, linked use with sudden infant death syndrome, or SIDS, and found that it can cause obstruction of infants' breathing passages during sleep, the health group said. The study found that children who died of SIDS were 10 times more likely to have been given Phenergan or a related drug recently than children in a control group. About 5,000 infants die of SIDS each year in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Its cause is unknown, but Phenergan is believed to be a contributing factor, the research group said. `` Even if only a small percentage of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> SIDS deaths are caused by prescription Phenergan, the increase in such deaths expected with OTC -LRB- over-the-counter -RRB- availability adds up to a senseless and avoidable tragedy,'' the letter said. Dr. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Naeye </PERSON>, chairman of the pathology department at the <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>, has done extensive research on SIDS and is one of the six experts who wrote the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> supporting the health group's petition. He said that while studies have not proven a connection between SIDS and Phenergan they have found an association between the two that needs more study. `` It's an unresolved issue, but I do n't think it's good to resolve it by putting it on the market over the counter,'' he said. <PERSON> Naeye </PERSON> said that while he generally endorses the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>'s push to make more drugs available without prescription, `` in this case, it's not prudent.''
