<HEAD>California Newspaper Group Chairman Dies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 27th graf pvs, `He is ...' to CORRECT James McClatchy's
age to 68 sted 58.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> `` C.K.'' <PERSON> McClatchy </PERSON>, who lambasted some fellow publishers for putting profit over news, was remembered upon his death as a leader with `` the very highest standards.'' The 62-year-old editor and chairman of the board of <ORGANIZATION> McClatchy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspapers </ORGANIZATION> collapsed Sunday afternoon while jogging in a park, said <PERSON> Erwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Potts </PERSON>, president of the company. He was pronounced dead a short time later at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, apparently of heart attack. <PERSON> Potts </PERSON> said <PERSON> McClatchy </PERSON> had no history of heart problems. `` He was a very healthy guy and he took good care of himself. ... It's just a shock to all of us. `` He was a hell of a newspaper man and he was a hell of a guy. We're just going to miss him an awful lot,'' said <PERSON> Potts </PERSON>, who had known <PERSON> McClatchy </PERSON> for 13 years. <PERSON> McClatchy </PERSON> was heir to a news empire that dated to the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Gold Rush. His family's newspaper group publishes 12 West Coast newspapers, including The Sacramento Bee; the <ORGANIZATION> Anchorage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, which won this year's Pulitzer Prize for public service; The <LOCATION> Fresno </LOCATION> Bee and The Modesto Bee; and The Morning News Tribune in <LOCATION> Tacoma </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Tri-City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, publisher and chief executive officer of the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, called <PERSON> McClatchy </PERSON> `` a splendid newspaper leader who represented the very highest standards of editorial and managerial excellence. `` He was uncommonly dedicated to quality in his newspapers,'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. `` His passing is a major loss to our profession.'' <PERSON> McClatchy </PERSON> blasted fellow publishers in a January 1988 speech, saying many paid more attention to profit margins than quality journalism. He told an audience at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Riverside </LOCATION>, that some media groups used their publications as `` ever-faithful cash cows for the owners.'' `` C.K. represents everything that was good about journalism and newspapering,'' said <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> Favre </PERSON>, executive editor of The Sacramento Bee. `` His values, his concerns, his integrity, his gentleness and his toughness, his generosity, his intellect, his curiousity and his caring created an environment which inspired all around him to do their best,'' <PERSON> Favre </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Weaver </PERSON>, managing editor of the <ORGANIZATION> Anchorage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, said that since <PERSON> McClatchy </PERSON>'s purchase of the paper a decade ago, the company provided it financial support `` to literally go from being on its deathbed to being the state's leading newspaper.'' <PERSON> McClatchy </PERSON>'s company became embroiled in a legal dispute in 1984 with then-Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Laxalt </PERSON>, a close friend of <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and one-time <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> candidate for president, after The Sacramento Bee and two other newspapers in the group published a story in 1983 on the <PERSON> Laxalt </PERSON> family's ownership of a hotel-casino in <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> during the 1970s It said federal agents believed someone had illegally skimmed profits from the casino to cut its tax liability. <PERSON> Laxalt </PERSON> filed a $ 250 million libel suit against the McClatchy newspapers. When the suit was settled in 1987, the papers issued a statement saying `` extensive discovery'' found no evidence of skimming. Both sides claimed victory. <PERSON> McClatchy </PERSON>, born March 25, 1927, in <LOCATION> Fresno </LOCATION>, earned his undergraduate degree at <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in 1950. He served in the Army from 1951 to 1953, and reported for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> from 1953 to 1955. The next two years, he was assistant press secretary to <PERSON> Adlai </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevenson </PERSON> in the Democrat's second unsuccessful presidential campaign against <PERSON> Dwight </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON>. In 1957, <PERSON> McClatchy </PERSON> returned to reporting, with <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. He joined The <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION> Bee in 1958, starting as a reporter and working his way to associate editor in 1962. He was named editor of <ORGANIZATION> McClatchy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspapers </ORGANIZATION> in 1974, elected company president in 1978, replacing his aunt <PERSON> Eleanor </PERSON> <PERSON> McClatchy </PERSON> and made chairman in 1988. In Feburary 1988, <ORGANIZATION> McClatchy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspapers </ORGANIZATION> offered public stock for the first time, but control remained under <PERSON> McClatchy </PERSON> and six other family members and several family trusts. <PERSON> McClatchy </PERSON> was the great-grandson of <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> McClatchy </PERSON>, an Irish immigrant who came to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> in 1857, became a reporter on the newly founded <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bee </LOCATION>, and purchased the newspaper a short time later. He passed the newspaper to son, C.K. <PERSON> McClatchy </PERSON>, who was editor and chairman of the company for 53 years until his death in 1936. His daughter <PERSON> Eleanor </PERSON> was the next president. <PERSON> McClatchy </PERSON> also was a member of the Pulitzer Prize Board, the <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advertising </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors, <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journalism </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> board of trustees and the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors executive committee. He is survived by two sons, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON>, 30, of <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON>, 26, of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>; daughter, <PERSON> Adair </PERSON>, 28, of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>; two brothers, <PERSON> James </PERSON>, 68, of <LOCATION> Tiburon </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Ellery </PERSON>, 64, of <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>; and his mother, <PERSON> Phebe </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Fesno </LOCATION>. He was divorced from his wife, <PERSON> Grace </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennan </PERSON>, whose father <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennan </PERSON> served as ambassador to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> under President <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> and was the architect of the post-World War II containment policy against Soviet expansionism. Funeral arrangements were not immediately announced.
