<FIRST>r w AM-Housing     04-17 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Housing,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>As Costs Rise for Poor, Number of Available Homes Shrinks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Despite increases in federal spending and the number of families being helped, poor families face an ever-growing shortage of low-rent homes and apartments, according to a private study of government data released Monday. More of the poor were forced to pay more for housing because of soaring costs from 1978 to 1985, said the study, entitled `` A Place to Call Home.'' The study was produced by two advocacy groups that generally advocate increased resources for social programs, the Center on Budget and Policy Priorities and the <ORGANIZATION> Low </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Income </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. The authors used data from a 1985 housing survey. The various findings of the study are captured in one statistic: The proportion of poor renting families who pay at least 60 percent of their income for rent and utilities rose from 44 percent in 1978 to 55 percent in 1985. Among poor owners, the proportion rose from 31 percent to 38 percent. Half of all poor renting households paid at least $ 266 a month in 1985, up from the 1978 figure of $ 229. In the 1970s and 1980s, housing demand increased while supply shrank, the study said. The number of households with cash incomes below the official poverty line rose 25 percent from 10.5 million to 13.3 million from 1978 to 1985. That line was $ 8,573 for a family of three in 1985. <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> guidelines consider housing `` affordable'' if it takes no more than 30 percent of family income. The number of houses and apartments available for a monthly rent of $ 250 or less _ 30 percent of the income of a family making $ 10,000 a year _ was 9.7 million in 1970, or 2.4 million more than the comparable number of families. In 1978, there were still 370,000 more units than familes, but by 1985 the number of families had risen to 11.6 million while the number of houses and apartments available at $ 250 or less had fallen to 7.9 million _ a deficit of 3.7 million affordable housing units. Of the 7.9 million, 800,000 were vacant and 1.5 million were occupied by families with incomes above the poverty line. The primary cause of the disappearance of low-cost housing, according to <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Zigas </PERSON>, executive secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Low </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Income </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, was `` upgrading, abandonment and changes in use,'' including gentrification in some cities, as well as `` substantial cost escalation in housing.'' `` Our housing resources are filtering up rather than down'' the income scale, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
