<HEAD>Highlights of President's Initiative of Incentives</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMTRAMCK, Mich (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are the major features of the package President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> unveiled Monday to reward <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> for its recent steps toward democracy and to encourage further political and economic reforms. _ Trade concessions The administration will submit to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> legislation to lower <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> tariffs on a variety of Polish goods. This would be accomplished by putting <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> under the Generalized System of Preferences, which gives this form of trade relief to selected countries with low per-capita incomes. The administration estimates the value to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> at $ 3.5 million to $ 25 million annually, depending on what products benefit from tariff reductions and how aggressively <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> reacts to the lowered tariffs. _ Old loans <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> called for other wealthy western nations to join the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in giving <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> easier terms for paying back its $ 38 billion foreign debt, only $ 2.4 billion of which is owed to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. But the debt stretch-out would be conditioned on economic reforms by the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> government. Administration sources said the step could lead to the rescheduling of up to $ 700 million in existing debt. _ New loans The administration said it would support conditional new loans to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> from the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>, but suggested they should be tied to movement toward `` market-oriented economic policies.'' The White House did not put a dollar value on the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> loans. Some official sources have suggested the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> loans could total $ 300 million if <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> meets all the requirements, followed perhaps by $ 250 million more from the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. _ Business investment The package provides a variety of incentives to encourage more <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> business investment in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, along with joint ventures with Polish businesses. These overtures would be made conditional on <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s progress in carrying out the political and labor reforms it has promised, including recognizing Solidarity and holding free and open parlimentary elections. _ Debt-equity swaps The government proposed that <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> be permitted to reduce some of its international debt by giving <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks or other investors shares in Polish enterprises in exchange.
