 <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s attorney predicted Monday the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> ethics committee will find no rules violations when it considers whether `` clear and convincing'' evidence exists of improper conduct by the speaker. Lawyer <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Oldaker </PERSON>, rebutting all the charges in the committee's statement of alleged violations, said they were based on `` a mischaracterization of facts ... outrageous readings of legislative history ... retroactive writing of the rules ... doublespeak.'' <PERSON> Oldaker </PERSON> commented after committee chairman <PERSON> Julian </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON>, D-Calif., announced the panel was charging the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Democrat with 69 violations of House rules In a lengthy statement, the panel found `` reason to believe'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> had broken rules requiring reporting of gifts, barring acceptance of gifts from persons with a direct interest in legislation and limiting outside earned income. Both <PERSON> Oldaker </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON> emphasized the committee's allegations were based only on a `` reason to believe'' that rules were violated. In order for the panel to declare actual violations took place and to recommend punishment by the full <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, it must find `` clear and convincing evidence,'' `` I am confident they will find no rules violations clearly and convincingly proved,'' said <PERSON> Oldaker </PERSON>, who particularly criticized the committee's special outside counsel, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, for its report Monday. The Committee on Standards of Official Conduct, the panel's formal name, charged that <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s friend and business partner, <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, real estate developer and investor <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON>, improperly provided $ 145,000 worth of gifts over a 10-year period The committee found that <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON> had a direct interest in legislation before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, making it a violation of <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> rules for <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> to accept more than $ 100 in gifts in a calendar year. <PERSON> Oldaker </PERSON> called the allegation that <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON> had a direct interest in legislation `` one of the most outrageous readings of legislative history.'' He called <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON> `` a close personal friend'' of <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> who had `` interest in oil and an interest in real estate. That covers everyone in the country.'' The attorney said <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON> `` never asked the speaker to do anything for himself or anyone else.'' The committee charged <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> with failing to report the benefits he received from <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON> as gifts on his annual financial disclosure forms. The items deemed `` gifts'' by the ethics committee included free housing from 1979 through 1984 in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>, valued at $ 31,698; cut-rate housing from 1985 through 1988, valued at $ 21,790; an $ 18,000-a-year salary paid to <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Betty </PERSON>, from 1981 through 1984, totaling $ 72,000, and the use and maintenance of a 1979 Cadillac from 1983 through 1988, valued at $ 19,391. According to <PERSON> Oldaker </PERSON>, it was <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON>'s practice `` to have employees live for free'' in the same <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> condominium complex he let the <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s use. <PERSON> Oldaker </PERSON> said <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON> wrongly implied that <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Betty </PERSON>, was inc