<HEAD>State to Charge for Use of `I Love New York' Logo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The cost of loving is going up. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, after years of allowing manufacturers free use of the `` I Love <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'' logo, will start charging royalties this year. People who print the logo on sweatshirts, key chains, pens or other consumer goods will be forced to give <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state 6 percent to 10 percent of the money they make, said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Morello </PERSON>, a state deputy commissioner for economic development. The state has spent more than $ 100 million advertising itself to tourists since launching the `` I Love <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'' advertising campaign in 1977, he said. The state registered the motto with a red heart symbol in place of the word `` love.'' Though the symbol has been adapted for a variety of bumper stickers and other uses, the state only holds the trademark for loving <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` We think this is one modest way to begin recapturing some of the investment without negatively impacting the motto's effectiveness,'' <PERSON> Morello </PERSON> said State officials have watched with great interest the success of the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> raisins advertising campaign, which has branched off into lucrative records, touring cartoon characters and other products, he said. A licensing agent will be hired to help market the logo, which tourism officials refer to in news releases as `` legendary.'' Up until now, the state has allowed manufacturers to include `` I Love <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'' in anything deemed appropriate, figuring it's helping the state advertise itself, he said Manufacturers who already use the logo will be allowed a certain period of time to sell off their inventory before they have to start paying, he said.
