<HEAD>Poles React to Solidarity Registration with Delight, Doubt</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Poles reacted with delight Monday to news that Solidarity was legal again, but some seemed doubtful that even the legalization of the independent union can solve the country's economic woes Many Poles had not heard by afternoon that the <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> had approved registration of the union that had energized the nation before being banned in the wake of the December 1981 martial-law crackdown. `` I did n't know. It's great. It should have happened a long time ago,'' said <PERSON> Gregorz </PERSON> <PERSON> Maracewicz </PERSON>, a Solidarity supporter who works in the science office of the <PERSON> Roza </PERSON> <PERSON> Luksemburg </PERSON> light-bulb factory. `` We will have to see what they -LRB- Solidarity -RRB- will do, but it will make a great difference for all of us,'' he said before heading home in a driving spring snowstorm after his shift. `` It's a good thing. It should change things, but it's hard to say whether Solidarity can do it all by itself,'' said a factory employee and former Solidarity member who declined to give her name. At the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Professional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Training </ORGANIZATION>, near where the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> branch of Solidarity had its offices during its first 16 months of legality, employees welcomed the decision. `` I am very happy. I really think it's a historic moment. I think registration was the first condition of all the changes which are going to improve things when there is more democracy,'' said sociologist <PERSON> Krystyna </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewinska </PERSON>. `` I do n't give interviews,'' said another institute employee who walked away and smiled. He then turned his head and added, `` But I am very happy.'' Most of those interviewed who were members of the union during its legal phase in 1980-81 said they would join again. `` That's obvious,'' said <PERSON> Alina </PERSON> <PERSON> Jablonska </PERSON>, an employee in a design office now on maternity leave, when asked if she would become a member again. `` We are full of hope. The whole society, at least my community, believes our life problems should disappear, perhaps not so soon, but in the long term,'' she said. An elderly woman, who like <PERSON> Jablonska </PERSON> was standing in line for meat at the <LOCATION> Hala </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mirowska </LOCATION> market, disagreed. `` It does n't matter who rules. What matters is that things should be good in this country so that I should n't have to stand in line for a piece of meat,'' said the woman, a retired factory worker who was a member of Solidarity in 1980-81. `` I do n't think anything will change,'' she added, declining to give her name. Authorities and the opposition hope the legalization of Solidarity will provide social calm needed for economic reforms to take effect. Chronic consumer shortages and the failure of wages to keep pace with inflation sparked two crippling waves of strikes in May and August 1988. Service on <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s $ 38 billion debt eats up hard currency needed for investments to modernize industry. In light of such problems, some Poles want to wait and see what the union can do before joining. The union once boasted 10 million members out of the 18 million-member workforce, but <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> has said he expects 5 million to 7 million in the new Solidarity. Others demonstrated their commitment to Solidarity even before the decision to register the union was officially announced. `` We organized when Solidarity was illegal, underground, so we are not used to this new situation. We represent committees already organized in our region. The big difference will be our freedom of action,'' said <PERSON> Roman </PERSON> <PERSON> Jarosz </PERSON>. The 26-year-old construction worker and three of his friends took the overnight train from their home in <LOCATION> Gorzow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wielkopolski </LOCATION> in western <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> so they could hold up a Solidarity banner in the courtroom where the decision was read.
