 <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration officials defended their 1990 African aid budget proposal Monday against a <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> senator's accusations of neglect and misplaced priorities. Sen. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON>, D-Vt., told his <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Operations </ORGANIZATION> subcommmittee that despite millions of dollars in American aid, countries south of the Sahara are `` facing every imaginable problem'' today, with less economic assistance provided for the half billion people who live in the region than for nine million people in two <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> countries, <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. The senator demanded that the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration halt what he called a Republican `` policy of neglect'' that he said was demonstrated by former President <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s never once visiting <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. `` To put it bluntly,'' <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON> said, `` your 1990 budget is wholly inadequate to meet the challenges. ... I want us to do more.'' <PERSON> Alison </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON>, deputy assistant secretary of state for <LOCATION> African </LOCATION> affairs, acknowledged that recent appropriations for <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> `` have fallen short of allowing us to meet our earlier stated objectives.'' The 1990 request for $ 820 million in economic and $ 85 million in military assistance for sub-Saharan <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, a 10 percent increase over 1989, has the correct emphasis, she said, with 10 times as much economic as military assistance. Ms. <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON> said the military aid is focussed on countries with important <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> strategic interests _ <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chad </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Zaire </L