<HEAD>Spy Agency to Build Computer Chip Plant to Make Sure of Secure Supply</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>'s decision to build its own top secret computer-chip plant was spurred by the threat of sensitive technology falling `` into the wrong hands,'' according to American electronics specialists. The <ORGANIZATION> NSA </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's biggest intelligence agency, says the $ 85 million microelectronics plant being built at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Meade </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, represents a `` unique capability within the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. government.'' The move comes amid increasing concern about erosion of American chip-making expertise and manufacturing capacity in the face of stiff competition from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and other countries. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>'s main missions are eavesdropping on communications around the globe, encoding <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> communications and cracking foreign codes, as well as safeguarding the security of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military computers and communications systems. To carry out those missions, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> agency makes heavy use of sophisticated, powerful computers. Author <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Bamford </PERSON>, an authority on the agency has reported that computers cover more than 5 -LCB- acres at its headquarters complex at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Meade </LOCATION>. According to <PERSON> Bamford </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> NSA </ORGANIZATION> has a work force topping 60,000 employees _ more than all other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> spy agencies combined _ and a budget estimated at more than $ 10 billion a year. The <ORGANIZATION> NSA </ORGANIZATION>'s public affairs offic