 at dealing with the threat of `` reverse engineering'' _ efforts to figure out the functioning of a computer system by scrutinizing its key components. `` That is why they do n't want to have a process made elsewhere. ... You have coding and so on, and if that falls into the wrong hands, the other side could find out what your code is. That's why they want to keep control of it in-house,'' he said. <PERSON> Hazan </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electrical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION>, a 300,000-member professional association, said that `` we are losing the commercial semiconductor competition.'' `` Since that, in turn, is what is driving the technology, we rapidly find ourselves where in defense, if you want to build defense systems, you wo n't have the capability here. You have to go overseas and hope that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> or somebody else is willing to apply the resources to that, as opposed to something else,'' he said. <PERSON> Hazan </PERSON> added that `` if you do that, then it's a -LRB- commercial -RRB- market _ presumably they'll sell it to anybody who has the need. So it's potentially a very tricky situation.'' <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Sumney </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Semiconductor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, an electronics company in Research Triangle Park, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, said that in 1982, while he was on the Pentagon staff, he chaired a <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> task force on development of very high-speed integrated circuits. The task force recommended to the science board that the government `` give some consideration to putting together a facility to provide state-of-the-art integrated circuits for classified applications,'' he said. <PERSON> Sumney </PERSON> noted that another <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> task force study in 1987 also `` called attention to the fact that the government could n't put itself in a position of being dependent on foreign sources.'' Asked about the <ORGANIZATION> NSA </ORGANIZATION>'s decision to build its own chip plant, <PERSON> Sumney </PERSON> said, `` I would think that now it's even more supportable, because we've continued to erode in our ability to be competitive in world markets for integrated circuits.''
