<FIRST>r w AM-ThirdWorldDebt     04-17 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Third World Debt,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Don't Expect Immediate Results, Brady Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The author of President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s new plan for encouraging commerical banks to voluntarily reduce Third World debt told <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Monday not to expect immediate results. Despite a $ 3.6 billion package put together last week by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> to support economic reform in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> said it is too optimistic to assume that commercial banks will immediately agree on how much to cut <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s debt to them. Mexican Finance Minister <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> Aspe </PERSON> was scheduled to begin negotiations this week with a consortium of 13 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commercial banks holding a large portion of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s $ 100 billion debt. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> told members of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Approporations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> that the $ 1.3 billion first-year portion of the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> package would depend on <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> negotiating debt reductions from the commercial banks. However, he said he expects negotiations to be `` lengthy'' before any agreement is announced. `` To be dead honest with you, I think you ought to be prepared to wait longer,'' he said. `` Let's not try to make the first of these transactions so big that it scares everybody to death. We do n't have to throttle the train up to a 100 miles per hour when we're first getting started.'' But Rep. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON>, R-Mo., said there is a `` short time span'' for the commercial banks to step forward The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> secretary said he was `` disappointed'' that the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> package announced last week did not include provisions for so-called debt-equity swaps. In those deals, a bank will forgive a portion of the principle or interest on a loan in exchange for an investment share in newly privatized enterprises that formerly were operated by the debtor country's government. Without naming them, <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> said he knew of two countries negotiating deals to write down by 20 percent loans for electric power stations that would be converted from public to private ownership. The parties involved, he said, believe that amount of money will be returned to the countries in the form of native capital that had earlier fled it. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> attempted to dispel fears that taxpayers will end up bailing out banks with Third World loans through arrangement by government-funded multilateral lending agencies like the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> to guarantee that commercial banks that reduce the loans will be paid the remaining balance. `` I do n't think anybody's going to be involved in putting more money into it than we're already putting into it,'' he said. But because countries can leverage money from the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and the loans held by commerical banks are being sold for only 25 to 60 percent of their face value, he said, the plan would allow countries to buy back a face value amount equal to 10 times the seed money, he said. `` You can get a $ 10 reduction for every dollar you spend on the process,'' <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> said. In addition, he said, $ 9 in procurement `` comes back our way'' for every dollar of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> taxpayer funds funneled to debtor countries through the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>.
