<HEAD>U.S. Stepping Up Efforts to Spot Private Coverage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government is planning to increase its efforts to assure that the <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> program does not pay medical bills for which private insurance carriers are liable. The secretary of health and human services, <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>, asked <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> in a letter Friday to release $ 7.5 million to begin the stepped-up enforcement plan. The <ORGANIZATION> HHS </ORGANIZATION> contingency funds would be used to make revisions in the contracts with <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> claims processors to require them to match their private insurance records with their <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> rolls, <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said. This would enable them to identify claims where private policies are liable for the bill. The coverage issue stems from an overlap between <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> and private health plans for elderly people who continue to work. Under the law, <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> is liable only for charges not covered by the elderly employee's private health plan. Current efforts by the <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> results in annual Medicare savings of more than $ 1.8 billion, but `` <ORGANIZATION> HCFA </ORGANIZATION> has known for some time that there is potential for even greater savings,'' <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said the department, which includes <ORGANIZATION> HCFA </ORGANIZATION>, would again propose legislation that would require all health insurers to provide information identifying those enrolled in their plans who may be eligible for <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION>. `` Although our efforts to convince the Office of Management and Budget of the need for this legislation have been unsuccessful,'' recent findings of an <ORGANIZATION> HHS </ORGANIZATION> task force as well as news reports of potential savings and possibile fraud highlight the need for greater efforts, <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has said it is reviewing a number of cases referred by <ORGANIZATION> HHS </ORGANIZATION> in which authorities believe <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> paid medical bills for which private carriers were liable. The department's civil division recently filed lawsuits against two private insurance companies to recover money the government claims should not have been paid by <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> reported earlier this month that its investigation of <ORGANIZATION> HCFA </ORGANIZATION> records shows as much as $ 10 billion may have been misspent over the last six years because the agency has failed to correct the billing problem. <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> currently is paying about $ 67 million this year to 88 commercial insurance companies that serve as claims processors to identify claims where private insurance carriers _ sometimes their own _ are liable. HHS Inspector General <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kusserow </PERSON> and others have said they are concerned about a possible conflict of interest in these companies' roles as a <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> contractor and commercial insurance carrier.
