<HEAD>Pisa's Tower to be Measured at the End of Each Season</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PISA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Leaning Tower of <LOCATION> Pisa </LOCATION> will be measured every three months instead of just once a year to see if seasonal change affects the landmark, scientists said Monday. Since 1913, the angle of the 800-year-old tower's lean has been measured every year in June. This year a reading was taken in March, and other measurements will be taken in June, September and December. `` There is no particular cause for alarm,'' said <PERSON> Brunetto </PERSON> <PERSON> Palla </PERSON>, a professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pisa </ORGANIZATION>. `` We are curious to see whether the change of seasons has an affect on the tower.'' The collapse of a 900-year-old tower in <LOCATION> Pavia </LOCATION> on March 17 has raised concerns over the stability and safety of <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s monuments. Four people were killed. The March measurements showed no notable variation from June 1988, <PERSON> Palla </PERSON> said. The monument began to lean shortly after its construction in 1173 when the soil beneath the 180-foot marble monument shifted.
