<FIRST>r w AM-TritiumSupply     04-17 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tritium Supply,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientific Group Says Don't Rush to Restart Tritium Production</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Eleven prominent scientists are urging the government not to rush into new production of tritium, an important constituent of nuclear weapons, until the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has been sounded out about reductions in the nuclear stockpile. Tritium decays and must be replenished in nuclear weapons from time to time. None has been produced in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> since the aging reactors at the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, plant were shut down a year ago for safety upgrading Officials have testified that at least one reactor must be restarted by the end of the year or the need for new tritium will become critical. Some members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> have said failure to restart production would amount to unilateral nuclear disarmament. The <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> plans to spend $ 7.5 billion to build two new tritium-producing reactors that could be ready in 10 years. In a statement dated Sunday, the 11 scientists said that once the options were studied, `` it would be surprising not to find that tritium requirements to maintain a fully adequate stockpile'' of weapons could be met for about five years without additional production. ` It should not take as long as five years, however, to determine whether the START and other arms-reduction negotiations are likely to produce cuts sufficient to permit continued suspension of tritium production,'' the scientists said. Their statement was organized by the <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, which has advocated a similar position. The signers included two Nobel Prize winners and three former staff members of the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alamos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION>, the principal nuclear weapons research and development installation. A spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> did not immediately return a telephone call seeking comment. The fusion of atoms of tritium, which is hydrogen containing two neutrons instead of none, is the driving force of thermonuclear weapons. Other weapons use the neutron burst from the fusion of small amounts of tritium to accelerate or `` boost'' the fission reactions of plutonium, reducing the amount of plutonium required for the same explosive yield. Weapons are loaded with a surplus of tritium and reloaded when all the surplus is gone. The reloading cycle is a secret and presumably varies from weapon to weapon. The scientists noted published reports that the reloading cycle is four to six years for current weapons and 10 years for new submarine-launched missiles. The scientists advocated more frequent reloading with a smaller surplus and the use of tritium from warheads withdrawn under treaty terms or simply retired. `` Some may already have been taken into account, and some may not provide much relief. But certainly these, and any other similar examples, should be exploited before it is concluded that there is any imminent crisis,'' the group said. The 11 scientists are <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> <PERSON> Bethe </PERSON>, retired professor of physics at <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON> <PERSON> Dyson </PERSON>, professor of physics at the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advanced </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Study </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Princeton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> <PERSON> Feshbach </PERSON>, retired professor of physics at <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Val </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitch </PERSON>, professor of physics at <ORGANIZATION> Princeton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldberger </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advanced </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Study </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Gottfried </PERSON>, professor of physics at <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoenig </PERSON>, scientific director of the <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON>, retired professor of chemistry at <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> <PERSON> Mark </PERSON>, consultant; <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Rathjens </PERSON>, professor of political science at <ORGANIZATION> MIT </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Weisskopf </PERSON>, retired professor of physics at <ORGANIZATION> MIT </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Bethe </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fitch </PERSON> hold the Nobel Prize in physics and <PERSON> Bethe </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> and <PERSON> Weisskopf </PERSON> formerly worked at <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alamos </LOCATION>. All 11 have advised or worked in federal government agencies.
</TEXT>
