<HEAD>Government Warns of Measures Against Chilean Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Authorities asked workers to ignore calls for a general strike Tuesday that would be the first mass protest against the military government since 1987. The General Workers Central, the country's largest labor movement, called the work stoppage to protest banishment of its two top leaders involved in the last major protest strike in October 1987. That strike against the government of President <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> failed to halt most activities in the country, but it ignited violence that left three people dead. The government said Monday it has taken `` all the necessary measures'' to maintain public order and `` guarantee the rights of those wanting to work.'' Interior Subsecretary <PERSON> Gonzalo </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> urged workers `` not to be afraid to go to work tomorrow.'' <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> did not elaborate on the anti-strike measures taken by authorities. In the past, the government has mobilized thousands of police and army troops during such protests. A series of mass protests shook the military government from 1983 to 1986, leaving at least 200 dead. The federation urged all the nation's workers to boycott work Tuesday and to keep their children home from school. A number of trade unions and a coalition of 17 opposition parties have said they will join the strike. Opposition politicians, however, have openly said they do not expect a significant work stoppage. The president of the opposition-controlled Workers Central, <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Bustos </PERSON>, and vice president <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> were sentenced to internal exile in small provincial towns last year. They were charged with promoting violence and breaking state security law. The federation also is demanding an increase of the minimum wage from $ 55 to $ 100 a month. <PERSON> Diego </PERSON> <PERSON> Olivares </PERSON>, acting president of the labor federation, said Monday the strike `` should be entirely peaceful,'' but some leftist groups are calling for street demonstrations in <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> and other cities. Police said the demonstrations will not be allowed. Three bombs went off in <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> on Sunday night, causing damage but no casualties. No one claimed responsibility, but police said they found pro-strike pamphlets nearby.
