<HEAD>Suit Filed to Halt Base Closings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An organization representing federal employees filed suit Monday to prevent the closing of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military bases, charging that the law creating the federal commission that recommends base closings is unconstitutional. The lawsuit, filed in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION> against the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, said the Base Closure and Realignment Act violates the Constitution `` by improperly delegating the important legislative function of regulating the disposition of government property, to the unelected secretary of defense, and to the unelected members of the commission.'' The suit also said that the Constitution requires that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> provide for the nation's defense. The base closure law calls for the commission's recommendations to be accepted in their entirety and denies <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> the right to determine `` the logistical arrangements for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military forces in the 21st century,'' the suit said. The union represents 5,000 employees at <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Norton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Chanute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. All are scheduled to be closed. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> approved legislation in October 1988 requiring the <ORGANIZATION> defense </ORGANIZATION> secretary to close and realign bases according to the panel's report. Two months later, the commission recommended closing 86 bases, partly closing five more and changing the mission of 54 others. Former <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> approved the commission's report in January. The House is scheduled to vote Tuesday on a resolution to disapprove the base closing recommendations. Last month, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, by a vote of 43-4, supported the recommendations; the full <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> is expected to do the same. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Peirce </PERSON>, president of the union, said the commission based its decision on `` erroneous and out-of-date information. To put it simply, the commission blew it and it does n't appear as if the majority of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> gives a damn.'' The union is seeking a declaratory judgment from the courts on whether the Base Closure and Realignment Act is unconstitutional.
