<FIRST>u i AM-Italy-Fusion     04-17 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Fusion,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Italian Scientists Report Achieving Fusion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Experts and news reports said Monday that Italian scientists had created nuclear fusion at room temperature in a small container. Scientists at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alternative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> in Frascati, outside <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, measured neutrons being emitted from their experiment, said a scientist familiar with the work. `` They saw a lot of neutrons; that means fusion,'' said <PERSON> Francesco </PERSON> <PERSON> Celani </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Physics </ORGANIZATION>, who worked with the Frascati group. The scientists were trying to copy an experiment by <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleischmann </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southampton </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION>, who announced last month they had achieved nuclear fusion in a glass beaker at room temperature. <PERSON> Fleischmann </PERSON> and <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> claimed their experiment yielded four times the energy put into it. If they are correct, the result could be a relatively inexpensive energy source that is virtually inexhaustible. No scientists have managed to duplicate the energy burst reported in the experiment, however, and many experts believe the two scientists made a mistake. Several universities have said they confirmed parts of the Fleischmann-Pons experiment. Another researcher, <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Brigham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Young </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, says he also created nuclear fusion but the energy output was virtually nil. <PERSON> Pierluigi </PERSON> <PERSON> Sani </PERSON>, public relations director of the Frascati agency, refused to confirm Italian media reports that scientists there had achieved fusion. A news conference has been scheduled for Tuesday, and `` officially we ca n't say anything until tomorrow,'' he said. <PERSON> Celani </PERSON> said the scientists at Frascati checked for neutrons but not energy emission. Fusion is the process powering the sun, in which tremendous amounts of energy are released when the cores of two hydrogen atoms fuse. By contrast, nuclear power plants get energy from fission, the splitting of atoms. Most scientists seeking a way to harness nuclear fusion have used extremely high temperatures and machines the size of houses to jam atoms together. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fleischmann </PERSON> used electrical current to herd hydrogen atoms into metal electrodes, where the hydrogen atoms apparently fused because of proximity. In the Frascati experiment, scientists forced hydrogen atoms into titanium and, according to <PERSON> Celani </PERSON>, lowered the temperature of the experiment to enhance fusion.
</TEXT>
