<HEAD>First Lady Lauds Volunteer Effort in Literacy Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, saying nearly all of society's benefits flow from literacy, praised a young woman Monday who learned to read and broke free from the welfare cycle Addressing more than 3,000 volunteer leaders at a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Way </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> national </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> conference </ORGANIZATION>, the first lady said: `` You are at the heart of virtually every worthy cause there is.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> praised <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Way </LOCATION> for its help and funding of such organizations as <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> and the Boy Scouts and Girl Scouts and causes as diverse as combatting child abuse and comforting young AIDS patients. Then, turning to the cause that has been the focus of her own volunteer leadership, Mrs. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said as many as 25 percent of Americans struggle with literacy. `` Literacy is everybody's business,'' she said. `` The need for literacy is linked to every other important need in society ... housing, nutrition, health ... employment.'' To illustrate the point, Mrs. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s address was followed by a videotape about <PERSON> Evelyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Vega </PERSON>, a 29-year-old <LOCATION> Stamford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, resident and mother of three children, who broke 11 years of welfare dependence by learning to read and getting a job. Mrs. <PERSON> Vega </PERSON> dropped out of high school during her first pregnancy and was the third generation of her family to live on public assistance. The film showed her receiving reading lessons from <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Way </LOCATION> volunteer <PERSON> Paige </PERSON> <PERSON> Oristano </PERSON> and working as the assistant manager at a fast-food restaurant. After the film, Mrs. <PERSON> Vega </PERSON>, who since has become a <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Way </LOCATION> volunteer, read from a letter she had written Mrs. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to thank her for supporting literacy programs. `` It is hard and scary to get off welfare. You can not do it by yourself. People like me need someone out there to teach them how to make that dream come true because it is all new to them. ... I still feel scared,'' she said, her voice choking with tears. Mrs. <PERSON> Vega </PERSON> presented the first lady with a copy of the letter and the two women hugged briefly as the gathering rose to its feet and applauded. Overcome with emotion, Mrs. <PERSON> Vega </PERSON> kissed Mrs. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s cheek Later Monday, Mrs. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> traveled to the <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> on the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Side </LOCATION>, where she officially opened an exhibit on the brain and learning disabilities. The permanent exhibit, called `` Learning and Learning Disabilties: Explorations of the Human Brain,'' is the first of its kind in the nation. ` This is truly an exhibit of hope,'' the first lady said. `` I applaud the museum for addressing this misunderstood subject in a public forum.'' The exhibit uses touch screens, video monitors, mannequins and giant brain models to show how the brain changes as it learns and how disabilties alter that process.
