<HEAD>Overturned Platform Sinks After Floating North</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A $ 42 million drilling platform that capsized in heavy seas off <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> 10 days ago drifted more than 280 miles to the northeast before finally sinking off <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, officials said Monday. The 27,500-ton structure sank shortly before 1 a.m. Sunday about 62 miles east of <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lookout </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> Chief Warrant Officer <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. The platform was being towed from <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Gloucester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, for a pipeline project when it capsized April 7. No one was aboard it. The platform, known as a jack-up rig, was used for exploratory drilling and other underwater projects. Authorities are not sure why it overturned, but <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said heavy seas contributed. The Coast Guard is investigating. After the platform capsized, it slowly sank, drifting northeast with the Gulf Stream, <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. A tug stayed with the rig to make sure no ships ran into it, he said. An estimated 500 gallons of oil, hydraulic oil and diesel fuel were aboard the platform, but officials do n't feel that presents a major environmental threat because the platform sank well off the coast, in water 1 -LCB- miles deep, <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. The platform, owned by <ORGANIZATION> Maitland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Littlestown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, was built in 1978 by <ORGANIZATION> Bethleham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> for $ 42 million, said company spokesman <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> McCormick </PERSON>.
