<HEAD>Man Charged With Killing 18 Elderly Women Dies of AIDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man who confessed to the serial murders of 18 elderly <LOCATION> Parisian </LOCATION> women died Monday of AIDS while awaiting trial, prison officials said. <PERSON> Thierry </PERSON> <PERSON> Paulin </PERSON>, a 26-year-old native of <LOCATION> Martinique </LOCATION>, was arrested Dec. 1, 1987, after a three-year manhunt for the killer of a large group of elderly women between October 1984 and January 1986. The women all were between 60 and 83 years of age, and nearly all were strangled, stabbed or smothered in their homes after being severely beaten. <PERSON> Paulin </PERSON> told police that he stalked the women and forced his way into their homes. <PERSON> Paulin </PERSON> had a record of arrests for thefts and drugs, but police said the killings did not seem to be linked exclusively to money. They said that during the interrogation, <PERSON> Paulin </PERSON> `` had trouble distinguishing between all the attacks he had committed.'' <PERSON> Paulin </PERSON>'s fingerprints were found in the homes of at least seven murder victims, police said at the time. Prison authorities, who declined to be identified in keeping with prison policy, said <PERSON> Paulin </PERSON> tested positive for AIDS in 1986 and last year began suffering symptoms of the disease that attacks and destroys the body's immune system. <PERSON> Paulin </PERSON> fell into a coma several days ago and was admitted to the intensive care unit of <LOCATION> Fresnes </LOCATION> prison hospital over the weekend. He died early Monday, authorities said without providing any other details. Before his death, <PERSON> Paulin </PERSON> blamed several of the murders on his accomplice, <PERSON> Jean-Thierry </PERSON> <PERSON> Mathuin </PERSON>, who was arrested shortly after <PERSON> Paulin </PERSON> and remains in custody. AIDS is most often transmitted through sexual contact. Other means of transmission include transfusions of tainted blood or blood products, and the sharing of contaminated hypodermic needles or syringes by drug abusers.
