<FIRST>r i AM-LuxembourgBirthday     04-17 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Luxembourg Birthday,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Luxembourg Marks 150 Years Of Independence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAF CASERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUXEMBOURG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION>, a nation smaller than the state of <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, marks its 150th anniversary Tuesday determined to survive among the great powers that spawned its independence. A speck on the world map _ tucked between <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> - the grand duchy has used its position on the crossroads of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s main cultures to maintain one of the highest standards of living in the world. `` Do n't mix us up with countries that are even smaller than ours,'' said <PERSON> Lex </PERSON> <PERSON> Roth </PERSON>, a government spokesman. <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION>, with a population of 372,000, became independent of the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> under the 1839 Treaty of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> signed by the European powers. Since then its fate has been determined by close cooperation with its neighbors _ an inevitable option for a nation that covers only 999 square miles. <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> is 1,214 square miles. `` It is essential a small state like us can survive and develop by keeping its independence only within great frameworks,'' Prime Minister <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Santer </PERSON>, who heads a center-left coalition government, said recently. <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION> is a founding member of the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> and an ardent member of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>. It is home for a number of <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> institutions, including the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION> license plates display the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> flag of 12 gold stars in a field of royal blue. Tuesday's independence celebrations will be attended by foreign dignitaries from many nations, including <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. In recent decades, <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION> has become a financial center. The city of <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION>, with a population of 75,000, has more than 100 banks from around the world and the banking industry employs 10 percent of the work force and accounts for a quarter of the national income. The financial institutions have helped keep unemployment at about 1.5 percent, by far the lowest in the 12-nation EEC. Immigrants account for 27 percent of the population, the highest in the EEC. Problems involving immigrants do exist, <PERSON> Roth </PERSON> said, but without the violence that mars coexistence in many other European nations. Although they have no voting rights, `` our <LOCATION> Portuguese </LOCATION> and Italian fellow citizens have all the same social rights as Luxembourgers,'' he said. To improve integration, a relaxed naturalization process in recent years has made it easier for immigrants to gain citizenship. Language poses a problem for foreigners from southern <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Roth </PERSON> said. Most Luxembourgers speak German and French along with <PERSON> Luxembourgish </PERSON>, a German dialect. But <PERSON> Roth </PERSON> added: `` We're a good blend. The French are more impulsive, the Germans more heavy-handed,'' giving Luxembourgers balance and patience.
</TEXT>
