<TEXT>
 A man convicted of slaying six people at a shopping center wept as relatives testifying at his sentencing described how he cared for his mother and ailing wife. It was the first public display of emotion by <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> <PERSON> Cruse </PERSON> during the long trial and numerous court appearances for the shooting rampage in <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> two years ago that claimed the lives of two police officers and four other people. <PERSON> Cruse </PERSON>, 61, was convicted April 5 on 32 counts of murder, attempted murder and kidnapping. The jury that found him guilty must recommend to Circuit Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Antoon </PERSON> whether <PERSON> Cruse </PERSON> should be sentenced to death or life in prison. <PERSON> Cruse </PERSON> cried when his niece, <PERSON> Rebbeca </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, told jurors that he doted on his wife, who had Parkinson's disease `` He was always there for her,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> said. `` They never had children, but they had each other.'' She said her uncle visited his mother every day in a nursing home until her death in 1980. <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cruse </PERSON>, widow of the convicted man's brother, said the defendant `` took good care of his mother. He would come over and fix her breakfast. If she was ill, he would stay all night. ... We all loved him and still do.'' Earlier, Assistant State Attorney <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> said <PERSON> Cruse </PERSON> should be put to death because he committed the murders in a `` cold, calculated, premeditated fashion.'' But Assistant Public Defender <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Arlt </PERSON> said witnesses would show <PERSON> Cruse </PERSON> was severely mentally disturbed at the time of the crime, had a reduced capacity to realize the consequences of his actions, did not realize he had hurt anyone and that his mental condition was aggravated by alcohol.
