<HEAD>Sanguinetti Says Referendum Settles Amnesty Question</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTEVIDEO, Uruguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanguinetti </PERSON> said Monday the question of amnesty for human rights abuses under military rule has been settled by voter approval of the amnesty law his government passed in 1986. With 7,037 of 7,072 districts reporting in Sunday's referendum, the vote was 1,013,554 for amnesty, or 52.62 percent, and 771,942 _ 40.08 percent _ who wanted the law discarded. <PERSON> Sanguinetti </PERSON>, a 52-year-old lawyer, told reporters Monday: `` Now the discussion has ended.'' When asked whether his government would consider a compromise with opponents of amnesty, since they got nearly 41 percent of the vote, he replied: `` They were the ones who chose this way. They were the ones who submitted the law to a majority vote. ... National peace is to accept the verdict of the ballot box.'' Blank or invalid ballots, and others classed as questionable that may or may not be counted, totaled 140,703, or 7.3 percent of the votes cast. About 85 percent of eligible voters participated. The amnesty law forbids prosecution of about 180 soldiers and police accused of torture, murder and other crimes in 1973-85, when the military ruled <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> and conducted what it called a war on leftist subversion. It was passed by the new civilian government in December 1986, after officers made clear they would not answer charges in the courts. Three military uprisings have occurred in neighboring <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> during the past two years because of the same issue. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> returned to civilian government in 1983 after nearly eight years of military rule and has tried many officers, including former junta members. Uruguayans voted on amnesty because the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> for a Referendum gathered 634,000 petition signatures during 1987, more than the required 25 percent of registered voters. <PERSON> Sanguinetti </PERSON> said his goal was to consolidate democracy in this nation of 3 million people, which was an example of representative government to <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> before 1973, and `` in this case, peace is justice.'' He told the news conference amnesty does not excuse or justify military abuses, which included the executions of about 150 Uruguayans, arrests and disappearances of 200 more and the torture of several thousand. It must be remembered, he said, that military intervention followed years of terrorism and economic chaos. <PERSON> Sanguinetti </PERSON> said leftist Tupamaro guerrillas were released from prison in 1985 and the military amnesty `` is on the same line.'' `` There is no sense of triumph'' in the referendum's result, he said, and added: `` The most important aspect in all this is that the country was able to do it'' by popular vote. `` Yesterday at 7:30 p.m., when the ballot boxes were closed, <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> completed its transition'' to democracy. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> for a Referendum, and the human rights and leftist political groups that supported the referendum, apparently accepted the outcome. Only the small <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> said the vote was not fair, claiming the government intimidated voters by hinting of trouble if the amnesty was overturned. <PERSON> Matilde </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> <PERSON> Larreta </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gutierrez </PERSON>, co-president of the referendum commission, said: `` in accordance with the results of the referendum, the amnesty has been confirmed. Without doubt, the decision of the electorate should be accepted.''
</TEXT>
