<HEAD>Another Eastern Jet Seized With Cocaine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One of the relatively few <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> jets flying since the beginning of a strike against the carrier was seized Monday by Customs after inspectors found 75 pounds of cocaine in a mail bag in the cargo hold. It was the 14th seizure of cocaine on an Eastern plane since September, and eight of those shipments were found in the mail, or courier, bags. The <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727 seized Monday landed in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> after a flight from <LOCATION> Asuncion </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION>, that stopped in <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, said Customs spokesman <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheehan </PERSON>. Customs imposed a $ 1.2 million fine on Eastern and demanded a letter of credit from the strike-hobbled airline before releasing the plane. `` We hate to kick an airline while it's down, but we will not allow illegal drugs into the country,'' <PERSON> Sheehan </PERSON> said. Because of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s financial problems, Customs has decided to cash in three previous credit letters worth about $ 3 million, he said. The letters are usually held until Customs and the airline negotiate an agreement on the fine. Eastern spokeswoman <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Ceremsak </PERSON> said Customs will have to go to bankruptcy court to get its money. `` We do n't think that fining airlines and seizing their aircraft is the way to stop drug trafficking,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Ceremsak </PERSON>. She said the airline spent $ 3 million on security last year, an amount that was not decreased this year even though <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> has had to severely shrink its schedule following the March 4 Machinists' strike that was supported by pilots and flight attendants But <PERSON> Sheehan </PERSON> said Eastern apparently was n't doing the job, even though smugglers were using the same method time after time. `` Due to the fact that over half of the seizure have been in courier bags, we find it difficult to understand why courier bags do not receive extra attention,'' <PERSON> Sheehan </PERSON> said. `` There should n't be a courier bag on <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> that is n't gone over with a fine-toothed comb. The bright blue and green bag, of a type used to carry mail, was found during a routine inspection Monday by the <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Contraband </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Team </ORGANIZATION>. It was not on the plane manifest, and authorities did not know where it was put aboard the plane. No destination was listed on the bag, suggesting that someone planned to remove it from the cargo hold in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Sheehan </PERSON> said. Meanwhile, eight men who were Eastern baggage handlers at the time of their 1986 indictment went on trial Monday in a smuggling scheme. They are charged with conspiracy to import cocaine and conspiracy to possess cocaine with intent to distribute.
</TEXT>
