<HEAD>Fighting Poses Logistical Problems For U.N. Force</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HEIDI VON EGIDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said Monday that the fierce combat that broke out in northern <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> at the outset of the independence process has created severe logistical problems for the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> monitoring force. <PERSON> Cedric </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornberry </PERSON>, second-in-command of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> contingent that is to oversee <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>'s transition to independence, said <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> personnel had planned to use vacated South African military facilities. But because of clashes between security forces and guerrillas of the <ORGANIZATION> South-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Africa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, South African troop withdrawal has been delayed, he said. This has created `` enormous competition'' for accommodation and other facilities in the relatively underdeveloped northern region of Ovambo. <PERSON> Thornberry </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> planned to start deploying police monitors in <LOCATION> Ovambo </LOCATION> this week who will check actions of the South African-led territorial police force. But he said it was hard to find offices for monitors that were easily accessible to civilians who might want to file complaints. The world body has urged civilians to report allegations of harassment or intimidation by the security forces or <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> supporters. At <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> Foreign Secretary <PERSON> Theo-Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Gurirab </PERSON> said Monday that Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> should visit <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> to restore public confidence in the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Gurirab </PERSON> said a visit by the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> chief would help restore the `` tarnished'' image of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> in the eyes of Namibians. He blamed the world organization for not stationing <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peacekeepers in northern <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> by April 1, the day a cease-fire was supposed to take effect at the start of a yearlong transition to independence but instead the day that <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas fought gun battles with South African-led security forces. Territorial officials say 278 guerrillas and 27 security force members have been killed and 28 guerrillas captured. <PERSON> Thornberry </PERSON> said 2,662 members of the planned 4,650-member <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> military force were in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> by Monday, with 410 Kenyan infantrymen due by Tuesday. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> said about 1,600 guerrillas crossed the border from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> in violation of an agreement that they stay at bases at least 100 miles inside <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. Up to 380 guerrillas returned to <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> after withdrawal orders from their exiled leader, and about 900 remain in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> African </LOCATION> offficials say. As of Monday, only seven guerrillas reported to <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> checkpoints established as part of a plan to give guerrillas safe passage back to <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. The others who withdrew did so on their own. Officials expressed doubt that guerrillas would venture near the assembly points because of the heavy concentration of police and soldiers around each area. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has ruled <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> since World War I. In December, it agreed to allow independence in exchange for <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>'s withdrawing its estimated 50,000 troops from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> has fought South African rule since 1966 and is favored to get the most votes in pre-independence elections scheduled for November.
