 Similarly, when <PERSON> Moncrief </PERSON> agreed in June 1984 to take a `` farm out'' from <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> of <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s interest in the drilling of a second <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> well -LRB- i.e., a buy-out of most of <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s interest in the well -RRB-, the terms of the `` farm out'' were in accordance with industry custom and the price was at or near market value. Thus there was no gift to <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>; nor can either the repurchase or the `` farm out,'' which both took place in 1984, reasonably be viewed as compenation to <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> for his efforts on <LOCATION> Neptune </LOCATION>'s behalf in 1979. As discussed in full in Section III. A. of this Report, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s receipt of the gift in excess of $ 100 from <PERSON> Moncrief </PERSON> violates House Rule XLIII, clauses 1 and 4; and consideration 5 of the Code of Ethics for Government Service His failure to disclose the gift violates House Rule XLIV.
