<NOTE>C. Wright's Publication and Marketing of ``Reflections of a Public</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Man''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 In early 1984, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> and his close friend <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> discussed producing a book of <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s earlier speeches, poems and writings which <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> and <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> testified would be sold at low cost to a very broad audience including college students and `` average citizens.'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> he wanted to give people an idea of what his personal feelings were on a number of subjects so that they could get to know the Majority Leader and next Speaker of the House. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> also discussed the book with his staff. <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> Cossolotto </PERSON>, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s congressional staff researcher and speech writer, testified that <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> first raised the subject of the book at a staff breakfast in February 1984. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> asked the staff to think about ways to market the book and suggested that when he gave a speech to a trade association or other group, he could sell the group books instead of taking an honorarium. Cossolotto testified that <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> explained to the staff that unlike honoraria, book royalties are exempt from the 30 percent maximum limit on outside earned income. Throughout 1984, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> had members of his staff collecting his old speeches and compiling, editing, typing and proofreading the manuscript for his book. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s staff obtained celebrity endorsements of the book for the back cover and selected a photograph of <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> for the front cover. <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> formed the <ORGANIZATION> Madison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION> company in 1984 as a division of <ORGANIZATION> Madison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>'s political consulting firm, for the purpose of publishing <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s book, `` Reflections of a Public Man.'' However, <PERSON> Madison </PERSON> <PERSON> Publishing </PERSON> did not `` publish'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s book. Nor has it published any other book. Madison Publishing designed the layout and printed the cover for <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s book. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> sent the book itself to be printed and assembled by <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Printing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> because, as he testified, <ORGANIZATION> Madison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION> did not have the capacity to print 20,000 copies. The Printing Center actually printed 19,068 books and reduced the charge to Madison Publishing accordingly. The final product was completed in early December 1984 and delivered in two installments on December 6 and 18, 1984. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> himself applied for and secured copyright protection for the book and hired a <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> real estate attorney to draft a `` royalty'' agreement between <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Madison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> supplied the attorney with specific provisions to be included in the agreement including the provisions for a 55 percent `` royalty.'' The agreement was executed on December 12, 1984, after 2,160 copies of the completed books had already been delivered to <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>.
