<HEAD>Ethics Reports Gives Opponents Ammunition, but Doesn't Strike Fatal
Blow</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Public airing of the ethics committee report on <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> provides his opponents with reams of political ammunition, but does not in itself strike a fatal blow. Democrats must move to quickly mold public opinion if the speaker is going to keep his leadership post, and <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s allies say having the facts on the table can help. The Committee on Standards of Official Conduct released a voluminous report by its special counsel and charged the speaker with 69 instances of violating House rules. The report provides sometimes embarrassing details of the financial benefits he received from friendships with two <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> businessmen. One, <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, gave <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> unusually high royalties he published the speaker's book, `` Reflections of a Public Man.'' With fifty-five cents of every dollar going to <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, the committee said it appeared that the speaker was using bulk sales of the paperback to evade <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> limits on outside income from speeches. The second friend, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON>, had a business partnership with the speaker. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Betty </PERSON>, benefited from the free use of a condominium and a car, and an $ 18,000 annual salary to Mrs. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>. House members are looking at the committee report on two political levels: within the institution and in their home districts. Within the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, release of the report Monday caused members to begin focusing on their own situations. `` We have to deal with it on a very specific level,'' said <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Frost </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, a <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> ally who contends lawmakers will make independent judgments despite pressure at home. `` I think members do n't want to be stampeded on this, one way or another,'' he said. <PERSON> Frost </PERSON> said members confronted with the committee's findings will find them troubling because of their broad implications. For example, it decided that <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON> had an interest in legislation using a standard so broad that anyone with wealth would fall in the same category, he contended, a situation that could snare many lawmakers. `` I think members will look at this in a serious way and say, ` Is this fair?''' he said. Outside of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, Democrats must persuade the public that the violations <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> is accused of are mostly technical and not really unethical. They ca n't afford to wait for the committee to render a verdict on whether <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> should be found guilty and punished. The initial rush of publicity was seen by virtually everyone as negative for <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, but <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> leaders argued that as they rebut the specific charges the public will come to believe that <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> is being held to an unjust standard. Rep. <PERSON> Beryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Campaign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said that `` once people clearly understand ... then you get an entirely different feel and reaction.'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> himself must also be convincing. `` If the speaker is well received in the country, and what he says is resonant with the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> public, he improves his chances,'' said Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Spratt </PERSON>, D-S.C. Further, the report itself is not a conviction. That could only be done by the full <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and even if that were to occur, it would be up to the Democrats who elected him to decide whether <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> has become an unsupportable political liability. With few exceptions, Republicans greeted the release with sounds of deference and respect to the process set up to investigate a fellow member. Despite the fact that the campaign to investigate <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s finances was kicked off by one of their own, Rep. <PERSON> Newt </PERSON> <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, the Republicans tried to portray themselves as above the fray. A key element in their strategy to wrest control of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> away from the <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> is to portray the <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> as the party of corruption and themselves as its enemy. `` The best politics for Republicans is no evidence of politics at all,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>. Some Democrats scoffed at the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> tactic. It was `` bipartisan, non-partisan garbage,'' said Rep. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Traficant </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>. `` Let there be no mistake, today in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> the party lines are being drawn in indelible ink.'' The verdict on <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> from the ethics committee may be technical and not so clear as the party lines. But when that comes, some weeks down the road, the public verdict may have already come in. `` We'll be opening our own mail for a while,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, D-Mont.
</TEXT>
