 The agreement provided that <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> would receive $ 3.25 -LRB- nearly 55 percent -RRB- of the $ 5.95 list price on all retail sales of the book. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> would receive $ 2.70 from which he would pay all printing and marketing expenses. Such `` royalty'' payments are unheard of in the publishing industry. In fact, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s previous royalty contracts with three major publishers provided for standard industry royalties ranging from 10 percent to 15 percent, depending upon sales. <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> <PERSON> Janklow </PERSON>, an expert on the publishing industry, testified that no rational publisher would agree to a 55 percent royalty on list price because it could not make a profit. <PERSON> Janklow </PERSON> also testified that in his opinion as literary agent for <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, Sen. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Schmidt </PERSON>, <PERSON> Sidney </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheldon </PERSON> and <PERSON> Danielle </PERSON> <PERSON> Steele </PERSON>, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s book was not commercially publishable. Although the agreement also provided that <ORGANIZATION> Madison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION> would publish and market the book, in fact, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> and his staff provided many of the ordinary services of a publisher and made the most significant contribution to marketing efforts. ... In this instance, <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> designed the layout and printed the cover of the book. He hired others to typeset and print the book itself. All other aspects of book production were performed by <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> or his staff. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> also sent out 300 to 500 letters soliciting orders for the book and employed 12 to 15 people for four hours a day during one week to make telephone solicitations from voter registration lists. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> arranged an autograph party, one or two newspaper advertisements and an appearance by <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> on the Larry King Show. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>'s marketing efforts resulted in precious few sales to `` average citizens.'' In fact, <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> testified that he never intended to sell the book to bookstores where average people could buy them because bookstores would only purchase at the discount price of $ 3.00 per copy. `` That does n't leave you much room.'' The real focus of the marketing effort for `` Reflections of a Public Man'' was on bulk sales to trade associations and other groups. Almost 98 percent of all sales of `` Reflections of a Public Man'' were bulk sales of 15 or more books. In some instances, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s staff informed various groups <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> spoke to that because he had already reached the maximum limit on outside earned income for that year, he would not be able to keep an honoraium offered to him. The staff then recommended that instead of paying <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> an honorarium, the organization could purchase books for the same amount. For example, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> gave a lecture in October 1984 at <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. The University paid <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> an honorarium of $ 3,000 in addition to his expenses, but was subsequently informed by <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s staff that he would be unable to accept the honorarium. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s staff suggested that the University purchase 504 books for $ 3,000 in lieu of the honorarium. The University purchased the books and distributed most of them to students in its political science department. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> endorsed the $ 3,000 check over to <ORGANIZATION> Madison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>. Despite the change in the nature of the transaction, the University's records plainly list the $ 3,000 expenditure as an honorarium for <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s appearance. Instead of passing up $ 3,000 or donating it to charity, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> thus received a $ 1,650 `` royalty'' for his lecture at the University. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> also spoke at a <ORGANIZATION> Satellite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- `` SBCA'' -RRB- trade show in September 1985 just several weeks after <ORGANIZATION> SBCA </ORGANIZATION> had purchased 1,680 copies of `` Reflections of a Public Man'' for $ 10,000. <ORGANIZATION> SBCA </ORGANIZATION> testified that although it historically has paid honoraria and expenses to congressmen for their appearances, in this case <ORGANIZATION> SBCA </ORGANIZATION>'s legal counsel, who arranged for <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> to speak at the trade show, suggested that <ORGANIZATION> SBCA </ORGANIZATION> purchase the books instead. Thus <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> received a $ 5,500 `` royalty'' for his appearance before the <ORGANIZATION> SBCA </ORGANIZATION>. Not all bulk sales were in lieu of honoraria. For example, <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> arranged a sale of 2,000 books to the Teamsters for $ 12,200 paid out of the DRIVE Political Fund. The books were distributed to Teamster members. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> had not spoken at any Teamster event. In addition, <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Payte </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> real estate developer, testified that he wanted to give <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> a $ 5,000 gift and, in fact, had given a $ 5,000 check to <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> subsequently informed him that he could not accept the gift and returned the check to <LOCATION> Payte </LOCATION>. Payte continued to search for a way to give cash to <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> and shortly after receiving the first check back from <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, wrote a second $ 5,000 check, this time to Madison Systems for `` revision and distribution of <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s books.'' <PERSON> Payte </PERSON> testified that he expected to receive 1,000 copies of the revised edition of the book and, in fact, he made a second payment of $ 1,000 when he realized that $ 5,000 would not buy 1,000 copies of the $ 5.95 book. However, the book was never revised. Payte testified he received approximately 300 to 500 copies of the old book instead. No further accounting was made.
