<HEAD>Senate Takes Up S&amp;L Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> opened debate Monday on President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s slightly altered plan for bailing out savings and loan depositors, Republicans blamed <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Democrats for the bulk of costs. `` There's enough blame to go around, but if you want to single out one culprit, it's the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION>,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Jake </PERSON> <PERSON> Garn </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, the ranking Republican on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Garn </PERSON> said the bailout costs _ estimated at a minimum of $ 157 billion over the next 10 years _ would be only half as much if in 1986, the Democratic-controlled <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> had gone along with a Senate-approved measure to pump $ 15 billion into the <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L insurance funds to close insolvent thrifts then. `` The kindest thing I can say about the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> is only that it is totally irresponsible,'' <PERSON> Garn </PERSON> said, referring to action last week by a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee that would require S & amp; L owners to put up less of their own money to stay in business. Former S & amp; L regulators have blamed <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> for stalling the 1986 legislation on behalf of thrift operators in his state. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ethics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Monday cleared <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> of charges he improperly intervened with <ORGANIZATION> S </ORG