in the works, according to <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> aides, although none were offered or voted on Monday. Among them was one by Sen. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Pressler </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-S.D. </LOCATION>, that would stretch out to June 1994, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s June 1991 deadline for small <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L operators with loans of less than $ 100 million to effectively double the amount of their own money at risk. <PERSON> Pressler </PERSON> complained the bill provides `` a heavy advantage toward larger institutions'' by allowing them to stretch out to as long as 25 years good-will exemptions from the capital requirements. A spokeswoman for Sen. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, said he is considering proposing a variety of pro-consumer amendments. Other possible amendments include: _ Reinstating a funding plan authored by <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON>, who claims it would save $ 150 million a year <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON> effectively abandoned the plan last week under a veto threat by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> but Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said he assumes it will consume `` considerable debate'' over the next two days. _ Giving non-profit groups and local housing agencies a 90-day right of first refusal to purchase at `` appraised market prices'' residential property that has fallen into the government's hand through loan defaults to insolvent S & amp; Ls The amendment by Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON>, D-Mass., was defeated in the <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, where it was criticized by Sen. <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Gramm </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, as `` social engineering. Meanwhile, three consumers groups _ the <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANI