<HEAD>New Report Sees Unfair Trade Barriers by Japanese</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> lawmakers said Monday that a draft <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report on Japanese barriers to imports of American wood products should bolster the case for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sanctions. The draft report, obtained Monday, says <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> uses unfair trade practices, including high tariffs, subisidies and even building codes that require the use of nails that can crack <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> plywood, to protect their mills from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> imports. The report said Japanese tariffs and other barriers were designed to bolster imports of raw logs and discourage imports of finished products. Despite earlier progress in opening some parts of the Japanese market, the report said barriers remain which impede <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> imports, and it said the government of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has refused to enter into a new round of talks. The report said `` it is unlikely that any further concessions will be forthcoming unless additional <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> efforts are made. Such concessions would only be obtained if there were a clear incentive or at the least inclusion of these barriers in the high priority of issues to be resolved by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Japanese governments.'' Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Packwood </PERSON>, R-Ore., who requested the study more than a year ago, said it should bolster the case for imposing trade sanctions against <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> unless the barriers are removed Rep. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyden </PERSON>, D-Ore., who had earlier called for sanctions, said in a letter to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Representative <PERSON> Carla </PERSON> <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> the report `` strongly supports'' a need for aggressive action by the administration Last month, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> asked <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> to rule the Japanese were engaging in unfair trade practices involving forest products and, if negotiations failed to resolve the dispute after 18 months, to impose sanctions. The association has estimated that exports of finished <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forest products to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> could increase $ 1.2 billion annually if the barriers were lifted.
