<HEAD>Lethal Barrages Pound Beirut, Surrounding Area</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with more killed, injured, MOVES
UP casualty count since renewed fighting broke out. Pick up 5th pvs, `Tens
of ...' DELETES 19th graf, `Police put ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Residents sought shelter Monday in basements and bunkers during citywide shelling that killed at least 45 people in three days and touched off international appeals for a cease-fire. The rocket and artillery barrages slammed into both the Christian and Moslem sectors during intensified fighting in and around <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> between Christian army units and an alliance of Druse militiamen and Syrian troops. The dead included <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s ambassador to <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Aristegui </PERSON>, and his father-in-law, prominent Lebanese poet <PERSON> Tewfic </PERSON> <PERSON> Youssef </PERSON> <PERSON> Awwad </PERSON>. Warrant Officer <PERSON> Youssef </PERSON> <PERSON> Bitar </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Lebanese </LOCATION> army's top explosives specialist, said on Christian-controlled <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lebanon </ORGANIZATION> radio the ambassador's residence was hit by a Syrian shell Police also said 175 people were wounded in renewed bombardments that broke out late Saturday. Police put the toll in 41 days of fighting at 262 killed and 932 wounded. The overwhelming majority of the victims have been civilians. Tens of thousands of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> residents had hardly emerged from their shelters Monday morning during a brief lull when guns and rocket launchers thundered back into action, sending them back underground. Many were trapped without water or electricity. Smoldering cars lay charred Monday in streets littered with glass shards and severed power cables. Hundreds of fashionable boutiques were gutted. Many buildings burned down because firefighters had no water. Only a few bakeries opened Monday morning, but there was not enough bread to go around. `` Please, please. I need five loaves. I have five children that I have to feed,'' shouted housewife <PERSON> Amina </PERSON> <PERSON> Shehab </PERSON> outside a bakery in Moslem west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. The baker yelled back: `` I've less than three dozen loaves, and there are many other people who want to eat as well. I can only give you two loaves.'' `` <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s apocalypse persists,'' <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s independent daily <ORGANIZATION> An-Nahar </ORGANIZATION> said in a front-page editorial Monday. The prime minister of the <ORGANIZATION> Moslem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> in the split government, <PERSON> Salim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON>, said Monday he reached agreement with French Humanitarian Assistance Minister <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kouchner </PERSON> to evacuate more wounded civilians. A source close to <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON> later said Moslem victims of the fighting would be evacuated to a French hospital ship on Tuesday if security conditions permit. Fourteen Christian victims were ferried to a French boat from the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> port of <LOCATION> Jounieh </LOCATION> on Friday. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>, Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> appealed for an end to the confrontation, which has developed into one of the bloodiest rounds of the 14-year-old civil war. Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> urged the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> nations to use their influence to bring about an immediate cease-fire. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> deputy spokesman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Boucher </PERSON> said, `` All parties, including <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, which is a direct participant in the artillery exchanges ... must stop the fighting.'' <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s foreign minister, <PERSON> Sheik </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabah </PERSON>, called for an emergency <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> council meeting. The battles began after Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>, the head of the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION>, ordered his forces to blockade several ports controlled by Moslem militiamen. <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> rallied to the militiamens' aid, and <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> pledged to expel the estimated 40,000 Syrian troops from <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> The <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> invited <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> to send in its forces as peacekeepers in 1976. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>, in an interview released Monday, accused the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> of covering up for Syrian attacks in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is undoubtedly trying to solve the <LOCATION> Palestinian-Israeli </LOCATION> or the <LOCATION> Arab-Israeli </LOCATION> problem at <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s expense and is thus sponsoring this dirty Syrian role in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>,'' he was quoted as saying by the London-based newsletter <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mirror </LOCATION> Text of the interview was sent by telex to The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bahrain </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials were trying to portray Lebanese strife as a problem between Moslems and Christians, but he said it is caused by occupation by Syrian and <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> forces, according to the interview. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> occupies a self-proclaimed `` security zone'' up to 10 miles deep in south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>.
