<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A former government employee went to court Monday seeking to halt construction of apartments and an underground garage on a site he claims was a nuclear dump. <PERSON> Oleg </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyanin </PERSON> said the site, along the <LOCATION> Leninsky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Prospekt </LOCATION> thoroughfare in south <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, was used to bury wastes from uranium processing at the beginning of the Soviet nuclear effort in the 1940s. No official evidence has been released that the dump exists and there is no evidence of nuclear leaks, the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> man said in a telephone interview. But he claimed scientists involved in the nuclear effort have pinpointed the spot and several others as the sites of nuclear dumps. `` We're sure there's a map, perhaps several made at different intervals of where and what is in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Lyanin </PERSON>, a former negotiator and translator for the Ministry of Foreign Trade. He said he filed his first court documents April 10 asking that the case be turned over to prosecutors for investigation of possible criminal charges. He said that request was granted three days later. According to a law passed after the <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> nuclear accident, disturbing buried radioactive waste is punishable by up to 10 years in prison, according to <LOCATION> Lyanin </LOCATION>. He said that in his court appearance Monday he asked the court to halt construction of the garage and apartments to `` leave trouble where it lies.'' There has been much greater concern in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> about nuclear safety since the <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> nuclear power plant disaster in April 1986. At least 31 people perished when a reactor exploded. The site for the garage and apartments in southern <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> is less than a half-mile from the <ORGANIZATION> Anglo-American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sch