<HEAD>House Passes Hatch Act Change</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> gave overwhelming approval Monday to a measure that would repeal major portions of the Hatch Act and allow federal <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> employees to participate in partisan political activity on their own time. But despite the 297-90 <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> vote, final enactment into law is far from certain. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approved an almost identical bill last year, but it died in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. The administration is opposed to the bill and Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> has said he will recommend a veto should it reach President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s desk. Nonetheless, the measure was pushed strongly by various unions representing federal workers and their leaders were quick to praise the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members who voted for it. `` This is not a political party issue ... it's a political freedom issue,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tobias </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>. `` We urge the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to join the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> in standing firmly on the side of rights for federal workers.'' However, <PERSON> Tobias </PERSON>' statement did not suggest there was anything more than an `` excellent possibility'' the measure will pass the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. The bill would: _ Allow federal employees to run for partisan political office on their own time, without taking a leave of absence unless campaigning would interfere with performance of their duties _ Permit employees to request unpaid leave to run for office and says leave must be granted unless the agency they work for determines they can not be spared _ Allow federal employees to manage political campaigns and raise campaign money during off-duty hours The measure would clarify and, in many cases, strengthen current Hatch Act prohibitions against using a federal position for political purposes. In a letter to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said enactment of provisions in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> will `` would lead to a tragic repoliticization of the federal workforce.'' Aside from concerns about specifics of the bill, wrote <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>, the overall effect on public perception of the fairness of government dealing `` might well be devastaging.'' `` For example, if it appears that a candidate of Party A has misappropirated funds, it will not inspire confidence to learn that the local <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney's office charged with investigating the allegation is headed by that candidate's campaign manager,'' he said.
