<HEAD>WASHN: was made.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Some bulk purchasers did not even want the books they paid for. For example, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> addressed the annual meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Mid-Continent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Gas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Mid-Continent purchased $ 1,000 worth of <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s book in lieu of paying him an honorarium, but asked to receive only three books. Mid-Continent suggested that the remaining books be distributed to libraries and other public institutions of <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s choice. There are no records reflecting the requested distribution. The Select Committee on Ethics interpreted Rule XLVII, clause 1 in Advisory Opinion No. 13 which makes it clear that the limitations on outside earned income may not be avoided by the mere characterization of a payment. `` In all cases, the real facts will control.'' -LRB- Select Committee on Ethics, Advisory Opinion No. 13, Ethics Manual p. 179. -RRB- In this case, the facts reveal that <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> compiled a series of previous speeches and writings into a commercially unpublishable manuscript. His good friend <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> formed a publishing company for the purpose of producing the book and entering into a so-called `` royalty'' agreement inordinately favorable to <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>. Together they sold the book almost exclusively to lobbyists, persons interested in legislation and other interest groups in order to provide income to <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>. The resulting income does not therefore become `` royalty'' income just because <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> calls himself a `` publisher'' and claims to pay `` royalties'' on book sales. The `` royalty'' contract was not an arms-length agreement between an author and his publisher, but a joint business venture _ a means by which <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> could help his friend <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> obtain money in excess of congressional limitations. Receipts from sales of <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s book should thus be characterized as outside earned income, not copyright royalties, and subject to the limits and reporting requirements for such income. As Advisory Opinion No. 13 makes clear, income a member earns through his own personal efforts is earned income for purposes of Rule XLVII, clause 1 even when the income is first paid to a corporation and then distributed to the member. In this matter, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> earned income from the books through his performance of publisher's duties including the marketing of the book. However, whether or not the income from sales of the book may be considered `` royalties,'' when books are allegedly `` sold'' to lobbyists or interest groups, but no books are delivered to those groups in exchange for their payments, the books retained are `` gifts'' received from persons with an interest in legislation before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Those books are also `` gifts'' when the group `` donates'' the books to a library or institution of <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s choice Furthermore, where the books are purchased in lieu of paying a customary fee for a speech or appearance, the payment received is an `` honorarium,'' in the form of a `` royalty.'' The term `` honorarium'' is defined to mean `` the payment of something of value ` accepted as consideration for an appearance, speech, or article.''' -LRB- Ethics manual, p. 83, quoting 11 C.F.R. 110.12 -LRB- b -RRB-; see also 2 U.S.C. 31-1. -RRB- In this case, the `` royalty'' was itself the honorarium paid for <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s appearance. Thus as discussed in full in Section III. C. of this Report, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s receipts of outside earned income, including honoraria, in excess of 30 percent of his congressional salary are violations of House Rule XLVII, clause 1. In addition, gifts exceeding $ 100 from lobbyists and other groups with interests in legislation before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> are violations of <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> rule XLIII, clause 4. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s receipt of an honorarium in excess of the $ 2,000 limit imposed by 2 U.S.C 441i is a violation of that law. Finally, his failures to disclose the receipts of income, gifts and honoraria are violations of House Rule XLIV. We found no evidence that campaign funds were used to produce the book.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>D. Wright's Use of Government Resources to Produce and Market ``Reflections
of a Public Man''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> used members of his staff to compile, type, proofread, edit, and market his book, `` Reflections of a Public Man.'' The book was <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s own project, from which he personally received income. <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> Cossolotto </PERSON>, a writer and researcher on <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s staff, testified that he spent about 200 hours preparing the book for printing. Other members of the staff had more limited roles in the preparation of the book, e.g., <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynam </PERSON>, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s Chief of Staff, solicited the quotes for the back cover of the book and also participated to some extent in marketing the book; <PERSON> Charmayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Marsh </PERSON>, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s Press Secretary, helped to select the photograph used on the cover of the book; <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Grisso </PERSON> occasionally entered passages for the book onto the word processor; <PERSON> Dorothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Biard </PERSON>, the office librarian, assisted in gathering and locating material; and <PERSON> Cathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s Executive Assistant and Scheduler, also participated in marketing the book to various groups <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> gave speeches to in 1984 and 1985. In addition, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> used other government resources, including a computer, to complete the manuscript.
