 <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> has ordered all soccer matches suspended for a week following the stabbing of a goalie by fans during a riot last week, officials said. In <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, a newspaper reported Monday that 18 people were injured on April 7 when thousands of fans made a rush for tickets to a soccer match. The reports followed the deaths of 94 British fans during a mad rush Saturday at a soccer match in <LOCATION> Sheffield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. The president of the Algerian <ORGANIZATION> Football </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Mohamed </PERSON> <PERSON> Baghdadi </PERSON>, said matches were suspended Saturday and would not resume for a week. The statement Sunday came in response to violence at a match the day before between <PERSON> Constantine </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Setif </LOCATION> that left two players injured. <LOCATION> Setif </LOCATION> goalie <PERSON> Antar </PERSON> <PERSON> Osmani </PERSON> was circled by about 100 fans and then stabbed in the abdomen. He said he had never seen `` such savagery'' during his 14-year career. It was not clear why <PERSON> Osmani </PERSON> was attacked. <PERSON> Baghdadi </PERSON> said the suspension should be used for `` meditation, consciousness-raising and a call to responsibility.'' In <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>, the government-run newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Young </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> said fans were injured during a run on tickets April 7 for a Union of European Football Associations semifinal game between the <ORGANIZATION> Dynamo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dresden </ORGANIZATION> soccer club and <LOCATION> Stuttgart </LOCATION> of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. The newspaper printed a letter by students of <LOCATION> Dresden </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Technical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, which said the ticket sale began suddenly around midnight, causing `` chaotic conditions. It also printed a reply by <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Stehr </PERSON>, security chief for the <LOCATION> Dresden </LOCATION> club, which said 18 people were hurt. <PERSON> Stehr </PERSON>'s letter said the injuries were caused by `` inconsiderate behavior and by the pushing and shoving of the unreasonable -LRB- fans -RRB-.'' He said the club also would revise the way it sold tickets. The newspaper earlier reported that some fans had been camping for two days for tickets to Wednesday's game. The students' letter said the box offices `` opened suddenly and prematurely,'' suggesting that the injuries were caused by a crush of thousands of fans trying to get into the line when officials began selling tickets eight hours ahead of the announced time. All 38,000 tickets were sold by the morning, the newspaper said.
