<HEAD>Shamir Makes Unannounced Visit to Hungary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> made an unannounced visit to <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION> reported the two countries apparently planned to renew diplomatic ties. A one-sentence announcement by the official Hungarian news agency <ORGANIZATION> MTI </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> arrived in <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>. It did not specify whether the visit was private or official and gave no other details. In <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, a <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> aide confirmed the rare unannnounced trip and said the prime minister is due back on Tuesday. He refused to elaborate on the purpose of the visit. The visit was not announced in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> before the midnight <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio report, which said the two nations apparently planned to renew diplomatic ties. The report did not elaborate. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> would be the first East European nation to resume full ties with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> since all Soviet bloc nations except <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> broke relations during the Middle East War in 1967. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> was accompanied to <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> by Justice Minister <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Meridor </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> officials said, speaking on condition of anonymity. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> made what was billed as a private visit to <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> in September when he met with <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Karoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON>. Upon his return, he announced <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> had agreed to renew full diplomatic ties with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. Premier <PERSON> Miklos </PERSON> <PERSON> Nemeth </PERSON> has said he expected full diplomatic relations to be restored between the two countries by June. Earlier Monday, the <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> announced that Hungarian and <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> officials had set up two joint committees to improve commercial ties between the two countries as a step toward normalizing diplomatic relations. This was agreed during a four-day visit to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> by <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s deputy foreign minister, <PERSON> Laszlo </PERSON> <PERSON> Kovacs </PERSON>, which ended Sunday <PERSON> Kovacs </PERSON> said last week that <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> would like to `` accelerate'' the process of normalizing relations.
