<HEAD>Bush Choice Says He Wasn't Involved in Iran-Contra</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Reginald </PERSON> <PERSON> Bartholomew </PERSON>, who was <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> in 1985 when <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> arms were exchanged for the release of an American hostage, told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Monday he knew `` precious little'' about the operation. <PERSON> Bartholomew </PERSON>, President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s choice for undersecretary of state for security affairs, said that in September 1985, he was directed by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> to make arrangements to receive a hostage and get him out of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> quickly and safely. On Sept. 14, 1985 a group of pro-Iranian Lebanese extremists released the Rev. <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Wier </PERSON>, one of six American hostages then being held in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bartholomew </PERSON> said he reported the <ORGANIZATION> NSC </ORGANIZATION> directive to the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and made the requested logistical arrangements. But he said he was not told, and did not know, that <PERSON> Wier </PERSON> was released in exchange for Israeli shipments to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> of 508 U.S.-made TOW antitank missiles. And he said he also did not know that <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON>, then a <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> lieutenant colonel attached to the <ORGANIZATION> NSC </ORGANIZATION> staff, had visited <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. `` If <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> was in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> when I was there as ambassador, I did not know it,'' <PERSON> Bartholomew </PERSON> said. `` I knew precious little about the organization of the whole affair or who was involved.'' `` I was not involved in Iran-Contra in any way,'' <PERSON> Bartholomew </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bartholomew </PERSON> was interviewed in private but was never called as a public witness during the various investigations into the Iran-Contra affair. <PERSON> Bartholomew </PERSON>, 53, has served in a number of <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> policy positions. He has been <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> since 1986. The <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> is expected to recommend <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> confirmation of the <LOCATION> Bartholomew </LOCATION> nomination, with final action likely later this week.
