<HEAD>Sinhalese Militants Kill Four Soldiers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sinhalese militants detonated explosives buried in the road and blew up an army truck on Monday in <LOCATION> southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>, killing four soldiers and wounding eight, government officials said. The vehicle was on patrol in <LOCATION> Embilipitiya </LOCATION>, 80 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>, reported the officials, who can not be identified under briefing rules. They said an attacker was killed during a raid by Sinhalese extremists on a police station in <LOCATION> Kurunagala </LOCATION> district, 85 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>. The violence came one day before expiration of a one-week cease-fire announced by President <PERSON> Ranasinghe </PERSON> <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON>. The truce was part of a peace package the government offered to Sinhalese and Tamil extremists in a bid to end six years of ethnic violence that has claimed at least 12,600 lives. Left-wing Sinhalese militants rejected the offer, but the largest Tamil militant group, the <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tamil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eelam </ORGANIZATION>, agreed on Saturday to hold talks with the government. <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> asked the Tamil rebels to pick a team for talks aimed at ending their campaign for a separate Tamil homeland. The Tamil acceptance came after at least 100 people died last week in attacks that were blamed on the rebels. The Tamils, most of them Hindus, comprise 18 percent of this island nation's 16 million people. The Tamils began the separatist campaign in 1983, saying the majority <PERSON> Sinhalese </PERSON> discriminated against them in jobs and education. Sinhalese, mostly Buddhists, make up 75 percent of the population and control the government and the military. The Tamil <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> rejected an India-sponsored July 1987 accord that gave Tamils limited autonomy, complaining it did not meet their demands for self-rule. <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> lies just south of the <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> peninsula </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> became involved because its own 60 million Tamils were sympathetic to the rebel cause. The accord triggered a violent Sinhalese backlash. Sinhalese extremists, who belong to the <ORGANIZATION> Marxist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, said the agreement conceded too much to the Tamils and vowed to kill anyone who supported it. The Front has been blamed for more than 2,500 political killings since January. Most of the victims were government officials and security personnel.
