<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> reports said Israeli soldiers killed two teen-agers Monday, the latest victims in a surge of violence that has cost the lives of 12 Palestinians in the occupied territories in five days. <PERSON> Rafideh </PERSON> <PERSON> Khalili </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON> <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Laban </PERSON>, 13, and <PERSON> Kayed </PERSON> <PERSON> Mousa </PERSON> <PERSON> Salama </PERSON>, 14, were shot to death in stone-throwing protests during funerals for earlier victims, the reports said. Ms. <PERSON> Laban </PERSON> was killed in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Salama </PERSON> in the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. A third Palestinian was electrocuted Monday when he climbed a power pole and tried to raise an outlawed <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> flag, and a fourth died of earlier injuries. Hospital officials said a 50-year-old woman of a family named <PERSON> Ayat </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Zeytoun </LOCATION> district was killed by a bullet through the heart and a male member of the family, aged betweem 25 and 30, also was killed. A young woman in her 20s was reported in serious condition and two children aged 2 and 12 also were reported wounded. No further details were given and circumstances of the shooting were unclear. The army said there was no army activity or gunfire in <LOCATION> Zeytoun </LOCATION>. Arab sources said 10 Palestinians were wounded in other clashes. Two Israelis were reported injured in scattered stoning incidents in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>. Jewish settlers in a tiny enclave in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> city of <LOCATION> Hebron </LOCATION> said they were creating a mobile armed militia and using attack dogs to defend their houses against <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> stonings. `` We've decided to create a trained group of people that would not interfere with the army but will reach troublesome spots and help defend Jewish houses in <LOCATION> Hebron </LOCATION>,'' settler leader <PERSON> Aharon </PERSON> <PERSON> Domb </PERSON> said on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio. `` We'll also secure Jewish houses by using guard and attack dogs, to be unleashed only in emergency situations.'' In <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, a Palestinian human rights group appealed to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> to urge an independent investigation of the killings of four Palestinians during a border police raid last week on <LOCATION> Nahalin </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> village. Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> rejected <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> demands for at least a partial army withdrawal as a condition for agreeing to elections in the occupied lands. `` There is nothing to talk about regarding changes in the deployment of Israeli army forces,'' <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> said on <ORGANIZATION> army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION>. `` This deployment is necessary to maintain order, and order is necessary for elections.'' Radio reports said <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> went before a parliamentary committee Monday and defended his election plan against critics in his own right-wing <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> bloc who said elections could be the first step to creating a Palestinian state. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> proposes the elections to choose Palestinians to negotiate with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. `` I will talk, and discuss, and argue with my friends. I hope I'll convince them that although these doubts have some basis ... we can overcome such things,'' the prime minister said on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> television. `` If those implementing the plan decide that there will be no <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> state here, I'm saying there will be no Palestinian state.'' <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> told the committee <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> election candidates would have to agree to certain limits in advance, including rejecting a <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> state, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio said. He also said he opposes international supervision of the vote. <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> on Sunday demanded such supervision and the withdrawal of <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> troops as a condition for elections. Palestinians in the occupied lands hinted a partial withdrawal would be a step toward the polls. On Monday, soldiers fired as hundreds of <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> youths threw stones, waved outlawed <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> flags and set tires ablaze during a funeral procession in Dheishe refugee camp near the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> town of <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> reports said. Ms. <PERSON> Laban </PERSON> was shot in the forehead and died en route to a hospital, the reports said. In Jabaliya refugee camp in the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, troops fired on stone-throwing youths after the funeral of a 50-year-old man who died earlier Monday, reportedly from a beating by soldiers, <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> witnesses said. <PERSON> Salama </PERSON> died at <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Shifa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> after a bullet sliced an artery in his leg, hospital officials said. In the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> village of <PERSON> Bani </PERSON> <PERSON> Suheila </PERSON>, 21-year-old <PERSON> Mahmoud </PERSON> <PERSON> Shihada </PERSON> <PERSON> Abu-Shad </PERSON> was electrocuted while trying to display a <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> flag, <PERSON> Arab 