<FIRST>u w BC-Wright-Phelan 5thadd   04-17 0838</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Wright-Phelan, 5th add,830</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHN: Rule XLIV.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 In 1981, <PERSON> Mallightco </PERSON> loaned the <ORGANIZATION> Wrights </ORGANIZATION> an additional $ 37,000. Over the period 1981 through 1983, the <ORGANIZATION> Wrights </ORGANIZATION> and the <PERSON> Mallicks </PERSON> made regular payments on their loans from the proceeds of their other investments. However, beginning in 1984, the <ORGANIZATION> Wrights </ORGANIZATION> made little progress in reducing the outstanding principal balance and, in fact, were not meeting their interest payments. The debt continued to accrue interest; <PERSON> Mallightco </PERSON> never demanded payment from the Wrights or took any steps to collect the debt. Mallightco distributed several dividends to its shareholders in 1986 and 1987. Despite the <ORGANIZATION> Wrights </ORGANIZATION>' failure to make significant payments on their loans, the company distributed $ 59,000 in cash to the <ORGANIZATION> Wrights </ORGANIZATION> as dividends. While the <PERSON> Mallicks </PERSON> also received dividends during this period, all dividends to the Mallicks were paid in the form of credits against their outstanding debts to the company until their loans were completely repaid in 1987. On June 9, 1988, the <ORGANIZATION> Wrights </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- through the <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr </PERSON>. Blind Trust formed in October 1987 -RRB- sold their Mallightco shares back to the company for $ 350,000, the alleged market value of the shares at the time of sale. The price consisted of $ 230,000 cash and a $ 120,000 unsecured, five-year, 10 percent interest-bearing note subordinate to all present and future debt of <LOCATION> Mallightco </LOCATION>. The Wrights paid back most of their outstanding loan balance, then $ 80,000, from the cash received from the sale. Approximately $ 12,700 in accured interest was forgiven in the transaction between <LOCATION> Mallightco </LOCATION> and the Blind Trust. It appears that the <ORGANIZATION> Wrights </ORGANIZATION> received greater benefit from their interest in <LOCATION> Mallightco </LOCATION> than did the Mallicks since the <ORGANIZATION> Wrights </ORGANIZATION> had the use of a substantial amount of cash provided by the Mallicks. However, although no effort was made to collect the <ORGANIZATION> Wrights </ORGANIZATION>' loans from <LOCATION> Mallightco </LOCATION>, those loans did accrue interest at the rate of approximately 10 percent per year and were ultimately paid back almost entirely. Although $ 12,700 in interest was not paid back, that transaction occurred between <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON> and the trustee of <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s Blind Trust. Special Outside Counsel assumes that <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> was unaware of this gift to his Blind Trust and will rectify the account with <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON> when the gift is made known to him. Thus <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> ultimately paid for the use of the money he borrowed and has apparently not violated any law or ethical standard with respect to his Mallightco investment. On the other hand, we believe that <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> violated House Rules with respect to his indirect receipt of and failure to report additional gifts from the Mallicks bestowed in the form of salary paid to <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> by <PERSON> Mallightco </PERSON>; free housing to the <ORGANIZATION> Wrights </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> from 1979 through March 1988; and the use of a 1979 <LOCATION> Cadillac </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Seville </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> from 1983 until approximately February 1989. <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> began working for <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON> in 1979 as a part-time consultant for <ORGANIZATION> Mallick </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Properties </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> which hired Mrs. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> to help <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON> expand his real estate ventures into areas of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> beyond <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>. Mrs. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> earned $ 18,000 per year for her part-time work on a brochure entitled `` The Mallick Community Concept''; for market studies of <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>; and for her access to officials and other key people in the <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION> areas. Although it is impossible to determine how much time Mrs. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> devoted to her employment with <ORGANIZATION> Mallick </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Properties </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, it does appear that she did identifiable work on projects arguably within her expertise which may have been worth $ 18,000 a year to the company. On January 1, 1981, Mrs. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> went on the payroll of <LOCATION> Mallightco </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> at a salary of $ 1,500 per month. According to <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON>, Mrs. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> was hired as a consultant to seek out new investment opportunities for <LOCATION> Mallightco </LOCATION>. However, Mrs. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, formerly on the staff of the Subcommittee on Investigations and Oversight of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, had no education or prior experience in investment analysis or financial counseling. She performed few, if any, services to <LOCATION> Mallightco </LOCATION> which has no record of any work product she created. Furthermore, although <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON> testified that Mrs. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> `` assisted'' him and `` advised'' him, he could not articulate what valuable services she performed. He testified to research she did on several investment opportunities during the four years she was paid by <PERSON> Mallightco </PERSON>, but could not produce any research reports or even point to one investment Mrs. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> researched which was ultimately made by the company. Moreover, although <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON> was the one responsible for making investment decisions and both he and his assistant, <PERSON> Pamela </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, performed services of value for <PERSON> Mallightco </PERSON>, neither <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON> nor <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> received a salary from <LOCATION> Mallightco </LOCATION>. In fact, Mrs. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s salary was <PERSON> Mallightco </PERSON>'s greatest expense The company frequently had to borrow money from the <ORGANIZATION> Mallick </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> or other <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON> entities in order to pay Mrs. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s salary. Ultimately, <PERSON> Mallightco </PERSON> could not continue the expense; Mrs. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s salary was suspended as of December 31, 1984. Thus from 1981 through 1984, Mrs. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s salary was a gift from <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON>.
