<FIRST>u a AM-GreekLibel     04-17 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greek Libel,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>Papandreou Takes Time Magazine to Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Greek Premier <PERSON> Andreas </PERSON> <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON> filed a libel lawsuit Monday accusing <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION> of defaming him in a story that suggested he took millions of dollars in payoffs, his American lawyer said. The lawsuit was announced here by lawyer <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Boudin </PERSON>, who said the lawsuit was filed in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> because the story was more damaging abroad than in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. He conceded, however, that another factor was that it is easier for a public figure to make a case under English libel law than under American. The Time story, which concerned allegations of financial wrongdoing at a Greek bank that have rocked the <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON> government since last fall, was on the cover of the magazine's March 13 international edition A similar story ran in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> edition, but it was not the cover story. The articles quoted former Greek bank president <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Koskotas </PERSON>, who is jailed in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> and fighting extradition to <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, as saying he passed millions from the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crete </ORGANIZATION> to <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON> and other figures in the premier's Socialist government. <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON> has been <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>'s premier since 1981. His government is up for re-election in June, but the banking scandal and the 70-year premier's open affair with a 34-year-old former airline stewardess have hurt his standing among voters, according to recent polls. <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON> has denounced the Time article as part of an international conspiracy to topple his government. <PERSON> Boudin </PERSON> said <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON> would ask for `` a considerable, reasonable sum'' in damages from Time, but said the amount has n't been decided He said clearing <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON>'s name was the main reason for the lawsuit, launched only after Time failed to respond to a demand for an public apology and retraction. Time promised in a statement to `` vigorously defend'' itself. `` What is most alarming about the announcement of this lawsuit is the inescapable conclusion that Prime Minister <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON> is suing the messenger because he wishes to discredit the message,'' the magazine said in a statement. `` Such a suit, just by being brought, disregards a central role of the press in a free, democratic society _ which is to make important information available to the public. Time magazine will take whatever steps are necessary to fight the allegations of this lawsuit and defend its right to report news and information it deems in the public interest,'' the statement said. <PERSON> Boudin </PERSON> said he could not recall another case in which a head of state sued for libel, although there have been a number of cases brought by highly placed public figures in recent years, including the lawsuit filed against Time by <PERSON> Ariel </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON>, the former Israeli defense minister. In that case, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> jury found in 1985 that Time had erred but had not acted with malice and therefore did not have to pay damages. In <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON> need only show that the story written about him was defamatory and injured his reputation, while the magazine has the task of proving that what it wrote was true, <PERSON> Boudin </PERSON> said. In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON> would have to show not only that <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> wrote untruths but that it acted with malice. Besides New York-based Time, the lawsuit filed in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> names as defendants Time-Life branches in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION>, and the writer of the article, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Ajemian </PERSON>. Time wrote that <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON> had refused to be interviewed or to answer questions the magazine submitted before publishing the article. But <PERSON> Boudin </PERSON> countered that the questions were of a general sort about government integrity and not about any specific accusations of wrongdoing by <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON>.
