<HEAD>Snow In Montana, Thunderstorms In The Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Western Montana got at least 4 inches of spring snow Monday as showers and thunderstorms fell across the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> ahead of a cold front that dropped temperatures 12 degrees in an hour. Showers and thunderstorms fell from <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>. In northern <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, thunderstorms produced hail a quarter-inch in diameter near <LOCATION> Gary </LOCATION>, South Bend and <LOCATION> Mentone </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>'s morning snowstorm dropped 2 inches of snow in an hour in the capital of <PERSON> Helena </PERSON>. Four inches fell in <LOCATION> Missoula </LOCATION> in six hours. The cold front brought sharply cooler weather to the upper <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> and the northern and central Plains. Temperatures Monday afternoon were about 30 degrees lower than at the same time Sunday from northern <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> to western <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> and northwest <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Platte </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Neb. </LOCATION>, the temperature was 37 degrees at 1 p.m., compared to 72 degrees Sunday. As the front moved through <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, generating winds off chilly <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, the temperature fell from 60 degrees to 48 degrees in an hour. In contrast, warm air pushing eastward raised temperatures in the central Rockies. The mercury jumped from 49 degrees to 61 in an hour in Casper, <LOCATION> Wyo </LOCATION>. At 1 p.m., it was 70 in <LOCATION> Craig </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>, and 43 in <LOCATION> Cheyenne </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wyo. </LOCATION>, which remained in the cooler air. Scattered thunderstorms fell in southern <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. While sunshine prevailed along the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, the central and southern coast of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> were cloudy. Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 27 degrees at <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, to 93 degrees at <LOCATION> Midland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. The forecast for Tuesday called for showers and scattered thunderstorms from <LOCATION> northeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and southeast <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> and the central and southern Appalachians; rain showers in the middle and northern <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> states; and scattered showers and thunderstorms in central and southern <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. High temperatures were predicted in the 40s and 50s from <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> to the upper <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, the Great Lakes and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>; the 80s from inland <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> to much of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and the Gulf Coast states; the 90s in southwest <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>; the 90s to near 100 degrees in the desert <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION> and in the 60s and 70s elsewhere.
