<HEAD>Rightist Party to Create Information Agency on Rebel Activity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vice President-elect <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Merino </PERSON> said Monday leftist rebels are `` the only generators of violence'' in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> and his rightist party is forming an agency to keep track of them. He was asked if abductions and killings of leftists by right-wing groups constituted terrorism and he said: `` Not that I know of, because there is no extreme right.'' Merino of the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION>, known as <PERSON> Arena </PERSON>, blamed rebels for a bomb attack on his home Friday that caused extensive damage and slightly injured a nephew. <PERSON> Merino </PERSON> and his wife <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonieta </PERSON> were not at home at the time of the bombing. Four children and two other nephews in the house were not harmed. Merino and President-elect <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> of <PERSON> Arena </PERSON> won the March 19 election, defeating the centrist <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION>, and are to be inaugurated June 1 for five-year terms. At a news conference Monday, <PERSON> Merino </PERSON> gave the names, addresses and workplaces of eight people he said belonged to the guerrilla cell that attacked his home. He said the information came from a rebel who was captured and interrogated by police but released for lack of evidence of involvement in the bombing. Police have not arrested the eight people he named `` because of an excess of work, for lack of resources or for lack of will,'' Merino said. He said <PERSON> Arena </PERSON> was forming an intelligence service to receive information from citizens about activities of the rebel alliance, the <ORGANIZATION> Farabundo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>. `` Our party, our local headquarters and our leaders will receive in confidentiality'' all the information and pass it on to `` the armed forces, the police and judicial authorities, according to the case,'' he said. `` People should go before our local leaders and tell them of these cases,'' he added. `` The members of our organization meet frequently and this way we can elaborate a more complete picture'' of the rebel movement `` so the people play a more active role in imposing order.'' Arena was founded in 1981 as an anti-communist group. International human rights organizations and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government linked party leaders, some of whom remain active, to rightist death squads that killed thousands of people in the early 1980s. The party denies any connection with death squads and <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> did not join the party until 1985. <PERSON> Merino </PERSON> said <PERSON> Arena </PERSON> would be only a conduit for citizen reports and would not take follow-up action on its own. He said `` security forces would definitely be the ones to take appropriate action. Arena is a civilian institution. We do not have the capacity to counter the military action of these groups.'' Merino called the guerrillas `` the only generators of violence in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>'' and added: `` If we can minimize the terrorists' action, the level of violence, of victims, will tend to diminish. Leftist rebels began their battle for power nine years ago. More than 70,000 Salvadorans have been killed and most of the victims were civilians.
