 During the 1979 through 1984 period that Mrs. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> was on the payroll of <ORGANIZATION> Mallick </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Properties </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Mallightco </LOCATION>, she and her husband also received free housing from <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON> just steps away from his office in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON> testified that housing was provided, not as a part of compensation, but because it was convenient for him to have Mrs. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> living only a few feet away from his office. <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON> could not explain why her job required her to be so close to his office. In fact, much of her work for <ORGANIZATION> Mallick </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Properties </ORGANIZATION> was done in <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION>. Moreover, throughout her employment with <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON>, Mrs. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> lived primarily in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, spending on the average only one week a month in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>. Thus her consulting jobs plainly were not jobs requiring her to be close to the office. The free housing was thus not job related, but a gift from <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON>. Beginning in 1985, the Wrights began paying rent for the housing <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON> provided. The rent was determined by dividing the fair monthly rental of the apartment, $ 650, by 30, the average number of days in a month. The Wrights were charged $ 21.67 -LRB- or sometimes $ 21.00 or $ 21.50 -RRB- for each day they personally occupied the apartment notwithstanding the fact that since their furniture and personal belongings occupied the apartment every day, they had constructive possession of the apartment daily. Thus in 1985, the <ORGANIZATION> Wrights </ORGANIZATION> paid rent of $ 881.50 for the equivalent of 41 days at $ 21.50 per day. In 1986, an election year, they paid $ 1,711.92 for 79 days. In 1987, they paid $ 756 for 36 days. At fair market rent, the apartment would have cost the Wrights $ 7,800 per year. Finally, after renting for 10 days through March 1988, the <ORGANIZATION> Wrights </ORGANIZATION> bought the apartment at what appears to be its fair market value of $ 58,500. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s receipt of housing at substantially below market rental is a gift from <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON>. Beginning in 1983, <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON> provided <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> with free use of <PERSON> Mallightco </PERSON>'s 1979 <LOCATION> Cadillac </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Seville </LOCATION>. Mrs. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> brought the car to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and has used it there ever since. Although the car is referred to in <LOCATION> Mallightco </LOCATION>'s records as the `` BW Cad.,'' <PERSON> Mallightco </PERSON> owned the car until approximately February 1989 and paid expenses including license fees, insurance, tires and repairs until approximately February 1989 On February 16, 1989, Special Outside Counsel received a copy of a February 9, 1989 letter to the Committee from <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Law </PERSON>, trustee of the <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr </PERSON>. Blind Trust. Law stated that he recently discovered that: -LRB- T -RRB- he Speaker's wife, <PERSON> Betty </PERSON>, as an officer of <LOCATION> Mallightco </LOCATION>, used an automobile owned by that company. I have been informed that the parties treated this transaction as a loan of the car to Mrs. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, to be handled similarly to other loans from <LOCATION> Mallightco </LOCATION> to its principals. I have been further informed that the parties intended that the automobile be purchased by the Trust at its inception. Unfortunately, due to an oversight, the automobile was overlooked at the Trust's creation and never accounted for. Thus only after Special Outside Counsel had completed its investigation and questioned witnesses regarding Mrs. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s use of the car, Law discovered the `` inadvertent'' omission of the car from the Trust records. Law further stated in his letter:
