 I have currently rectified this situation by purchasing, as Trustee, the automobile from <LOCATION> Mallightco </LOCATION>. The purchase price was $ 7,050, the value of the automobile on <PERSON> Mallightco </PERSON>'s books as of January 1, 1983, at which time it was taken to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> D.C </ORGANIZATION>. The Trust made a cash payment of $ 7,050 plus 7 percent interest dating back to January 1, 1983, for a total cash payment of $ 10,011. In addition, the Trust holds a $ 120,000 note, payable from <LOCATION> Mallightco </LOCATION>. This note has been reduced by $ 9,302.85, representing the sums paid by <PERSON> Mallightco </PERSON> for insurance on and repairs to the automobile from January 1, 1983 to present. Law does not explain how the oversight was discovered. Nor does he explain how the purchase of the automobile in 1989 at its 1983 book value `` rectifies'' the Trust's failure to purchase the car in 1987. ... Plainly, Law's February 9, 1989 letter to the <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> is an attempt to cover up <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s violations of House Rule XLIII, clause 4, with respect to <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON>'s gift of the car. <PERSON> Mallightco </PERSON> never expected nor attempted to collect rental or ` loan'' payments for the car. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON> testified that <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> had the car because she `` would use -LRB- the car -RRB- in connection with her work for Mallightco.'' However, even assuming that <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s employment by <PERSON> Mallightco </PERSON> in 1983 and 1984 was bona fide, there is no evidence that she did any work for <LOCATION> Mallightco </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> which required use of a car. In addition, regardless of the legitimacy of Mrs. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s Mallightco employment, there is absolutely no justification for her retention of the car after she stopped working for the company. Therefore, the value of using the car from 1983 to date and all related expenses are gifts from <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON> to <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> received in violation of House rules. Of course, in order for gifts to violate House Rules, they must be received from someone with a direct interest in legislation before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. In this matter, we believe it is clear that <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON> had such an interest. We further impute his interest in legislation to his wife <PERSON> Marlene </PERSON> <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON>. <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON> is and has been a major real estate developer in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> having developed commercial and residential properties worth over $ 160 million. Prior to 1986, <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON> also had major holdings in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> oil and gas ventures. In 1986, he stood to profit from the proposed redevelopment of the Fort Worth Stockyards which relied heavily on public funds being appropriated by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Thus, he had a direct interest in legislation affecting the taxation of real estate, interest rates, the oil and gas industries and appropriations for the Stockyards project. In addition, <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON>'s financing of certain real estate ventures through savings and loan associations and the subsequent foreclosure on at least one of those properties gave <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON> a direct interest in legislation regarding the savings and loan industry. Nevertheless, in late 1986, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> designated <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON> to conduct an investigation and prepare a report concerning the `` savings and loan crisis'' in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. The report addressed issues of concern to <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON> and recommended legislation which would curb the industry's right to foreclose on loans in default. Thus as discussed in full in Section III. E. of this Report, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> repeatedly violated House Rule XLIII, clause 4; Rule XLIV; and consideration 5 of the Code of Ethics for Government Service.
