<HEAD>New Jersey, Illinois Families Share Part Of Record $69 Million Lottery</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Louis and...,' to UPDATE that Matlosz' are from
Elizabeth and to CORRECT wife's name to MaryAnn, sted Mary Ann.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Members of two farflung families came forward from four states Monday to claim half the record $ 69.9 million Illinois Lotto jackpot, leaving the holders of the two other winning tickets unknown. `` It's more money than any of us ever expected to see in our lifetimes,'' said <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON>, 38, of suburban <LOCATION> Naperville </LOCATION>, Ill.., who bought one winning ticket for his wife's family <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Matlosz </PERSON>, of <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, and their four children, including <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON>'s wife <PERSON> MaryAnn </PERSON>, and three grandchildren, joined <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON> at a news conference, saying they would split their $ 17.5 million share of the jackpot and plan to spend the money on vacations and on the grandchildren. Another winner was <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, 36, a hog buyer from <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, who will share his prize with brothers in <LOCATION> Stafford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Chandler </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said he was `` hysterical,'' after learning he had won `` I sat at the table and laughed.'' The news got around fast in <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, a town of 300 in west-central <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, and a big sign in the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> declared `` Congratulations, <PERSON> Ron </PERSON>.'' State computers recorded that four winning tickets were sold _ two in the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> area, one in west-central <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> and one in southern <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. Both the <PERSON> Matlosz </PERSON> family and the <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> family bought 15 Lotto tickets, and <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said he was not surprised the $ 69.9 million jackpot was being shared. `` It's more money than I'll ever use,'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. He said he would not quit work altogether, but `` I'll find something I like a little better.'' The Matlosz family members planned to keep working. The remaining winners were expected to come forward this week, perhaps after making financial preparations. `` Most people will have already gotten some advice,'' said state Lottery Director <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON>. The final figure for the jackpot, boosted by four winner-less drawings and a frenzy of ticket-buying last week before Saturday's drawing, was $ 69,940,000, Ms. <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON> said The huge jackpot, which nearly doubled in the week before the drawing, drew dreamers to Lotto outlets from around the country and even the world, as travelers flocked to Lotto kiosks at O'Hare International Airport between planes. By Monday, life was back to normal in Lotto-land. `` It's a lot slower than last week,'' Ms. <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON> said. The jackpot, bolstered by a week of record sales, beat the world record of $ 61.98 million set in October in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. That pot was split among three winning tickets, one bought by an individual and the others bought by groups of co-workers. If only one person had matched the numbers, the jackpot would have been the largest paid to a single winner. But with four ticket-holders sharing the pot, the largest single winner in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> history remains a <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> woman who walked away with $ 55.16 million in the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> lottery in September. The winning numbers drawn Saturday were 3, 14, 32, 40, 46 and 54. Illinois Lotto players pick six numbers from 1 to 54 with two chances on each $ 1 ticket. The odds that a ticket carries a winning sequence are 12.9 million to 1.
