<HEAD>Students Mourn Hu Yaobang, Demand that China's Politburo Resign</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs on sit-in, other developments. Picks up
8th graf, `The four-hour...' with minor editing to trim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nearly 2,000 students swarmed into central <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s Tiananmen Square by bicycle and on foot before dawn Tuesday and cheered demands that the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s ruling Politburo resign. More than 1,500 students in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> also took to the streets to express grief over the death Saturday of former <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Hu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yaobang </PERSON> and to demand more democracy. Students marched in both cities Monday. They put up posters on campus mourning Hu, a liberal reformist, and expressing vague dissatisfaction with the government. A poster at <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> attacked senior leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON> for the first time, although not by name. It blamed the 84-year-old <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> for <PERSON> Hu </PERSON>'s removal in 1987. The marches were the largest since the 1986-87 pro-democracy demonstrations that led to <PERSON> Hu </PERSON>'s forced resignation. Conservatives accused Hu of being too liberal and failing to halt student demonstrations. Tuesday's demonstrations brought the revived student movement closer to a new political stage. <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> students cheered when one speaker climbed on a monument to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s revolutionary heroes and demanded that the 22-member Politburo resign. They cheered a demand that party leaders reassess <PERSON> Hu </PERSON>'s place in history. It could not be determined how many demonstrators joined in formulating the demands. Most students dispersed after reaching <PERSON> Tiananmen </PERSON>, but about 200 staged a sit-in before the Great Hall of the People, the national seat of government next to the square. They presented six demands to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, or parliament, including reassessment of Hu's role, opposition to anti-liberal political campaigns, and disclosure of leaders' incomes They demanded freedom of speech and press, higher pay for intellectuals, and lifting restrictions on street marches. The six demands did not include one for the Politburo's resignation An unidentified official received the demands but said they were major matters that needed to be studied at length. The students sang the national anthem and the socialist <ORGANIZATION> Internationale </ORGANIZATION>, chanted `` Long live democracy!'' and `` Oppose dictatorship!'' and asked other students back on the campus to join them. The four-hour march from campuses in northern <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> had the atmosphere of a recreational outing. Students joked and laughed, and many said they did n't know what they would do once they reached <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION>. `` We're going to honor the memory of <PERSON> Hu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yaobang </PERSON>,'' one said. `` We do n't have any political goals.'' Several said the march began spontaneously shortly after midnight at <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, which is <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s leading university and has a history of political activism. Students from other schools joined the procession, along with some bystanders. Several students carrying a white sheet with the words `` <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s Spirit'' led the march A few police stationed around the square made no attempt to interfere. More than 600 students from <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s Political Science and <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> marched to <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> on Monday and placed two funeral wreaths at the monument. In <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, thousands of students from <ORGANIZATION> Fudan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> participated in marches that began Sunday. <PERSON> Jason </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurpado </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, an English teacher at <LOCATION> Fudan </LOCATION>, said students sang revolutionary songs during the first march, substituting <PERSON> Hu </PERSON>'s name for that of revolutionary leader <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Tse-tung </PERSON>. This week's marches reflected not only grief at Hu's death but also the volatility among students unhappy with living conditions and bleak career prospects. The officially supervised Student Union at <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, in an apparent attempt to channel the students' emotions, set up a temporary memorial hall honoring Hu. The Communist Party has said an official memorial service will be held in the Great Hall of the People, but no date has been set. <PERSON> Hu </PERSON> was eulogized by the party as a statesman and proletarian revolutionary.
