<HEAD>WASHN: Government Service.</HEAD>
<HEAD>F. Wright's Possible Exercise of Undue Influence in Dealing With
Officials of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 In early 1986, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- the `` <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>'' -RRB-, perceiving worsening conditions in the <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION>'s economy and thrift industry, began a massive examination of almost all the savings and loan associations in District 9, which included associations in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> As a result, the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> discovered that many associations, especially those in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> where state regulations were especially permissive, were built on risky investments, uncollectible loans and fraudulent appraisals. While the real estate market was booming, these associations appeared to be doing well. However, when the bottom dropped out of the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> real estate market, the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>'s examinations showed that much of the profit had been imaginary. The burgeoning number of savings and loan failures in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and elsewhere placed enormous strains on the <ORGANIZATION> FSLIC </ORGANIZATION> fund, which insures deposits in federal and state-chartered savings and loan associations. Under federal law, when <ORGANIZATION> FSLIC </ORGANIZATION> places an insolvent federally-insured savings association into a receivership, it must pay off the insured depositors almost immediately. Therefore, each closure requires <ORGANIZATION> FSLIC </ORGANIZATION> to make an immediate cash outlay approximately equal to the insolvent association's deposits. As <ORGANIZATION> FSLIC </ORGANIZATION>'s reserves dwindled, it lost the financial ability to close even the most insolvent associations. In late 1986, approximately 250 associations required <ORGANIZATION> FSLIC </ORGANIZATION> assistance. Of these, <ORGANIZATION> FSLIC </ORGANIZATION> considered 130 associations, with stated assets of $ 47.6 billion, to be severely troubled. In response to this crisis, in May 1986 a bill was introduced in the House of Representatives which provided, among other items, $ 15 billion in new funds for <ORGANIZATION> FSLIC </ORGANIZATION> without the use of general revenues. The bill was referred to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee on Banking, <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> and Urban Affairs, which passed the bill by a vote of 47 to 1 without significant amendment. The bill was placed on the suspension calendar and was scheduled for consideration by the full <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> on Monday, September 29, 1986. -LRB- The suspension calendar is reserved for bills engendering little controversy. -RRB- However, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> removed it from the calendar prior to its consideration. The bill was rescheduled on October 6, 1986 and on October 7, 1986 it passed the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> under suspension of the rules. However, because the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s version of the bill contained controversial provisions, insufficient time remained to resolve the differences before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> adjourned on October 18, 1986. On January 6, 1987, substantially the same bill was reintroduced in the new <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The Banking Committee held hearings later in January as members began increasingly to pass along complaints about regulators' `` arbitrary'' actions in closing down savings and loan associations. For the first time, `` forbearance'' provisions, i.e., provisions restricting <ORGANIZATION> FSLIC </ORGANIZATION>'s ability to close associations, were discussed as part of the bill. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> supported these forbearance provisions as well as a reduction in the recapitalization amount to $ 5 billion. The <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> believed the forbearance provisions and the reduced recapitalization amount would severely hamper its ability to deal with the crisis. Although <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> later supported $ 15 billion, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> passed the recapitalization bill at the $ 5 billion level. The amount was raised to $ 10.8 billion in conference and the forbearance provisions were weakened. The bill was signed into law in August 1987. During this 1986-1987 period, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> intervened with the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> on behalf of four <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> businessmen who were deeply embroiled in the savings and loan crisis. One of these businessmen, <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>, met with <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> on September 2, 1986 and informed him that the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> was out of control and taking action against him which would have serious repercussions in the <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> communities. Hall is a Dallas-based real estate syndicator and one of the largest owners of real estate in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Once Hall determined that the worsening <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> economy threatened his ability to remain current on loans held by numerous savings and loan associations, he sought assistance from the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banks </ORGANIZATION> in restructuring his debts held by FSLIC-controlled savings and loans. Although the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> was not adverse to the concept of a global restructuring, it believed it could not legally assume the role of negotiator for those associations involved in the Hall restructuring which were already under <ORGANIZATION> FSLIC </ORGANIZATION> control. Hall was required to negotiate individual agreements with the Special Representatives of each FSLIC-controlled association. Hall was able to reach agreement with all but one FSLIC-controlled association, the <ORGANIZATION> Westwood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION>, which held approximately $ 200 million in Hall loans. <PERSON> Westwood </PERSON>'s Bank Board-appointed Special Representative, <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Schultz </PERSON>, and its outside counsel refused to accept conditions to the restructuring which were adverse to <PERSON> Westwood </PERSON>'s interests and decided to foreclose on <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>'s properties and allow him to go bankrupt rather than accept his restructuring plan. At the onset of foreclosure proceedings, the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banks </ORGANIZATION> ceased communication with <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>. Hall told <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> in their September 2, 1986 meeting that he had received no response to his efforts to re-establish communication with the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banks </ORGANIZATION>. Soon after meeting with <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> called a meeting in his office with several <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> congressmen and representatives of the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, including its Chairman, <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>. Although Hall may have been mentioned, the meeting was generally devoted to passing along reports that <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> regulators were mistreating <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> savings and loans. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> called Gray shortly after the meeting to complain about <PERSON> Westwood </PERSON>'s Special Representative, <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Schultz </PERSON>, whom <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said was not as flexible or understanding as he might be. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> asked if there was not anything <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> could do about that situation. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> never discussed the merits of the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>'s position and he rebuffed the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>'s offer to explain its position in the Hall matter. <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> decided to further investigate the Hall matter. On Friday, September 26, 1986, <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> Chief of Staff <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> <PERSON> Fairbanks </PERSON> went to a meeting with <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> and his <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> savings and loan creditors. On that day, <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> learned that because of <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s interest in <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>'s situation, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> had placed a `` hold'' on the <ORGANIZATION> FSLIC </ORGANIZATION> recapitalization bill which had been scheduled for consideration by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> on the following Monday <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fairbanks </PERSON> thus determined that if they were to obtain a recapitalization bill, they would have to facilitate a restructuring of <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>'s loans. On September 29, 1986, <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> replaced <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Schultz </PERSON> with another Special Representative who was instructed to disregard outside couunsel's legal advice and determine if there was any way to build a responsible economic case in support of renegotiating <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>'s loans. Following <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>'s removal of <PERSON> Schultz </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>'s later assurances to <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> that the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> would not treat <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> savings and loans unfairly, the bill was returned to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> calendar. It was passed by the full <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> under a suspension of the rules on October 7, 1986.
