 <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> did not merely `` urge prompt consideration'' of or `` express judgment'' on the Hall matter as specifically permitted in the Select Committee on Ethics' Advisory Opinion No. 1. He removed the recapitalization bill from <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> consideration in order to pressure the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> into changing its resolution of the Hall matter regardless of the merits of the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>'s position. Such pressure is a violation of House Rule XLIII, clause 1, as interpreted by Advisory Opinion No. 1. On October 6, 1986, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> met with <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Mann </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, an <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> savings and loan operator who complained that the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> was discriminating against <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> savings and loans associations and that a recapitalized <ORGANIZATION> FSLIC </ORGANIZATION> would close large numbers of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> institutions. <PERSON> Mann </PERSON> also set forth his complaints in a letter of October 7, 1986 which <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> forwarded to <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> asking that he check on the situations described. <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> investigated <PERSON> Mann </PERSON>'s charges and reported to <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> that <PERSON> Mann </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> CreditBanc </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> had committed serious regulatory violations and was in a precarious financial condition. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> took no further action. Thus <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s request that <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> check on <PERSON> Mann </PERSON>'s charges is within the guidelines of Advisory Opinion No. 1 which expressly provides that it is appropriate for a member to request information or a status report. In early November 1986, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> telephoned <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> regarding <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s `` friend'' <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaubert </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, a Texas-chartered association with its main office in <LOCATION> Irving </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gaubert </PERSON> was also a contributor to the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and treasurer of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Campaign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. In January 1986, <PERSON> Gaubert </PERSON> had been permanently removed from Independent American and prohibited from operating any FSLIC-insured association. <PERSON> Gaubert </PERSON> had been involved in questionable transactions at an <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> savings and loan as well as regulatory violations and unsafe or unsound practices at Independent American. As of November 30, 1986, <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> had a negative net worth of $ 454 million. Although <PERSON> Gaubert </PERSON> entered into a written agreement removing him from the industry, he later argued that he had been misled and treated unfairly and, therefore, that the agreement was invalid. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> asked <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> to meet with <PERSON> Gaubert </PERSON> personally in order to get <PERSON> Gaubert </PERSON>'s side of the story. <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> protested that <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> rules prohibit the Chairman from meeting with parties to actions before the Board. Despite <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>'s protests, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> insisted that <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> meet with <PERSON> Gaubert </PERSON>; <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> did so as an accommodation to <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>. Following his meeting with <PERSON> Gaubert </PERSON>, <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> made the unprecedented decision in January or February 1987 to appoint an independent counsel -LRB- selected by counsel for <PERSON> Gaubert </PERSON> -RRB- to determine whether the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> had in fact wrongfully removed <PERSON> Gaubert </PERSON> from Independent American. <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> testified that but for his perception of <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s influence on the recapitalization bill, he would not have appointed independent counsel Independent counsel ultimately determined that the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> had not violated any statutes or regulations in its treatment of <PERSON> Gaubert </PERSON>, although it did note some instances of improper or unfair behavior, none of which justified <PERSON> Gaubert </PERSON>'s claim that he was removed improperly Nonetheless, despite the significant concessions made by <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>, at a meeting with officials of the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> and FHLB-Dallas on February 10, 1987 in <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s office, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> made it plain that he viewed the outcome of the <PERSON> Gaubert </PERSON> matter to have been extremely unsatisfactory. The clear inference is that <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> was not simply seeking impartial consideration of <PERSON> Gaubert </PERSON>'s claim, but a change in the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>'s regulatory response to <PERSON> Gaubert </PERSON>. Such use of <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s influence is a violation of House Rule XLIII, clause 1 as interpreted by Advisory Opinion No. 1. In December 1986, Congressman <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON> called <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s aide, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Mack </PERSON>, and requested <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s assistance on behalf of <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON> of Vernon Savings and Loan in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON> informed <PERSON> Mack </PERSON> that the <ORGANIZATION> FSLIC </ORGANIZATION> was going to shut down <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> that day. He asked that <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> attempt to get <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON> a grace period as <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON> said he had a willing buyer. <PERSON> Mack </PERSON> testified that following his conversation with <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON>, he told <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> of <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON>'s problem. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> telephoned <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> and asked him whether <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> was being closed down. <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> responded that closing an institution requires a <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> meeting and he had not authorized any such meeting. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> asked <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> to find out if anything was happening and to call <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Mack </PERSON> with the information. <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> later informed <PERSON> Mack </PERSON> that <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> was not being `` shut down,'' but the FHLB-Dallas supervisory agents were going to seek a `` consent to merger agreement'' from <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON>'s directors at the end of December 1986. <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> explained that such an agreement would not affect the association's ability to find an investor and that <PERSON> Mack </PERSON> should let the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> know if an investor were found. Ultimately, no investor was found and <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> was placed in receivership in March 1987. In this instance, since <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> merely asked for information from the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, no violation occurred. In November 1986, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> again called <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> to express his concern about the way <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> institutions were being treated by the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. He brought up the subject of <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Selby </PERSON>, the Director of Regulatory Affairs at the FHLB-Dallas and formerly the acting Comptroller of the Currency, who had the reputation of being a tough regulator and who had been brought into the savings and loan crisis by <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> to implement the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>'s supervisory and regulatory response. Because of his hardline posture, <PERSON> Selby </PERSON> was feared and distrusted by many in the thirft industry. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> told <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> he understood from unnamed sources that <PERSON> Selby </PERSON> was a homosexual who was sending all of FHLB-Dallas' work to a `` ring of homosexual lawyers in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> asked <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> if there was anything <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> could do to `` get rid of'' <PERSON> Selby </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> refused <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s request and defended <PERSON> Selby </PERSON> as a highly competent regulator doing the tough job expected of him. Although unsuccessful, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s attempt to destroy <PERSON> Selby </PERSON>'s career based upon such an accusation violates <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> rule XLIII, clause 1, because it does not reflect creditably on the House Similarly, when in late