<HEAD>Artist-Photgrapher Petrov Given Permission to Leave Russia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Artist-photographer <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON> <PERSON> Petrov </PERSON> said Monday he was being allowed to leave the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> after being refused permission to emigrate for eight years and that he hoped to go to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> this week. The 36-year-old <PERSON> Petrov </PERSON> said in a telephone interview that he had tried since 1981 to join his <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> wife, <PERSON> Virginia </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, but was turned down for reasons of state security. Now, he said, `` I have my passport in my hand.'' <PERSON> Petrov </PERSON> said he received notification from the Soviet visa office in Sunday's mail and picked up his external passport Monday. He said he filed repeated invitations for visits to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> with the visa office long ago and that `` they just picked one.'' He replied when asked why he now was being granted permission to leave: `` I will never know. I think the reason is all the joint effort of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, and other countries like the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>. But mostly it was the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s pressure.'' <PERSON> Petrov </PERSON>'s photographs were put on display at the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> late last year and his case has been a priority human rights case pursued by <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. He said he will go to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` as soon as I can, sometime this week,'' but that his plans were not certain. The photographer said former <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartman </P