<TEXT>
 At least a dozen states are considering laws that would force companies to insure their employees as a way to stem billions of dollars in hospital losses and protect some of the 37 million Americans without health insurance. <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> in 1974 became the first state in the nation to adopt a mandatory insurance law, and it was followed last year by <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. This year, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and other states are debating bills that would order companies to cover workers, impose tax penalties on those that do n't and provide incentives for those that do. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and a few other states have adopted pilot projects to provide health care to the working poor.
