<HEAD>$Adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon PMs April 24 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Youth Center to Teach Nazi Horrors Planned for Dachau</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DACHAU, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After eight years of sometimes bitter controversy, Bavarian leaders are planning a youth center in <LOCATION> Dachau </LOCATION> to help teach younger generations of the <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> horrors that occurred in its notorious concentration camp. But deep philosophical differences remain over just how the center will pass on its bitter lessons. Politicians here in highly conservative <LOCATION> Bavaria </LOCATION> want the youth center to be under governmental control. They envision it as a youth hostel that would combine instruction about the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> with a chance to learn about the modern-day city of <LOCATION> Dachau </LOCATION>. On the other side, an association that has members in several countries argues that the leadership of the center should reflect more diverse views and be more international in scope. The Association for a <ORGANIZATION> Dachau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Youth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Meeting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> says the guest house should serve almost exclusively as a forum to analyze the <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> past and its implications today. <PERSON> Juergen </PERSON> <PERSON> Zarusky </PERSON>, a leader of the association, said he sees dangers in government control. `` That means everything must be under government protection, so that the past will be presented as a formal history lesson,'' <PERSON> Zarusky </PERSON> said in an interview. `` Both the personal impact and the search for meaning for today wo n't be presented as strongly.'' <PERSON> Zarusky </PERSON>, a 30-year-old doctoral candidate in modern history who's lived in <LOCATION> Dachau </LOCATION> for three years, said his group feels unfairly excluded from the project because local conservatives fear `` this could go in a leftist direction.'' The concentration camp site, including a museum and memorials to the dead, already attracts about a million visitors a year, two-thirds of them foreigners. The site also contains watch towers, barbed wire fences, a reconstructed barracks and the crematorium where the dead were once burned. <LOCATION> Dachau </LOCATION>, which is about five miles north of <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION>, was the first of a string of <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> concentration camps that became centers mainly for the extermination of Jews, mostly in gas chambers, in World War II. Official Nazi records say that 206,000 prisoners were kept at <LOCATION> Dachau </LOCATION>, although the actual number is believed to be much higher. Nazi records say that nearly 32,000 prisoners died there, but thousands of other deaths were not registered. The <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> set up the concentration camp at <LOCATION> Dachau </LOCATION> two months after seizing power Jan. 30, 1933. Its prisoners included Jews, Communists, Social Democrats, clergymen and other opponents of the Nazi regime. Bavarian officials opened the camp as a memorial in 1965, after agreeing to cooperate with the Brussels-based <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dachau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> in supervising the site. The committee, made up of former <LOCATION> Dachau </LOCATION> prisoners, has representatives on the board of trustees of the association that wants an international youth center. The association was formed in 1984, after three years of efforts by a local committee to establish a place where young people could meet and spend the night. The plans ran into vehement opposition from the conservative <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> officials at <LOCATION> Dachau </LOCATION>'s city hall. They repeatedly have maintained that such a center would unfairly a create `` an extra burden'' on a city already saddled with a notorious past. In 1987, members of the state parliament in <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION> filed several motions, seeking to take the matter out of local hands as a way to find a solution. As a result, the Bavarian Education Ministry this past September approved a plan for creating the youth center with sleeping accommodations for about 100 people, as well as meeting rooms, for both West Germans and foreigners. `` The youth guest house should contribute to enabling and promoting a discussion of the past that is linked to the spirit of democratic responsibility,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said. In its proposal for <LOCATION> Dachau </LOCATION>, however, the <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> called for the exclusion of events focusing on `` day-to-day politics.'' The ministry's <PERSON> Manfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Heger </PERSON>, who is handling the project, said the guest house is supposed to be `` multi-functional.'' `` It is n't supposed to be set up exclusively for instruction about the camp memorial, the concentration camp site, Nazism and fascism.'' The Association for a <ORGANIZATION> Dachau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Youth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Meeting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> has rejected the government plan and continues to push for its own ideas, including a greater reliance on former prisoners to narrate their horrifying experiences. <PERSON> Gabi </PERSON> <PERSON> Hendl </PERSON>, another leading member of the association, brushes aside objections that the center could damage the city's reputation. `` This youth meeting center is a chance for <LOCATION> Dachau </LOCATION> and the people who live in the city to hear what young people from other countries are thinking,'' said the 24-year-old Ms. <PERSON> Hendl </PERSON>, a member of the leftist-leaning <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. Another member of the association is <PERSON> Nikolaus </PERSON> <PERSON> Lehner </PERSON>, 65, a Jew who survived <LOCATION> Dachau </LOCATION>. `` We are n't politicizing,'' he said. `` We're discussing history.''
</TEXT>
