<SECOND>PM-Israel-Phoenicians, Adv 25,0722</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues PMs April 25 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cemetery of Ancient Phoenicians Uncovered in Northern Israel</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Archaeologists have unearthed an ancient cemetery in northern <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and say the 3,000-year-old finds indicate the Phoenicians were landlubbers before they went to sea and dominated the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION>. The Phoenicians emerged about 1,000 B.C. and established city-states throughout the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basin </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, surviving until Roman times. Pottery, jewelry and other remains of their cities show a variety of influences from Greek cultures in the <LOCATION> Aegean </LOCATION> as well as ancient <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mesopotamia </LOCATION>. But little is known of the origins of the ancient Phoenicians. Evidence uncovered by a <ORGANIZATION> Hebrew </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> team in the tombs at <LOCATION> Achziv </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s border with <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> point to a Semitic background, either from the ancient land of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, also known as <LOCATION> Canaan </LOCATION>, or further inland. The team declined to give a specific location of the cemetery for fear of plunderers; they believe artifacts and gold may be buried in the tombs. <PERSON> Elat </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazar </PERSON>, an archaeologist at <ORGANIZATION> Hebrew </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, said the architecture of the tombs carved into the bedrock linked the early Phoenicians to the ancient Hittites, a Semitic people who lived in what is now <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> and had no significant sailing tradition. `` We found a hole in the ceiling on the tomb which is characteristic of Hittite burial chambers,'' she said. `` In their cult of the dead, it was a symbolic link between the living world and the world of the dead.'' She added that the Phoenicians had a sophisicated society with advanced sailing technology, refined tastes in jewelry and an unparalled ability to adapt material from other cultures. `` There is no question they were more developed than the Israelite culture of the time. They were Semitic and close to the Israelites but different.'' The pack-rat characteristic of borrowing from neighboring societies made the Phoenicians something of a mystery, however. <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, a British-born anthropologist and dentist interviewed at her laboratory in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Hadassah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, said a study of the ancient human remains show the physical features of the Phoenicians were Semitic. `` This was no Greek,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, turning the skull of a Phoenician and pointing to the wide skull, arch of the nose and the high cheekbones. A cast of an Israelite skull from the same eighth to seventh century B.C. period had similar features. From his teeth, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> deduced that the man, 45 to 50 years old when he died, suffered either from fever or hunger in his infancy but was quite fit as an adult, with not a single tooth cavity. `` Apart from this hole in his head, he was very healthy,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said of the Phoenician, who died of a powerful blow to the back of his head, apparently struck by a heavy blunt instrument. The Israeli expedition unearthed about 50 skeletons from two cave tombs measuring about 10 feet by 10 feet. The cemetery covers seven acres and may contain the remains of thousands of Phoenicians spanning almost the entire 1,000-year life of their society here. Ms. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said she hoped to use the remains, especially the skulls, to recreate the general `` Phoenician look.'' `` It will be very exiting to find out who the Phoenicians were.'' Ms. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> uses video cameras and still photography to recreate faces. She employed the technique on behalf of the prosecution in the trial of <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, autoworker convicted last year in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nazi </LOCATION> war crimes and sentenced to death. She made a video that superimposed a recent video image of <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON> on a 40-year-old Nazi identity card to show it was the same man. With the Phoenicians, she plans to use the same technique to superimpose video images from ancient drawings of Phoenicians and modern sketches over the skulls themselves. `` I would be able to define a type, but not an individual. We should be able to tell how varied the Phoenicians were,'' she said, explaining that a perfect re-creation was impossible without knowing the features of soft tissue such as eyelids, ears and lips.
</TEXT>
