<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed PMs April 26 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Israeli Rabbi Group Monitors West Bank Human Rights Abuses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two bearded rabbis recently slipped under the cover of night into an occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> village to question residents about allegations of <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> troop brutality during an army-imposed curfew. They are members of the new <ORGANIZATION> Rabbinic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Watch </ORGANIZATION>, which is gaining prominence among the growing number of Israeli groups monitoring abuses in the occupied territories. Membership has swelled from a handful of rabbis a few months ago to 75 rabbis embracing all streams of Judaism _ the Orthodox, Conservative and Reform movements. The group's first action was to survey community health care in several <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> villages, then write to Defense Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> complaining that medical treatment was being `` used as a means of political pressure on the population.'' `` It was immediately published in the papers and we said, ` We as rabbis have the power.' We have credibility as Jewish leaders who first of all think of the moral side,'' said the U.S.-born chairman of the group, Rabbi <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Forman </PERSON>. The group has since monitored the Palestinian village of <PERSON> Batir </PERSON>, three miles outside <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>. In early April, one day before a group of rabbis was to have visited <PERSON> Batir </PERSON>, the army clamped a curfew on the village in retaliation for a stone-throwing attack on a train. Four days later, <PERSON> Forman </PERSON> and another rabbi, <PERSON> Yermiyahu </PERSON> <PERSON> Milgrom </PERSON>, slipped into <PERSON> Batir </PERSON> at night to hear the villagers' complaints. Their report of alleged troop brutality, including beatings and verbal abuse, was submitted to <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> and was carried in the Israeli press. The group includes about 10 Orthodox rabbis, with the rest of its members equally divided between Reform and Conservative clerics. It is run by a board of six rabbis that includes two representatives from each of the three movements. The unusual cooperation between Orthodox and rival Reform and Conservative rabbis, as well as the group's lack of political ideology gives it a moral authority over most of the dozen or so other Israeli movements considered to be comprised of leftists. Western human rights groups, on the other hand, are considered by many Israelis to be biased in favor of the Palestinians. `` We raise our voice, the moral voice of the Jewish spirit, which holds that every man and woman, without regard for religion and nationality, is created in the image of God,'' the group's platform states `` Invested with a religious mandate to speak for the Jewish people who has suffered so painfully, we must forever remain sensitive to the suffering of others.'' <PERSON> Forman </PERSON> criticized <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s religious leaders on grounds that they failed to speak out against brutality in the occupied territories. `` We sense a lack of the rabbinic voice and when we do hear it, it's usually on the farthest right,'' said <PERSON> Forman </PERSON>, 45, a reform rabbi who immigrated to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> in 1972. `` We invite the chief rabbis to respond to what's happening because it opposes the spirit of Jewish law and tradition.'' Chief rabbinate spokesman <PERSON> Eitan </PERSON> <PERSON> Eizman </PERSON> denies the allegations, saying <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s Orthodox chief rabbis `` have responded every time there was an outstanding violation, writing that innocent people should not be harmed or beaten.'' Rabbi <PERSON> Moshe </PERSON> <PERSON> Levinger </PERSON>, a settlement leader in <LOCATION> Kiryat </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arba </LOCATION> near the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> town of <LOCATION> Hebron </LOCATION>, called the rabbis' criticism misguided. `` We have never agreed that these are occupied lands,'' <PERSON> Levinger </PERSON> said. `` We'll stop the moment the Arabs stop.'' The rabbis' group is careful not to endorse a political solution to the 16-month-old conflict, and it denounces <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> violence. <PERSON> Milgrom </PERSON>, 35, said <ORGANIZATION> Judaism </ORGANIZATION> `` is often seen as something that comes to discriminate and persecute the non-Jewish side, and we oppose that. It does not correctly portray <ORGANIZATION> Judaism </ORGANIZATION>. ... Man was created in God's image, every man and not just the Jews.'' The rabbis said adherence to Jewish religious tradition has also helped the group in gathering testimony. At <PERSON> Batir </PERSON>, for example, <PERSON> Forman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Milgrom </PERSON> used a method described in Talmudic religious law of comparing testimony from different witnesses. <PERSON> Forman </PERSON> said that as a result he was convinced people told the truth, despite an army denial of events described in the group's report. He said the rabbis' group also offers `` rabbinical counselling for soldiers deeply troubled by the moral and ethical struggle they confront'' while serving in the occupied territories. The group's next project is an investigation of the army policy of forcing Palestinians to remove barricades built by protesters in the occupied territories, <PERSON> Forman </PERSON> said. `` I do n't want to compare us with other countries,'' he said. `` We have to measure our behavior by Jewish standards. If we start using the lowest common denominator, we cease to be a light unto the nations.''
</TEXT>
