<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Today is Saturday, April 29, the 119th day of 1989. There are 246 days left in the year. Today's highlight in history: On April 29, 1945, <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> soldiers liberated the <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> concentration camp in <LOCATION> Dachau </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, where tens of thousands of people had perished. With the Third Reich collapsing around him, <PERSON> Adolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> appointed Admiral <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Doenitz </PERSON> his successor. <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> also married his mistress, <PERSON> Eva </PERSON> <PERSON> Braun </PERSON>, in a <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> bunker. On this date: In 1429, <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> of Arc entered the besieged city of <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> to lead a victory over the English. In 1861, <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Delegates </ORGANIZATION> voted against seceding from the Union. In 1862, <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orleans </ORGANIZATION> fell to Union forces during the Civil War. In 1863, newspaper publisher <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Randolph </PERSON> <PERSON> Hearst </PERSON> was born in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. In 1894, several hundred unemployed men known as `` <ORGANIZATION> Coxey </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'' swarmed into <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to ask <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for help In 1913, Swedish-born engineer <PERSON> Gideon </PERSON> <PERSON> Sundback </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Hoboken </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, patented the zipper. In 1916, the Easter Rising in <LOCATION> Dublin </LOCATION> ended as Irish nationalists who had seized control of the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> surrendered to British authorities. In 1946, 28 former Japanese leaders were indicted in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> as war criminals. In 1974, President <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> announced he was releasing edited transcripts of some of the secret White House tape recordings related to the Watergate scandal. In 1977, <PERSON> Pope </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> XI </PERSON> and the Archbishop of <LOCATION> Canterbury </LOCATION>, Dr. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Coggan </PERSON>, participated in a Christian unity service in the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>'s Sistine Chapel. In 1983, <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON> was sworn in as <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s first black mayor, vowing to freeze hiring and fire recent political appointees to ease the city's fiscal crisis. In 1985, the space shuttle `` Challenger'' lifted off with seven astronauts and a `` mini-zoo'' of monkeys and rats. Ten years ago: <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> voted to reinstate the death penalty for terrorists convicted of `` acts of inhuman cruelty,'' one week after a <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> attack claimed the lives of four Israelis. Five years ago: President <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON>, flew 600 miles from <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> to central <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, where they saw farms, peasant villages and an archeological site. One year ago: The head of the federal agency researching `` AIDS'' drugs, Dr. <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fauci </PERSON>, told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel he was basically satisfied with the job scientists were doing, but acknowledged some human trials had been delayed due to lack of money. Today's birthdays: Movie director <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Zinnemann </PERSON> is 82. Actor <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Ewell </PERSON> is 80. Actress <PERSON> Celeste </PERSON> <PERSON> Holm </PERSON> is 70. Football coach <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> is 67. Poet <PERSON> Rod </PERSON> <PERSON> McKuen </PERSON> is 56. Conductor <PERSON> Zubin </PERSON> <PERSON> Mehta </PERSON> is 53. Singer <PERSON> Tommy </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> is 42. Actress <PERSON> Kate </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulgrew </PERSON> is 34. Thought for today: `` How easy it is for a man to die rich, if he will but be contented to live miserable.'' _ Henry Fielding, English author and dramatist, 1707-1754.
