<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:PeerGynt Adv20   04-17 0939</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Peer Gynt, Adv 20,0960</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thurs AMs, April 20, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Marathon Version of Ibsen's `Peer Gynt' at Hartford Stage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At the <ORGANIZATION> Hartford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>, director <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Lamos </PERSON> has recreated the magical, mystical world of `` Peer Gynt'' in a dazzling two-part, five-hour production of <PERSON> Ibsen </PERSON>'s rarely performed masterpiece The play, on view through May 20, is a glorious theatrical adventure, a journey that <PERSON> Lamos </PERSON> manages to make both epic and intimate. Using 26 actors in more than 70 roles, the director and scenic design wizard <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Conklin </PERSON> transport theatergoers around the globe _ from rustic <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> to a bizarre troll underworld to the sands of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> to a <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION> madhouse to a ship wrecked in a raging sea and then back again to <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>. But <PERSON> Lamos </PERSON> does n't forget this tale is one man's story of self-discovery, from brash, self-centered, carefree and charming youth to cynical, even despairing, old man who finally finds redemption through the love of a forgiving woman. Negotiating the sweep and intimacy of <PERSON> Lamos </PERSON>' production is actor <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>. He plays Peer with a fierce determination. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, who was a robust, non-melancholy <PERSON> Dane </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION>'s `` Hamlet'' last year, is one of those fearless, energetic actors, willing to take a chance. Despite his eagerness, he does n't rush through <PERSON> Ibsen </PERSON>'s difficult poetry, done here in a new, very modern translation by <PERSON> Gerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Bamman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Irene </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Berman </PERSON> They follow the playwright's original rhyme schemes <PERSON> Bamman </PERSON> played the older Peer in <PERSON> Livui </PERSON> <PERSON> Ciulei </PERSON>'s production of the play in 1983 at the Guthrie Theater in <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lamos </PERSON> saw that revival and thought about doing it at <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION>. `` The play has always been sitting there in my mind, waiting, I guess,'' <PERSON> Lamos </PERSON> says. `` Every year it would come up, and we've talk about it. But after <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> played ` Hamlet' here, we decided to do it.'' In fact, <PERSON> Lamos </PERSON> said if it were n't for <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, he would n't have attempted the mammoth revival. The actor, according to <PERSON> Lamos </PERSON>, exuded `` a willingness to take a journey with ` Peer Gynt' that really did n't always seem as if it had a purpose or a goal to it. That was really the best part of the rehearsal process. We just kept looking at each other and saying, ` Well, let's just keep traveling. We are n't going to get all the answers right away.''' <PERSON> Lamos </PERSON> felt he would get to know the play better if he could collaborate with <PERSON> Bamman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Berman </PERSON> as they worked on the translation, which was commissoned by <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION> Stage. `` It was a wonderful way of learning ` Peer Gynt' from the inside out and without preconceptions and not taking anything for granted,'' <PERSON> Lamos </PERSON> says. `` Literally, each moment in the play had to be dealt with very, very carefully and specifically. `` The big surprise was that we found out that a lot of the existing translations were glossing over more of the crudities <PERSON> Ibsen </PERSON> was after and more of the slang that he definitely put into the play. At first, things that we were criticizing in the early drafts we discovered were, in fact, <PERSON> Ibsen </PERSON>'s intentions. `` And that made a huge difference in the whole approach to the play. It was one of the reasons the production became more childlike and naive and began to have more of a folk quality than I originally thought it would have.'' <PERSON> Conklin </PERSON>'s settings re-enforce that theme, beginning with the opening moments of the play. The stage is decorated like a surrealistic nursery in which Peer lounges in a cradle or commands a rocking horse as if it were a galloping steed. The director and designer have created several memorable images, the most poignant being the death scene of Peer's mother at the end of `` Into the Mountains,'' which is Part 1 of the play. The mother, beautifully played as a loving scold by <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Conolly </PERSON>, is transported to her grave in Peer's cradle now turned into a sleigh and driven by her son. In Part 2, `` The Voyage,'' <PERSON> Conklin </PERSON> fills the stage with billowing black plastic which becomes the violent sea that finally washes Peer back home. The designer uses yards of fabric to cover the theater floor, creating snowy mountains, yellow deserts and green forests. More cloth hangs like a curtain over the theater's back wall, allowing lighting designer <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> to conjure up mountains as well as spectral images. <PERSON> Conklin </PERSON>'s original designs were more complicated, <PERSON> Lamos </PERSON> says. `` At first, <PERSON> John </PERSON> created a set model which was filled with large and colorful scenery,'' he said. `` We slowly took pieces out of it until we came to something much simpler and realized we wanted something that had more fluidity. That's when we arrived at the idea of these thousands of yards of flowing <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> silk and the shadows that they made behind them.'' The large cast matches <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>' enthusiasm, particularly <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Rowe </PERSON> as the vulgar, hedonistic troll king who urges Peer to `` be yourself and nothing else,'' a motto that still has a large following today. For <PERSON> Lamos </PERSON>, the most challenging aspect of the production was `` to stay open and not try to contain the play with a metaphor of some kind. I just let it be what it turned out to be, and then it began to unify itself in a funny way.'' What can <PERSON> Lamos </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION> Stage do for an encore? The director is not thinking about that just yet. `` I do n't even want to browse through my drama book shelf at home,'' <PERSON> Lamos </PERSON> sighs. `` I just want to go look at the ocean for a while.''
</TEXT>
