<FIRST>s a BC-APN--SnowTrain ADV30   04-17 1158</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Snow Train, ADV 30,1193</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 30</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w photo.)</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 It's called the Snow Train or the Moose Meat Special, depending on the time of year and the interests of its passengers, and for tourists it's a way to pierce the wilds of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> without severe damage to the household budget. First built to haul iron ore and timber out of the hinterland north of <LOCATION> Sault </LOCATION> Ste. <PERSON> Marie </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Algoma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railway </ORGANIZATION> was later discovered by hunters, artists and sightseers.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By PAIGE St. JOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAULT STE. MARIE, Ontario (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The train is highballing through an awesome crack in the Earth's surface, on a scenic journey to nowhere and back. Inside the no-frills passenger cars, steam heat and the morning sun fog the wide windows. A bored kid punches his sister in the arm. She wails. Their grandmother is preoccupied with the vista outside the window, pristine soft snow and black rock, snow so deep it reaches the roofs of fishing cabins. In the dining car, a young couple from <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> asks if they can get American bacon instead of Canadian bacon with their eggs. Three happy-go-lucky guys lurch down the aisle without spilling a drop from their open cans of beer. All had crossed the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> border at <LOCATION> Sault </LOCATION> Ste. <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> and bought a $ 35 ticket for an eight-hour, round-trip train ride through the Canadian wilderness to <PERSON> Eaton </PERSON> 120 miles to the north. Ninety years ago, the <ORGANIZATION> Algoma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railway </ORGANIZATION> first pierced the Canadian hinterland. It was built to bring iron ore out of <LOCATION> Wawa </LOCATION> and timber out of <ORGANIZATION> Hearst </ORGANIZATION>. Then it was discovered by artists, sportsmen and tourists, who know it by such names as the Snow Train or the Moose Meat Special, depending on the time of year. Business is brisk in the snowbound winter, gets even better during the spring and summer. Today, <PERSON> Lucy </PERSON> <PERSON> Dassance </PERSON> was riding the rail with her daughter's family, the seven of them among the hundreds of Americans who take <ORGANIZATION> Algoma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION>'s weekend tour each year A local makes regular stops along the way during the week, but on the weekend sightseeing run there are no stops. No depots. Just ride to the end of the line, get up, turn your seats around and ride back. `` My husband did n't come,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Dassance </PERSON> says. `` He said he had enough snow back in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>.'' Outside, a cold wind rips through <LOCATION> Agawa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canyon </LOCATION>, tearing at the rock walls with ice crystals, further eroding this wild, open cut in the Earth's skin. The Agawa Canyon has been molded by erosion and sculpted by glacier. Up close, it is a narrow cleft in the dark, gray rock through which a river tumbles and the railroad runs. Giant pressures thrust up granite mountains so long ago the range has eroded to its jutting, broken spine. Volcanic fissures shot up veins rich with minerals: gold, iron, phosphate, silica sand. It takes a satellite to show the gorge's true nature _ a 90-mile north-south crack in the planet, says <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Frey </PERSON>, a staff geologist for <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> and Mines. `` The rail line follows a natural weakness in the Earth's crust. It's a major fault.'' Agawa means `` sheltered place'' to <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Stone </PERSON>'s people, the <LOCATION> Ojibwa </LOCATION>. From <PERSON> Michipicoten </PERSON> <PERSON> Harbour </PERSON>, near the rail's midpoint, Stone guides American hunters and tells black bear legends handed down from his father and grandfather. Stone's stories also include a topical account of the 1850 treaty his people signed with the Crown, giving away land that 30 years later was granted to the railroads to open up <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>. The mining and timbering produced small towns along the track _ <ORGANIZATION> Hawk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Junction </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Batchawana </LOCATION>, Searchmont _ but so much of the territory remains a wilderness that game hunters ride in by rail, shoot their quarry and then flag down the train for the ride back. In October, moose season, the <ORGANIZATION> Algoma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railway </ORGANIZATION> adds cars to carry the quarry. They call it the Moose Meat Special, but moose is n't the only meat on board. `` I've seen bear ride the train, too,'' <PERSON> Stone </PERSON> says. You could get there by road, in many places, but that loses the romanticism, he says. There was no road beyond <LOCATION> Batchawana </LOCATION> when the <ORGANIZATION> Algoma </ORGANIZATION> line attracted its first train tourists _ a band of rebel Canadian artists called the Group of Seven. In 1918, some of these radical artists hopped a caboose in <LOCATION> Sault </LOCATION> Ste. <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> to ride into the wild <ORGANIZATION> Algoma </ORGANIZATION>. They shunted from siding to siding, sketching the strong land with wild Picasso skies on the inside covers of their cigar-box palettes. The art world laughed but the Seven prevailed. They would become some of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s most famous artists. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> understands what drew the Seven. At 66 and retired from <ORGANIZATION> Algoma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> is starting a career in art, following the path laid by the Seven and mapped personally for him. `` I have been in the area,'' he says. `` I have stood in the spot where J.E.H. <PERSON> MacDonald </PERSON> did ` The Solemn Land.' You can feel it.'' Decades after the train trips, <PERSON> Murray </PERSON>'s sister-in-law rented a summer cottage to a returning member of the Seven, A.Y. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> was born to the land but he never saw it as `` the rich, strong North'' until <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> showed him how. `` He opened my eyes,'' <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> says. To <PERSON> Stan </PERSON> <PERSON> Black </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Algoma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railway </ORGANIZATION> is more than art and recreation. It is commerce. <PERSON> Black </PERSON>, a vice president of the company, says the railroad last year moved 1.4 million tons of iron ore, limestone and coke. The railroad carried an additional 1 million tons of manufactured products such as steel and almost half as much timber and wood pulp, he says. But there is a shadow across Black's figures. Eighty percent of the railroad's life comes from freight traffic. The biggest hunk _ as much as 57 percent _ is jeopardized by <ORGANIZATION> Algoma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION>'s talks of closing the <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> MacLeod </PERSON> iron ore mine in <LOCATION> Wawa </LOCATION>. It not only is the only producing iron ore mine on the line, but it is also the very mine the <ORGANIZATION> Algoma </ORGANIZATION> railroad was built to serve in 1899. At <LOCATION> Eton </LOCATION>, 120 miles from <LOCATION> Sault </LOCATION> Ste. <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> -LRB- the Soo -RRB-, the tourist train stops. The seats are reversed and the tour starts back. Passengers fell asleep in the warm sun of late afternoon, rocked by the sway of the train. <PERSON> Margo </PERSON> <PERSON> Downing </PERSON> grabs some peace in a cup of coffee and a cigarette and vows she is going to quit her job as train tour guide. `` I used to enjoy this,'' she says. `` But there are some days when nobody's happy.'' She looked out the window at the spectacular view, the frozen waterfalls, the jagged cliffs. `` I know I'll miss this,'' she says. `` It's the one thing I'll really miss.''
</TEXT>
