<HEAD>$Adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 30</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w photo.
ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Little things bring home the reality of starring in a big Broadway play. People on the bus who ask, `` Did I go to high school with you?'' or `` Did you live in my mother's apartment building?'' Or the persistent gaze of strangers who give you the kind of stares that mean they either want to steal your purse or congratulate you on your performance. Such are the problems facing actress <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, who now has her name above the title in <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON> <PERSON> Wasserstein </PERSON>'s hit comedy, `` The <PERSON> Heidi </PERSON> <PERSON> Chronicles </PERSON>.'' `` I try to be nice to people, but it makes me embarrassed,'' says the quiet, almost shy <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, relaxing in her tiny dressing room backstage at the Plymouth Theater. `` Especially when they say ` Where do I know you from?' And then you have to stand there and say ` I did this and I did that' and listen to them say, ` No, No. No.' And finally, ` Oh, that's it!'' For <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, the Plymouth Theater has become something of a permanent home. She was there last season in <PERSON> Lanford </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>'s `` Burn This.'' She won a Tony Award as best actress for her portrayal of a grieving dancer mourning the death of her roommate. Now she is back with `` The <PERSON> Heidi </PERSON> <PERSON> Chronicles </PERSON>,'' which won the 1989 Pulitzer Prize for drama. In it, she plays art historian <PERSON> Heidi </PERSON> <PERSON> Holland </PERSON>, a witness to 20 years of changing attitudes toward women in modern <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. `` <PERSON> Heidi </PERSON> is a very complicated character,'' <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> says. `` The more I've done the play, the more I've learned about her.'' And she has had time to get acquainted with <PERSON> Heidi </PERSON>. The play began last December at off-Broadway's Playwrights Horizons, a small but important <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> company where such works as `` Sunday in the Park with <PERSON> George </PERSON>'' and `` Driving Miss Daisy,'' two other recent Pulitzer Prize winners, got their start. `` <PERSON> Heidi </PERSON> may not get involved, but she takes everything very personally,'' <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> says. `` She feels things deeply and sticks to her own path. Because she does n't rail at the winds, people find her to be some sort of a pushover. I do n't find her to be that passive.'' The play follows <PERSON> Heidi </PERSON> from the late'60s and the era of Vietnam War protests to the late'80s when the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> era has come and gone and the dreams of the baby boomers have begun to burst. The 32-year-old <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> came of age some seven or eight years later than the character she plays on stage. And with less turbulence. The actress is from <LOCATION> Rochelle </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, some 80 miles west of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. Her father, now retired, ran a gas station. `` It's farm country _ corn fields and soybeans,'' she says. `` It was very quiet and a great way to grow up. I was allowed to be a kid forever.'' <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> first went to <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> where as a freshman she studied drama and met <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Malkovich </PERSON>, a junior. The following year <PERSON> Malkovich </PERSON> transferred to <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and linked up with people like <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinise </PERSON>, <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinney </PERSON> and <PERSON> Laurie </PERSON> <PERSON> Metcalfe </PERSON>. Out of this group of young drama students came the <ORGANIZATION> Steppenwolf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>. After college, <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> joined the fledgling company which had found a home in the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> suburb of <LOCATION> Highland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>. To earn money, she kept a full-time job as a secretary for an educational film company. `` My experiences are n't like those of a lot of other actresses,'' she says of her early days. `` With Steppenwolf, I had a ready-made family. I would know what show I was doing, and I almost never auditioned during the entire seven years I lived in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. We read for parts among ourselves. It created a lot of security. We did n't have to keep proving ourselves.'' <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> kept her job as a secretary even when she was doing eight shows a week at <LOCATION> Steppenwolf </LOCATION>. Only when she came to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in 1983 with a <LOCATION> Steppenwolf </LOCATION> production of `` And a Nightingale Sang'' did she quit outside work. The success the previous year of <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Shepard </PERSON>'s `` True West,'' starring <PERSON> Malkovich </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sinise </PERSON>, made the move to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> easier for other <LOCATION> Steppenwolf </LOCATION> members. `` Until then, I had never been to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> _ not even to visit,'' <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> says. `` It was the right time in my life. I was in my late 20s, and it was a good role for me. Again I came with a <LOCATION> Steppenwolf </LOCATION> show, so there was a sort of built-in security.'' In `` Nightingale,'' <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> played a shy, crippled English spinster. From the show, <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> got an agent, rave reviews and a six-month run. She decided to stay in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and won a part in <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Durang </PERSON>'s comedy `` The Marriage of <PERSON> Bette </PERSON> and Boo,'' as well as movie roles in such films as `` Peggy Sue Got Married,'' `` Manhunter'' and `` Tucker.'' <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> teamed up with <PERSON> Malkovich </PERSON> for a year-long run in `` Burn This,'' which first played <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, then <LOCATION> Steppenwolf </LOCATION>'s theater in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and finally <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The month that `` Burn This'' opened on Broadway in 1987, <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> did a reading for `` The Heidi Chronicles.'' It was an early draft of the play, but <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> immediately knew she wanted to play <PERSON> Heidi </PERSON> when the comedy was done on stage. She got her wish. For the next six months or so at the <ORGANIZATION> Plymouth </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> will concentrate on <PERSON> Heidi </PERSON>, refining the character. `` When we started rehearsals, <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON> would drop telling comments about the kind of woman <PERSON> Heidi </PERSON> was and then I would use my imagination,'' <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> says. `` We also sat in on some art history lectures and talked to different art historians.'' The actress also met with well-known feminist art historian <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Nochlin </PERSON> who teaches at the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>. She attended <PERSON> Nochlin </PERSON>'s graduate class and read her essay, `` Why are there no famous women painters?''. Still, the actress does n't know if her portrait of <PERSON> Heidi </PERSON> <PERSON> Holland </PERSON> will ever be complete. `` That's what is so good about the theater,'' she says. `` It's an alive art form You keep working on something and hopefully, the more you do it, the better you get at it.''
