<SECOND>BC-Continent in Crisis-Chile, Adv 23-2 Takes,0715</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 23, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>CONTINENT IN CRISIS: Chile _ An Ominous Military Shadow</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 For the first time in nearly 20 years, Chileans will elect a president this year to replace an iron-fisted military leader. But it could be too early for rejoicing. This is another in a series of periodic reports by The Associated Press on the economic, social and political turbulence that has turned <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> into a continent in crisis.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lame ducks though they may be, <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>'s military leaders already are casting an ominous shadow over the civilian government that will take office next year They have made it unabashedly clear that while they will step aside they wo n't step out and will seize power again if they think it is necessary. And therein lies a major difficulty for the civilian who wins the presidential election Dec. 14 and takes over March 11 from Gen. <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, the iron-fisted president since 1973. The military government will bequeath a growing and stable economy to the civilians, but they also will leave deep and potentially explosive social imbalances. Millions of Chileans are still poor _ as they were when <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> led the military into the civilian disarray of September 1973 and overthrew President <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Allende </PERSON>, the Marxist who professed to want to help the poor. Recent opinion polls indicate that while Chileans have a relatively robust economy, low salaries and unemployment are high on their list of priorities for the civilian government. As politicians prepare for the election, <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> and other military leaders make it clear they do not plan a complete retreat from the political scene. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> recently said military leaders have the obligation to ensure that the future civilian president is `` an authentic democratic man.'' And the military is on record that it wo n't hesitate to intervene again. `` If the institutional order is broken, the armed forces have the duty to restore it, using compulsion and all the necessary means,'' Gen. <PERSON> Alejandro </PERSON> <PERSON> Medina </PERSON>, head of a center of strategic studies, said in a recent lecture to non-commissioned officers. Civilian politicians complain that will place the armed forces in the role of `` armed guardians'' of the civilian government. A constitution drawn up by the military government in 1980 gives the armed forces the means for such a role. It allows <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, who still commands the army, and the commanders of the navy, air force and national police to keep their posts until 1998. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, who is constitutionally prohibited from seeking re-election in December, has already said he will remain as army commander after the election. That is tantamount to `` creating an armed state within an unarmed democratic state,'' said <PERSON> Genero </PERSON> <PERSON> Arriagada </PERSON>, vice president of the centrist <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, the largest in the opposition. The constitution also established a military-dominated <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, which may `` represent'' its views to the civilian government on key matters. More complicated for the future leaders may be the problem of human rights violations during 16 years of military rule. Opposition leaders say that should they win the election, they will investigate the abuses and try those found responsible. The military leaders have made it clear, however, they it will not permit reprisals for what they see as actions that were part of a war. In the military years, thousands of leftists were arrested, many were sent into exile and hundreds were killed. Local and foreign human rights groups have documented more than 700 cases of dissidents who disappeared after being arrested by security forces. A recent opinion poll taken by the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION>, an independent research institute, however, indicates that Chileans are more interested in their personal economic situations than in the political complexities of the process to restore civilian rule or in the military threats to take power again. In a nationwide poll taken by the center in March and April, 46 percent of the respondents mentioned low salaries and inefficient public health services as the two top items on a civilian government's agenda.
</TEXT>
