<FIRST>s i BC-Turkey-Pressures Adv23-2Takes   04-17 0758</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Turkey-Pressures, Adv 23-2 Takes,0779</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 23, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Turkey Looks West But Feels Pull of East</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Turkish yuppies in bluejeans and miniskirts sip coffee at a fashionable waterside cafe on the Bosporous, seemingly oblivious of the Moslem faithful bent in sabbath prayers in a mosque just a few feet away. <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> is a country of such contrasts. <LOCATION> Istanbul </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ankara </LOCATION>, the centers of commercial, intellectual and parliamentary life, feature glittering Hiltons, shopping centers and traffic-clogged streets, while an hour's flight away are the horse-drawn carts and souks of <LOCATION> Diyarbakir </LOCATION> in the far east where politics are often inflamed by blood feuds. With one foot in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the other in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> yearns to be a part of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> but also feels the pull _ and bears the vestiges _ of the East. Its armies reached the gates of <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> three centuries ago but were beaten back in what was the start of the decline of the Ottoman Empire. Today <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> seeks to enter <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> peacefully, bidding for membership in the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- EEC -RRB-, the symbol of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> democracies' economic and political clout. It would fulfill the dream of <PERSON> Kemal </PERSON> <PERSON> Ataturk </PERSON>, the revered father of modern <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>, who put the overwhelmingly Moslem country on a Westward bent by turning away from Islamic law to build a republic based on separation of church and state in 1923. Turkish officials believe they have already paid their dues for admission to the West by fighting alongside <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops in <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and by membership in <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, protecting a land border with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. But the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> bid is seen as the acid test. `` It's one of the few subjects in which there's more or less a consensus in <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Inal </PERSON> <PERSON> Batu </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. He acknowledged, stressing <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>'s dilemma, that some Europeans think the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> `` is a club for Christians.'' Says <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Karper </PERSON>, general manager of <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Istanbul </LOCATION> and an American: `` Europeans have to become familar with <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>.'' But Turks, too, have become increasingly wary of signs of a rise of Islamic fundamentalism, which has seen women marching in the streets covered head to toe and strained <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>'s relations with neighboring <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. That, coupled with a history of military interventions to topple democratic governments and charges that torture in prisons persists, raises questions about how solid Western foundations are. On the other hand, since the military returned to the barracks in 1983, Premier <PERSON> Turgut </PERSON> <PERSON> Ozal </PERSON> has taken giant steps in shaping a <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> of the late 20th century. New airports, highways and power grids have gone up around the country, bringing electricity and direct-dial telephone service to remote mountain villages in the east. Vast housing projects are being built, replacing the `` gecekondu'' -LRB- meaning `` built overnight'' -RRB-, the shantytowns that gave <LOCATION> Ankara </LOCATION> and other cities a Third World look. Bankers are high on <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> as a safe place for foreign investment and cite its large domestic market and food resources. `` When you can feed people, they have more patience,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION>'s Karper. On the drawing board is a vast project to irrigate the barren southeast Anatolian plain, near <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>'s borders with <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, to further exploit <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>'s rich agricultural potential and stem the flow of peasants to the cities in search of work. In other words, development in a rush not only to get <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> on the European track but also to provide for a fast-growing population now at 55 million. But Turks, and now <PERSON> Ozal </PERSON> himself, have paid a price for this. <PERSON> Ozal </PERSON>'s liberal economic policies aimed at forcing Turkish industries to compete on European terms and heavy public spending have spurred economic growth but also triggered inflation running as high as 75 percent that has impoverished many Turks. This in a country where school teachers and other civil servants earn as little as $ 100 a month without wage indexing to protect against inflation so dear to <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s Socialist economies. Voters punished <PERSON> Ozal </PERSON> in nationwide local elections in March, sending his governing <ORGANIZATION> Motherland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> to a humiliating third place in the polls. But others factors were also blamed and tell much about <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> today. <PERSON> Ozal </PERSON>'s expressed sympathy for Moslem fundamentalist women, barred by the <ORGANIZATION> Constitutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> from wearing Islamic headscarves on university campuses, apparently cost him the votes of millions of `` secular'' Turks. The fundamentalist vote, about 10 percent of the electorate, went to a religious party.
</TEXT>
