<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--MedicalResidents-AIDS Adv20   04-17 1172</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Medical Residents-AIDS, Adv 20,1197</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, April 20, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AIDS Reduces The Ranks Of Residents At NYC Hospitals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Kings </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> is the <LOCATION> Parris </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> of American medicine, a sometimes hellish boot camp that tuns out seasoned professionals. It has 140 internists in training, more than any other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> institution, and some of the city's poorest and sickest people. Recruiting a few good men and women, however, has been getting harder and harder. Five years ago, 90 percent of the hospital's medicine residents _ staff doctors in training _ were graduates of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> medical schools; today, less than half are. Even in the worst years, <LOCATION> Kings </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> could count on getting 20 to 25 graduates of the medical school of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>, with which it is affiliated; last year not a single <ORGANIZATION> SUNY </ORGANIZATION> graduate applied, and only three of 60 first-year residents are from American schools. There are a many reasons why young doctors might shun a hospital like <LOCATION> Kings </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, but here's the most obvious: Half the patients in the internal medicine service have AIDS. `` That may have been the straw that broke the camel's back,'' says Dr. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON>, the medical school's provost. With more than 8,800 residents, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> hospitals train almost 10 percent of the nation's physicians _ three times more than any other city. But at a time when the hospitals need more residents than ever, the quality and quantity of applicants is declining. Leading teaching hospitals ca n't attract their top recruits, and others have scrambled to fill their residency slots with graduates of foreign medical schools. In recent years fewer <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> medical students have gone into less lucrative `` primary care'' specialities like internal medicine and pediatrics. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> seems to be having more trouble attracting such residents than other cities and one thing that sets it apart from them is AIDS. It has a fourth of the nation's cases, and in two years as many as 10,000 of its 25,000 general hospital beds could be filled by AIDS patients. Although the chances of doctors catching acquired immune deficiency syndrome from their patients are low, a survey at <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> hospitals found that fear of AIDS preoccupied doctors and gave them nightmares. Medical students `` can be so overwhelmed with AIDS patients you do n't get the broad experience a resident wants,'' says <PERSON> Caroline </PERSON> <PERSON> Reich </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Emory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, chairman-elect of student representatives to the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Colleges </ORGANIZATION>. A residency is supposed to expose young physicians to a wide variety of illnesses and patients; doctors worry that if too many of their patients have AIDS, their exposure becomes too narrow and their diagnostic skills atrophy. A residency is also supposed to be educational but AIDS patients are so sick that their care leaves little time for study or consultation with senior doctors. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> is chief of medicine at <LOCATION> Kings </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>. When he was making his hospital rounds as a resident 25 years ago, he usually had to spend only five to 10 minutes with each patient. `` A good proportion of them were n't particularly sick,'' he says. Now, though, `` one AIDS patient might require as much time and attention as six of the people I used to see,'' <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> says. `` It takes an enormous toll, physicially and emotionally, on our staff.'' AIDS is the health care crisis of the decade, but in much of the nation it remains an exotic curiosity. `` Most people who are looking to go into private practice do n't think they'll be seeing many AIDS patients and do n't feel they need an intensive exposure to AIDS during their residency,'' says <PERSON> Cindy </PERSON> <PERSON> Osman </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Brown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Student </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Some doctors and students argue that caring for AIDS patients is good training. `` It does n't sound nice to say it, but AIDS patients have lots of medical problems, and the sickest patients are often the ones you learn the most from,'' says <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Samuels </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Syracuse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, who plans to do his pediatric residency a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> hospital. The real problem may not be AIDS per se but the type of AIDS patients increasingly entering <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> hospitals: intravenous drug abusers. Nationally, AIDS is spreading fastest among drug users, their sex partners and children, and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> has about a third of all such cases. Drug abusers have surpassed gay men in newly reported cases in the city. The average drug-addicted AIDS patient is a physician's nightmare: he requires vast amounts of care, although very little can be done to help him He frequently fails to follow medical instructions, and often resents the doctor's inability to halt his decline. `` An important part of medicine is identifying with the patient, knowing how to talk to them,'' says <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Caldwell </PERSON>, a student at <ORGANIZATION> Mount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sinai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. `` But that's so lacking with a lot of these AIDS patients. `` I have nothing in common with a male prostitute drug addict. I have sympathy for him, but I ca n't empathize.'' Homosexual men, on the other hand, are generally regarded as good patients. They tend to have supportive relatives and friends and a respect for medical authority. At <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>, which has relatively few drug addicts, applications for internal medicine residencies has increased. The burden of caring for AIDS patients is accentuated by a shortage of nurses and support staff. That translates into the bane of every resident _ scut, hospital slang for necessary but non-medical tasks that can be performed by non-physicians, such as taking blood or delivering medical records. If students think <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> is short of people to help with scut, they'll give its hospitals a wide berth, said <PERSON> Clay </PERSON> <PERSON> Balentine </PERSON>, chairman of student representatives to the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Colleges </ORGANIZATION>. `` The time you spend pushing a wheel chair is time you ca n't spend reading.'' At elite institutions like <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Presbyterian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> University-Bellevue </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, AIDS and its related problems have merely made residency programs less selective. At others, it has meant an increase in the number of foreign medical school graduates hired as residents. Although everyone pays lip service to the notion that foreign medical school grads _ FMGs, as they're called _ are n't necessarily inferior to AMGs, the best teaching hospitals take virtually nothing but AMGs because they are a known commodity. This attitude, passed to students, guarantees segregation. `` If a program has a high percentage of foreign school grads, that program is that much less attractive to American school students,'' says <PERSON> Beth </PERSON> <PERSON> Aklo </PERSON>, a fourth-year medical student at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Connecticut </ORGANIZATION> and a student representative to the medical colleges association. `` While most of us feel that the good students at foreign medical schools are as as good as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> grads, the bad are really bad. They could n't get out of American schools. Doctors do n't want to work with other doctors who are weak.''
</TEXT>
