<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--FireAnts Adv20   04-17 0676</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Fire Ants, Adv 20,0690</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, April 20, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Spread Of Fire Ants Not Likely To Be Checked, Researcher Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TIFTON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Farmers and homeowners should probably just learn to live with fire ants, says a researcher who has been unsuccessful at stopping the imported pests whose sting sends 21,000 Americans a year to doctors. `` With today's technology, there's nothing out there that'll eradicate them,'' said <PERSON> Stan </PERSON> <PERSON> Diffie </PERSON>, a researcher at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION>'s Coastal Plain Experiment Station `` We can control them, but we ca n't eradicate them.'' <PERSON> Diffie </PERSON> and entomologist <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheppard </PERSON> are evaluating chemical and biological controls for the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> insect believed to have entered the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in Mobile, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, about 60 years ago. Since then, fire ants have spread to 270 million acres in the <LOCATION> Carolinas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>. Fire ants reproduce quickly and spread rapidly. In south <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, it's not uncommon to find 40 mounds per acre, which is n't a problem in pastures, but in fields where machinery is used `` you would have a problem,'' <PERSON> Diffie </PERSON> said `` They're a nuisance _ a people pest, whether it's unsightliness in your yards or stinging your kids,'' said <PERSON> Diffie </PERSON>. The ants' painful stings force at least 21,000 people to seek medical treatment each year, according to a survey of physicians in 13 states for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Allergy </ORGANIZATION> and Immunology Nearly 40 percent of those treated were in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, according to the survey, and 20 percent were in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. Thirty-two people died from stings last year, mostly people especially sensitive to the toxin and bitten more than once. `` People and physicians should take these stings seriously,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Rhoades </PERSON>, a pediatrician at the <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> who monitors medical problems caused by fire ants. People allergic to other kinds of insect stings should be especially cautious. The stings cause a burning sensation, usually followed by formation of pus around the site within 24 hours. But fire ants also help farmers by attacking pests such as ticks, worms and other insects that damage sugar cane, cotton and pecans. Up to 250,000 ants can live in each mound, which can extend up to six feet in the soil. `` They'll eat anything that's dead. You have to have something out there to clean up the carcasses,'' <PERSON> Diffie </PERSON> said. In the search for effective controls, <PERSON> Diffie </PERSON> has studied baits, pesticides and natural enemies such as nematodes and mites. He makes bait from corn grits soaked with soybean oil and poison. The bait, scattered on pastures and fields, is carried into fire ant mounds and kills ants that consume the mixture. Only a few ants in each colony are capable of reproduction. Fertile males and females have wings and mate in flight. Then the males die and the females establish new colonies. `` You have got to kill the queen,'' <PERSON> Diffie </PERSON> said. `` If you do n't, she'll just keep laying eggs.'' Common pesticides can kill fire ants, but do n't remain active long enough in the soil to be a long-term solution, he said. `` It would be nice if we could put them where we want them _ get them out of the yard and put them in the pecan orchards and sugar cane fields. But I'd rather see them gone altogether. If we did n't have them, we'd find ways to control the other pests.'' Concern about the environmental hazards has led researchers to look for biological controls, including microscopic worms known as nematodes, and straw-itch mites, which are a natural enemy of fire ants. `` Nematodes were mixed in water and poured over a fire ant mound. About 2 million nematodes could be mixed in two gallons of water,'' <PERSON> Diffie </PERSON> said. Those tests were n't considered very successful because only about 37 percent of the colonies treated with nematodes were destroyed. Mites were `` fairly successful,'' he said, `` But the cost is prohibitive as treatments are $ 5 per mound and two treatments are necessary.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for April 20</NOTE>
