 William </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Henry </PERSON>, <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON> vice president of marketing. `` Our opportunity with <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON>'s is to appeal to a lot of people in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> who have never even had a <ORGANIZATION> Stroh </ORGANIZATION>'s,'' said <PERSON> Hal </PERSON> <PERSON> Riney </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> advertising executive who created the new campaign. `` And there are millions of those.'' <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON> will spend $ 20 million on <PERSON> Riney </PERSON>'s new ads, which will stress both the new packaging and the company's 200-year heritage as a family enterprise. <ORGANIZATION> Anheuser-Busch </ORGANIZATION>, by comparison, spent an estimated $ 130 million in 1988 just to advertise Budweiser. Another industry expert questioned whether <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON> could overcome the growing piles of money that <ORGANIZATION> Anheuser-Busch </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> are throwing into a market diluted in recent years by beverages other than beer. `` I know of no brewers in the history of the brewing industry who have ever turned around a brand after a serious slide,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinberg </PERSON>, head of R.S. <ORGANIZATION> Weinberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>. `` It's a very unforgiving industry.'' <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON> still has other brands on which to fall back, including <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Schlitz </PERSON> and <PERSON> Schaefer </PERSON>, all of which it acquired earlier this decade. But officials are hopeful of reviving the company's namesake brand. `` In my 11 years here, this is the most striking set of changes I've seen,'' <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON> president <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Fridholm </PERSON> said. `` I think we have 