<HEAD>Coatings, Chemicals Pace Record First Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> PPG </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said today that higher sales and operating earnings in its coatings and chemicals businesses helped produce the company's best first quarter ever, with a 9 percent profit increase. The company said after-tax earnings rose to $ 129.8 million, or $ 1.15 per share, in the first 1989 quarter from $ 118.6 million, or $ 1.07 per share, in 1988's first quarter. Sales increased 6 percent to $ 1.459 billion from $ 1.373 billion. Lower sales of flatglass and unfavorable currency transactions washed out sales gains for original and replacement auto glass, the Pittsburgh-based company said. Sales of glass, <ORGANIZATION> PPG </ORGANIZATION>'s leading product, slid 1.7 percent to $ 588 million from $ 598 million. Operating earnings for the unit dropped 18.3 percent to $ 94 million from $ 115 million. Increased sales of automotive paint and industrial coatings and progress in controlling costs overcame the less favorable currency exchange rates in <ORGANIZATION> PPG </ORGANIZATION>'s second-largest line. Unit sales rose 10 percent to $ 512 million from $ 465 million, and operating earnings rose 17.6 percent to $ 80 million from $ 68 million. Improved prices and sales volume for most basic and specialty chemicals, including a new chemical plant in <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, helped lift the unit's revenue 40.7 percent to $ 315 million from $ 261 million and boost operating earnings 20.6 percent to $ 76 million from $ 63 million.
