<HEAD>Lockheed To Deliver Last Of 50 C-5B Planes To Air Force</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with last plane delivered; PICKS
UP 5th graf pvs, `The C-5B ...' Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> today delivered the last of 50 C-5B jumbo cargo planes to the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>, completing a seven-year, $ 6.9 billion contract that drew accusations of greed from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The final C-5B, the biggest air cargo carrier in the free world, took off after a ceremony, made a salute lap around <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in suburban <LOCATION> Marietta </LOCATION> and then headed for the air base at <LOCATION> Dover </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Del </LOCATION>. The company has no plans for further production of the C-5B, said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Z. </PERSON> <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON>, director of the C-5 program. <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautical </ORGANIZATION> is a division of <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> Calabasas </LOCATION>, Calif.-based aeronautics giant. The C-5B is 248 feet long, has a wing span of 223 feet and a 65-foot, T-shaped tail, high as a six-story building. The jet, an updated version of the C-5A, can carry almost any piece of the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s hardware _ two 50-ton M-1 tanks, for example. It has been used recently for such non-military missions as carrying equipment and supplies to the site of the Exxon Valdez oil spill in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and aid to the victims of the earthquake in the Soviet republic of <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> spokesman Capt. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Dolney </PERSON>. The huge contract has been a boon to the Atlanta-area, providing thousands of jobs and pumping millions of subcontracting dollars into 40 states. Today's ceremony marked a happy landing in the flight of the C-5B project. But it was a bumpy ride. <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> won the contract in 1982, beating out <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION>. The original pact was for $ 7.8 billion. Production of the plane's predecessor, the C-5A, was marred by revelations that the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> had purchased ineffective repair kits from <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> that included $ 229.94 nickel-sized washers. Shortly before the first C-5B was to be delivered in late 1985, it was discovered that tens of thousands of nuts on the planes had to be replaced because the ones installed were the wrong kind. The Pentagon accused the company of inflating the C-5B contract by as much as $ 500 million by withholding details of a proposed two-tier wage system for its new employees; by 1987 the price tag had been whittled down to $ 6.9 billion. A review by the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' investigative arm, found that in late 1986 <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> proposed to charge the government $ 211.13 for an inch-long shim, a metal wedge that was an excess part from C-5B production and originally valued at $ 22.09 Last month, the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> said it had imposed flight restrictions on 20 C-5B's because of a problem with the pylon, the assembly that holds the jet engine to the wing. <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> has proposed to the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> that the plant maintain its C-5B tooling, company spokesman <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> said. `` Their decision will pretty much tell us what the future of the C-5B is,'' he said.
