<SECOND>BC-Earns-Boise Cascade,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Idaho Wood Products Company Reports Record Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Boise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cascade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Monday reported all-time quarterly records for profits, sales and earnings per share During the first three months of 1989, the Boise-based wood products company said after-tax income rose to $ 78.2 million, up 14 percent from $ 68.5 million in the same quarter a year earlier. Sales came to $ 1.1 billion in the latest quarter, up from $ 1 billion a year before. Earnings per share were $ 1.68 in this year's first quarter compared to $ 1.44 in the corresponding 1988 quarter. It was the second straight quarter and the sixth in the last seven in which new highs were posted in net income. `` We expect the company to have another excellent year in 1989 if the economy continues to grow at a modest rate,'' Chairman and Chief Executive Officer <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Fery </PERSON> said. `` Relatively strong markets for most paper grades and for office products should largely offset a soft market for newsprint.'' All three of the corporation's major segments _ paper and paper products, building products and office products _ posted increased sales and operating income over the first quarter of 1988. In the paper segment, which produces over half the company's sales, price increases for uncoated papers offset softness in the newsprint sector and continued tight margins in the corrugated container business as well as disruption of pulp and paper mill operations due to severe weather in February Office products posted record sales and operating income as volume increased 17 percent over a year earlier and the corporation maintained and increased its market share in almost every major urban area it serves, <PERSON> Fery </PERSON> said. The building products segment showed only modest improvement over a year ago, but the gain came despite the sale of three wood-products plants that were contributing to the corporate balance sheet during the first quarter of 1988. With prices for western lumber and plywood up from year-earlier levels, <PERSON> Fery </PERSON> said, `` We expect our building products segment to do as well as it did last year.''
