<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Fall In Europe</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs planned by 5:30 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar fell sharply Monday against major currencies in European trading after signs of a slowdown in the American economy. Gold prices also dropped. Foreign exchange dealers said recent <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic statistics had confused their market about whether the dollar was headed higher or lower and the uncertainty caused a drop. They said the main factors had been the 20.9 percent swelling in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit to $ 10.5 billion in February and the slowing of the growth rate in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> producer prices. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> consumer price index due on Tuesday could set the dollar's tone for the rest of the week, dealers said. One dealer said if the rise in the index is small, the dollar could drop from 1.85 German marks to 1.83. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, one British pound cost $ 1.7095 late Monday, more expensive for buyers than Friday's $ 1.7000. Other late rates for the dollar in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> compared with Friday's late rates: 1.8565 West German marks, down from 1.8725; 1.6385 Swiss francs, down from 1.6510; 6.2825 French francs, down from 6.3350; 2.0953 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1145; 1,364.00 Italian lire, down from 1,374.25; 1.1855 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1875 Earlier in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> the dollar closed at 131.83 Japanese yen, down from 132.55 at Friday's close. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> late Monday the dollar traded lower at 131.70 yen. Gold bullion traded late in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the major market, at $ 385.00 bid a troy ounce, down from $ 386.50. The late bid price in <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION> was $ 384.50, down from $ 387.00. Earlier in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold closed at $ 385.65, down from $ 382.65. Silver bullion traded late in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid $ 5.80 a troy ounce, down from $ 5.89.
