<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The start of multibillion-dollar industrial waste cleanups around the nation has triggered a legal war between insurance companies and corporate polluters over who should foot the bill. Insurers last week won their second battle in recent months, when a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> judge ruled that 126 insurers for former <ORGANIZATION> Diamond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shamrock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> bore no liability for injuries caused by the production of a toxic byproduct of the defoliant Agent Orange. Lawyers said the decision by <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Reginald </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanton </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Morristown </LOCATION> will have bearing on more than 50 similar lawsuits involving billions of dollars around the country. Potentially, the problem could involve thousands of cleanup sites. The Diamond Shamrock case is `` part of a larger struggle that's going on between the insurance industry and companies'' facing cleanup costs, said <PERSON> Jacquie </PERSON> <PERSON> Warren </PERSON>, a lawyer with the <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> In December, a jury found <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> liable for cleaning up the <LOCATION> Rocky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arsenal </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>, where the company leased land from the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> from 1952 to 1982 for a pesticide production plant. The jury ruled that <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> could not collect from its more than 250 insurers for cleanup and injury costs at the site estimated by the federal government in 1983 at $ 1.8 billion. `` I think that the insurance companies are now engaged in a massive nationwide effort in courts and the media to try to renege on their obligations to their policy-holder,'' said <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> lawyer whose firm represents more than 40 policy-holders fighting for insurance coverage. Judge <PERSON> Stanton </PERSON> ruled that <PERSON> Diamond </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON>'s insurance policies do not cover an industrial cleanup of more than $ 25 million because the company knowingly bypassed environmental controls, polluting the <LOCATION> Passaic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> and land around a <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION> plant with dioxin. The company, then known as <ORGANIZATION> Diamond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alkali </ORGANIZATION>, made Agent Orange and other herbicides at the <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION> plant from 1951 to 1969. A byproduct was dioxin, which has been linked to various cancers, liver disease, birth defects and a severe skin rash. `` Diamond's conduct in operating the <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION> plant was unacceptably wrong and irresponsible,'' <PERSON> Stanton </PERSON> wrote in a 50-page opinion. `` Diamond always put its narrowly perceived economic interest first. It deliberately and persistently cheated on the limited environmental regulations which were in place.'' But <PERSON> Stanton </PERSON> did order the insurers to pay the company's $ 23 million share of a $ 180 million settlement with <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> War victims of Agent Orange, which was used to strip natural cover from guerillas. For <ORGANIZATION> Maxus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Diamond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shamrock </ORGANIZATION>'s parent, the cleanup cost in <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION> will exceed $ 25 million. <ORGANIZATION> Maxus </ORGANIZATION> said it intervened as soon as dioxin was found at the site in 1983 and cooperated with environmental officials in its removal. Diamond Alkali was a predecessor of <ORGANIZATION> Diamond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shamrock </ORGANIZATION>, which was sold to <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in 1986. <ORGANIZATION> Maxus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> assumed liability for cleanups of certain sites, including the <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION> plant. After the 1986 sale, <ORGANIZATION> Maxus </ORGANIZATION> set aside a $ 75 million reserve for cleanup costs, spokeswoman <PERSON> Ginger </PERSON> <PERSON> Shearburn </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Maxus </ORGANIZATION> called <PERSON> Stanton </PERSON>'s ruling on the dioxin `` incorrect'' and is considering an appeal. Its stock dropped 12 -LCB- cents to $ 7.62 -LCB- Wednesday, a day after the decision was released to lawyers, and was trading in the $ 7 range Monday. <PERSON> Stanton </PERSON>'s ruling goes against much of the state's case law on the subject, which is generally favorable to policy-holders, lawyers said. More than a dozen such lawsuits have been filed in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, the most in the nation. Diamond Shamrock sued its insurers over the <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION> plant in 1984. Two years later it again sued its insurers, seeking coverage for about 20 non-dioxin sites nationwide. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bates </PERSON>, attorney for <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Re-Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <ORGANIZATION> Princeton </ORGANIZATION>, a defendant in the <LOCATION> Morristown </LOCATION> lawsuits, said <PERSON> Stanton </PERSON>'s decision could have a major impact on the second case, in which cleanup costs were not available Ms. <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, an environmental activist group, said insurance policies should be expensive enough and companies should assume enough risk to guarantee they handle and dispose of dangerous materials properly. But she added that society needs an `` insurance cushion'' to protect an innocent third party if a company can not pay for a cleanup. `` It's a fine line to draw,'' she said.
