anagement, creditors and the unions show cause why he should n't put the entire airline up for auction, including assets owned by <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> before <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> bought it three years ago. `` We are not here selling a used car at a foreclosure sale,'' creditors committee attorney <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Zweibel </PERSON> told the judge. `` We are selling a complicated business.'' At the urging of <PERSON> Zweibel </PERSON> and lawyers for Eastern management, <PERSON> Lifland </PERSON> gave them one more week to negotiate and review possible options for the Miami-based airline, one of the nation's largest and most unprofitable. He set a new hearing for 11 a.m. next Monday. <PERSON> Lifland </PERSON> granted the delay over the objection of attorneys for the unions and a dissident creditor who sought the hearing. They have been pushing for more aggressive court action to get Eastern flying again, either through a sale or the appointment of an outsider to run the airline. Eastern management has said it wants to restructure into a much smaller operation. Eastern workers have been on strike since March 4, charging <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> boss <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> has butchered it and plotted to destroy their unions by transferring valuable assets to sister carrier <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> put Eastern into bankruptcy court refuge March 9 and sought a buyer. <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON>, the former baseball commissioner and Olympics organizer, nearly completed a $ 464 million deal to buy <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> but the sale collapsed. However, sources familiar with the Eastern situation have said <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON> remains interested in making a new offer. <PERSON> Pritzker </PERSON>, owner of the Hyatt hotel chain, and <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, also have been lurking in the background as possible buyers. After the <PERSON> Lifland </PERSON> hearing today, pilots union attorney <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> attorney <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> told reporters there was a fourth bidder. In a statement issued today, <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> was quoted as saying the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> board believes a sale of Eastern `` is not in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Air or <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s best interests or in the best interests of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s creditors. The board made the decision at a meeting this morning and its vote was unrelated to <PERSON> Lifland </PERSON>'s action today, <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Art </PERSON> <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> said from the company's headquarters in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. The statement said: `` In order to resolve promptly the Eastern situation, <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> had been willing to agree to a quick sale -LRB- even at a price which did not nearly reflect <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s net asset value -RRB- and had selected the prospective buyer _ the group led by <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON> _ who it believed was most likely to be able to consummate a transaction promptly. `` With the collapse of those efforts, because of totally unreasonable and unworkable union demands, <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> has determined that further sale efforts are unlikely to be successful, and in fact, would be counterproductive.'' <PER