<HEAD>Animal Rights Groups Put Issues Before Shareholders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEAN GOLEMBESKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In a growing movement to force corporations to disclose more information about animal experimentation, animal-rights activists are taking their fight directly to shareholders. This year, shareholders at 10 companies will vote on resolutions proposed by animal-rights activists, an increase of two over 1988, according to the Washington-based Investor Responsibility Research Center. `` It's a thoughtful and sophisticated way to encourage companies to seriously consider questions of humane treatment of animals in connection with their business,'' said attorney <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Lovenheim </PERSON>, who has represented about a dozen groups seeking animal-rights resolutions. Corporations generally have opposed the proxy resolutions. After years of fruitless picketing against <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Surgical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s use of dogs in product tests, activists secured a resolution on the company's proxy ballot for its May 2 annual meeting demanding a halt to the tests People for the <ORGANIZATION> Ethical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treatment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Animals </ORGANIZATION> has proxy resolutions asking eight corporations _ <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Avon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Bristol-Meyer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Colgate-Palmolive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Greyhound </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Schering-Plough </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Johnson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGAN