PERSON> Lovenheim </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> has supported every resolution he has proposed or defended, despite corporate objections. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Anti-Vivisection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> last week filed suit in federal court in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> against Norwalk-based <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Surgical </ORGANIZATION>, charging the company used false information in recommending that a resolution calling for suspension of animal testing be rejected. The society has owned 66 shares of <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Surgical </ORGANIZATION>, which manufactures surgical products, since 1983. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Surgical has been a target of protests by animal-rights groups for years, but the dispute drew national attention in November, when an animal activist allegedly planted a remote-controlled bomb outside the company's headquarters. Authorities said animal activist <PERSON> Fran </PERSON> <PERSON> Trutt </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> intended to detonate the bomb and kill <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Surgical Chairman <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Hirsch </PERSON>. No one was injured in the incident. Trutt is awaiting trial on a charge of attempted murder.
