<HEAD>1st-Qtr Profit Rises at Tribune, McGraw-Hill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said Monday its first-quarter earnings rose 14 percent from a year ago, while another media concern, <ORGANIZATION> McGraw-Hill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said an accounting change turned what would have been an earnings decline into a 15.6 percent increase. The Chicago-based <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said it earned $ 36.8 million, or 49 cents a share, in the three months ended March 26 compared with $ 32.2 million, or 42 cents a share, in the same 1988 period. First-quarter revenue rose 6 percent to $ 553 million from $ 522 million in 1988. <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> said its operating profit from newspapers including the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> rose 19 percent to $ 61.6 million as revenue rose 5 percent to $ 394 million. Its broadcasting and entertainment group had an operating loss of $ 1.4 million in contrast with a loss of $ 3.5 million in the same quarter in 1988 despite a 15 percent rise in revenue to $ 105 million. The division includes six TV stations, five radio stations, a syndicated TV news program and the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cubs </ORGANIZATION> baseball team. Operating profit from its newsprint operations fell 27 percent to $ 16.7 million on steady revenue of $ 109 million. <ORGANIZATION> McGraw-Hill </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said its profit rose to $ 31.2 million, or 64 cents a share, in the three months ended March 31 compared $ 27 million, or 56 cents a share, a year earlier. First-quarter revenue rose 5.2 percent to $ 416 million from $ 396 million a year earlier. The publishing and information services concern said an accounting change involving income taxes boosted its first-quarter profit by $ 8 million, the cumulative effect of the accounting change in previous years. It said without the change, made in accordance with <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> standards, the company's profit would have fallen 14 percent. <ORGANIZATION> McGraw-Hill </ORGANIZATION> said its pre-tax income tumbled 27.8 percent, reflecting sale of assets including a professional training system, healthcare publications and an accounting software business. That was partially offset by tax benefits from those sales, the company said. Its publishing division which includes Business Week magazine, four television stations and its educational publishing business had an operating loss of $ 8.1 million in contrast with a loss of $ 3.3 million a year earlier. The wider operating loss reflected costs of starting a new reading series and the acquisition of <ORGANIZATION> Random </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>'s college and school divisions for $ 200 million last December. The operating profit at its information services division fell 13.2 percent to $ 28.8 million. That division provides data in a variety of forms to the construction, legal, aerospace and energy markets among others. <ORGANIZATION> McGraw-Hill </ORGANIZATION>'s financial services unit had an operating profit of $ 28.2 million, up 34.3 percent from a year earlier. That division includes the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's debt ratings as well as equity and commodity information.
