<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The stock market closed narrowly mixed in light, featureless trading today, as investors turned cautious ahead of Tuesday's consumer price report. The market opened lower, rebounded briefly then edged downward through the remainder of the session as many participants retreated to await the latest economic data. Analysts said the market is expecing a rise of between 0.4 percent and 0.6 percent in the consumer price index, which is a gauge of the cost of living. In February, consumer prices rose 0.4 percent. `` The whole world revolved around that number today,'' said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` People were reluctant to take positions pending the outcome.'' On Friday, the market had rallied sharply after the government reported that the producer price index rose 0.4 percent in March. The market interpreted the data as good news after rises of 1 percent in each of the previous two months. Economists said the <ORGANIZATION> PPI </ORGANIZATION>, a measure of inflation at the wholesale level, was in line with other data that suggested the economy is slowing and that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> probably would not be pushing interest rates up in the immediate future. `` People realized that Friday might have been too much too soon,'' said <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Puccio </PERSON>, senior vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Dillon </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Read </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co. Even before trading activity slowed, analysts said volume was fairly light with many players taking the week off in preparation for the Jewish holiday of Passover on Wednesday.
