<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar lost ground Monday against most other major currencies in worldwide foreign exchange trading tempered by anticipation of yet another report due Tuesday on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> inflation. Gold prices edged up in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> trading after falling overseas. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> quoted an after-hours bid for gold at $ 385.30 a troy ounce, up 30 cents from Friday's late bid. Traders have grown increasingly uncertain about the prospects for the dollar as recent <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic reports provided an inconclusive view of the economy. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit widened in February, but the growth in producer prices slowed in March and the level of industrial production held steady. Traders were looking to Tuesday's scheduled release on the consumer price index for March to see if inflation is slowing. `` We wo n't see any major direction until we see the CPI number,'' said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Barbanel </PERSON>, manager of futures trading at <ORGANIZATION> Gruntal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. He said trading was relatively quiet and there was no sign of central bank intervention in the currency markets. `` Foreign currencies are begining to generate an upswing and we may see a little bit of correction against the dollar in the short term. But in the long term, we still see the dollar relatively strong,'' he said. <PERSON> Barbanel </PERSON> said he did not think the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> would tighten credit conditions on the basis of a strong consumer price rise alone because the producer price figure showed slower growth in March. `` That gives short-term rates a respite for a while,'' he said. Rising <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest rates usually give the dollar a lift. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, the dollar fell to 131.83 Japanese yen from 132.55 yen on Friday. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar was quoted at 131.70 yen. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the dollar edged up to 132.155 yen from 132.05 yen late Friday. But the dollar finished lower against most other major currencies. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the British pound rose to $ 1.7095 Monday from $ 1.7000 late Friday. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the pound rose to $ 1.7133 from $ 1.7055 late Friday. Other dollar rates as of 4 p.m. in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with late rates Friday, included: 1.8605 West German marks, down from 1.86525; 6.3005 French francs, down from 6.3090; 1.6405 Swiss francs, 1.6465; 1,366.35 Italian lire, down from 1,368.63; and 1.18495, down from 1.18605. Late rates for the dollar in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with Friday's late rates, included: 1.8565 West German marks, down from 1.8725; 1.6385 Swiss francs, down from 1.6510; 6.2825 French francs, down from 6.3350; 2.0953 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1145; 1,364.00 Italian lire, down from 1,374.25; 1.1855 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1875. On <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Commodity Exchange, gold for current delivery edged up 20 cents a troy ounce to close at $ 386.20 an ounce. Earlier, gold traded at $ 385.00 a troy ounce in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, down from $ 386.50 late Friday. The late bid in <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION> was $ 384.50 an ounce, down from $ 387.00 on Friday. In <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold closed at $ 385.65 an ounce, down from $ 382.65. Silver