<HEAD>Palladium Prices Tumble; Profit-Taking Cited</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Palladium futures prices came crashing down Monday from 8-year highs as speculators took profits and lowered their expectations that nuclear fusion research would lead to explosive demand for the metal. Platinum futures also declined sharply while gold and silver advanced. On other markets, petroleum futures soared; grains and soybeans were sharply higher; and most livestock and meat futures also advanced. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, all palladium contracts except the spot April contract fell the permitted daily limit of $ 6 a troy ounce. The April contract, which has no limit pending its upcoming expiration, plunged $ 12.30 to $ 168.35 an ounce. Platinum settled $ 18 to $ 18.50 lower with July at $ 550.70 a troy ounce. Both metals were components in a <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> chemistry experiment, announced on March 23, in which researchers claimed to have recreated in a bottle the elusive nuclear reaction that powers the sun and stars. The discovery raised hopes that nuclear fusion could become a major energy source. Last Thursday, palladium rocketed to an 8-year-high and platinum surged to its highest price in four months as other scientists replicated the <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> experiment. But the speculative fever began cooling Friday and disappeared Monday morning amid media reports that the fusion research was not likely to create significantly stronger demand for palladium and platinum. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Demler </PERSON>, metals economist with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said both markets had become `` sorely overbought and due for a correction.'' Gold and silver futures inched higher on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Commodity Exchange in light, cautious trading ahead of Tuesday's government report on consumer price movement during April. Gold settled 20 cents to 30 cents higher with June at $ 390.10 a troy ounce; silver was 0.5 cent to 0.6 cent higher with May at $ 5.83 a troy ounce. Crude oil prices spurted above $ 21 a barrel on the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Merc </LOCATION> for the first time in 20 months. Analysts said the buying was inspired by chart signals rather than new supply-and-demand developments. The rally was led by the unleaded gasoline market, which has been moving higher since mid-February. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 8 cents to 53 cents higher with May at $ 21.22 a barrel; heating oil was .85 cent to 1.19 cents higher with May at 53.76 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was 1.05 cents to 2.06 cents higher with May at 72.08 cents a gallon. Corn and soybean futures surged on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> amid forecasts for dry and much warmer weather in the western Corn Belt later this week. Many traders remember the dramatic price increases for corn and soybeans that accompanied last summer's drought, and each day without rain in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> bolsters the bullish trend despite the fact that farmers in the region have barely begun their spring planting. `` This is awfully early to be having a weather rally,'' said <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Leighty </PERSON>, a grain-market analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. Wheat settled 2 -LCB- cents lower to 3 -LCB- cents higher with May at $ 4.10 \ a bushel; corn was 5 -LCB- cents to 6 -LCB- cents higher with May at $ 2.76 -RCB- a bushel; oats were 5 cents to 7 \ cents higher with May at $ 1.99 a bushel; soybeans were 10 cents to 15 -LCB- cents higher with May at $ 7.47 \ Higher cash prices for fed cattle fueled a moderate rally in cattle futures prices on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> and helped lift pork futures prices. Live cattle settled .20 cent to .62 cent higher with June at 71.32 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .18 cent to .65 cent higher with May at 76.45 cents a pound; live hogs were .03 cent lower to .55 cent higher with June at 46.62 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .32 cent to 1.20 cents higher with May at 33.62 cents a pound.
