<HEAD>Ford's Mustang Turns 25</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With fanfare and a closed-circuit broadcast, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> patted itself on the back Monday for the Mustang, introduced 25 years ago as an inexpensive sporty car that took the country by storm. `` It spawned a whole new class of cars,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Marsden </PERSON>, a professor of pop culture at <ORGANIZATION> Bowling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Green </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> who was on hand for the birthday party. `` The -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Chevrolet </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- Camaro would n't exist if the Mustang had n't come along.'' On April 17, 1964, about five weeks after the first one rolled off the line at the <LOCATION> Dearborn </LOCATION> assembly plant, the Mustang was introduced formally. Living up to the executives' promises, it weighed 2,570 pounds and cost $ 2,368. Since that day, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> has built and sold more than 5.7 million Mustangs, making millions of dollars off the cars. Its best sales year was in 1966, when 549,000 of the cars were sold. Its worst sales year was 1983, when 117,000 Mustangs were driven off dealers' lots The first Mustang, now in the <ORGANIZATION> Henry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Dearborn </LOCATION>, was sold to an airplane pilot in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Johns </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION>, in April 1964. The pilot, <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> now of <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION>, was convinced by <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> to trade in Job 1 for Job 1,000,001 two years later, so that the original could be preserved. On Monday, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> rolled out a vintage <PERSON> Mustang </PERSON> as officials and workers gathered to cut a cake in the shape of a <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> oval and topped by an edible model of a Mustang. Behind the ceremony, <PERSON> Mustangs </PERSON> continued to be assembled, at a rate of 52 an hour. The executives were brought to the plant's finishing area in <LOCATION> Mustangs </LOCATION>, of course, to the beat of <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickett </PERSON>'s tune `` <PERSON> Mustang </PERSON> <PERSON> Sally </PERSON>.'' The ceremony was telecast live to all <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> plants in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> through an in-house broadcast system. Plant Manager <PERSON> Lou </PERSON> <PERSON> Callaway </PERSON>, who began his <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> career at the <LOCATION> Dearborn </LOCATION> assembly plant and got a rousing cheer Monday when he stepped from a new Mustang, said in an interview before the birthday party there was a feeling that the car would do well even before it was introduced. `` You can always tell when a car is going to be successful,'' he said, `` because the employees are excited about it.'' One of the employees there when the first Mustang rolled off the line, and who is still working at the plant is <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Bevins </PERSON>, 62, whose enthusiasm for the car continues. `` We make the best cars in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Bevins </PERSON>, whose family has had three <ORGANIZATION> Mustangs </ORGANIZATION> _ a blue 1966, a blue'78 and a brown'80. They were all driven by other members of his family. `` I have a'77 -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` I refer to it as my truck.''
