<HEAD>Judge Lets Stand Injunction Against Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge Monday refused to modify an order preventing the free world's largest gold concern, South Africa-linked <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> S.A. </ORGANIZATION>, from acquiring any more shares of No. 2 gold producer <ORGANIZATION> Consolidated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gold </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fields </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>. The decision by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mukasey </PERSON> continues a preliminary injunction he issued last October barring <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION> from acquiring the 70.4 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Gold </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fields </ORGANIZATION> shares it does n't already own Last fall, <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION> corporation largely controlled by two South African concerns, <ORGANIZATION> Anglo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> De </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consolidated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, launched a $ 4.9 billion hostile takeover bid _ since upped to $ 6 billion _ for <ORGANIZATION> Consolidated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gold </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fields </ORGANIZATION>. But Gold Fields, a British concern, resisted and filed an antitrust action in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, claiming that a takeover could result in <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION>'s `` dominating the strategically important world gold market.'' `` This court enjoined the takeover because the resulting combination would control 32.3 percent of the non-communist world gold market,'' <PERSON> Mukasey </PERSON> said in a 45-page opinion issued Monday. <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION>, through its various holdings, is the largest gold producer in the West, accounting for 20.3 percent of all production. Gold Fields, with about a 12 percent share, is the second-largest, according to court papers. <PERSON> Mukasey </PERSON>'s injunction also prevents <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION> from selling its Gold Fields holdings to other entities within the South African conglomerate without court approval. <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION> sought to modify the injunction, allowing it to complete its acquisition of Gold Fields while promising to sell off certain <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, Australian and South African assets within a year to resolve antitrust allegations made by Gold Fields. But <PERSON> Mukasey </PERSON> rejected that bid saying there was no guarantee that <ORGANIZATION> Anglo </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> DeBeers </ORGANIZATION> would n't eventually repurchase the divested concerns because South African laws enable companies there `` to conceal the source of their overseas investments in order to avoid the effects of anti-apartheid laws.'' Last month, a federal appeals court upheld <PERSON> Mukasey </PERSON>'s preliminary injunction on antitrust grounds and ordered him to consider whether the takeover bid violates <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> securities laws. In Monday's ruling, however, <PERSON> Mukasey </PERSON> rejected Gold Fields' claims that <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION> had failed to fully disclose its South African interests in violation of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> securities laws Gold Fields sought to widen the scope of the injunction by claiming <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION> violated the anti-fraud provisions of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> securities laws, for allegedly `` making and false and misleading statements'' about how much control South African corporations and individuals have over it. Gold Fields claimed the Oppenheimer family of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> indirectly controls <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Anglo </ORGANIZATION> American and <ORGANIZATION> DeBeers </ORGANIZATION> and that the stigma of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s apartheid racial policy could make it difficult to conduct business in some countries. But <PERSON> Mukasey </PERSON> found those claims were only part of a delaying tactic to push <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION>'s offer past its April 26 deadline, which under British law would bar it from renewing its bid for more than a year. Gold Fields has significant gold mining holdings in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, including 90 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Newmont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gold </ORGANIZATION>, the largest gold producer in the country.
