<HEAD>Sculley Says Apple Will Stick To Its Knitting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> will stick to making personal computers for the mass market rather than going upscale in the battle against invaders like <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Microsystems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, Chairman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sculley </PERSON> said Monday. <PERSON> Sculley </PERSON> said some hot new technologies are too expensive and untried to be offered by <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> itself, although other companies may offer them as add-ons to the popular Apple Macintosh. Apple will offer the new technologies on the Macintosh once they become cheaper and better accepted, he said. As examples he cited artificial intelligence and digital signal processing chips, which take voices and video signals and turn them into code that can be acted on by a computer. <PERSON> Sculley </PERSON> appeared to be staking out the middle ground of the personal computer market as <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION>'s own, putting less emphasis on the high ground where <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> faces its sternest competition. <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Microsystems </ORGANIZATION> last week unveiled a family of low-priced Sparcstation computers that can zoom through more than 12 million instructions per second. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Jobs </PERSON>, who co-founded <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> and went on to create <ORGANIZATION> Next </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, is pitching a speedy Next workstation that comes in an elegant black magnesium box. <PERSON> Sculley </PERSON> said he does not foresee a collision between personal computers and workstations, which are cousins of PCs that cost more, run faster and have superior graphics. `` There are a lot of things you have to do to be successful in the personal computer industry beyond offering hardware under $ 10,000,'' <PERSON> Sculley </PERSON> said in a news conference. Sun's compact Sparcstation starts at less than $ 9,000. But <PERSON> Sculley </PERSON> said it is still about twice the price of the new Macintosh IIcx, which he described in an earlier speech as possibly the company's best computer ever. And he said software for the Sun machine is much more expensive than Macintosh software. Still, analysts say the Sun and Next machines are tough competition for the most expensive Apple models, such as the Macintosh IIx, which sells for $ 10,000 to $ 12,000. `` That's one of the reasons they want to emphasize the mid-range of the products. The competition is getting pretty fierce at the high end,'' said <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Lederman </PERSON>, an analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Duff </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Phelps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. She said she was concerned that waiting too long to put new technologies into the Macintosh could leave Apple playing catch-up `` I do n't think they're really any longer at the forefront of technology.'' <PERSON> Sculley </PERSON> gave the keynote address at the <ORGANIZATION> Macintosh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exposition </ORGANIZATION>, which was billed as the biggest Macintosh event ever in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. He followed the speech with a news conference.
