<FIRST>u f AM-OilAntitrust     04-17 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Antitrust,0656</SECOND>
<HEAD>California Court Revives Suit Against Oil Companies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal appeals court on Monday allowed the state of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> to go to trial with claims that six major oil companies conspired to depress the price of oil they pumped from state-owned tidelands in <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>. The suits in federal and state court claim losses to the state and the city of <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> totaling $ 789 million in 1971-77 and 1980-85. Damages tripled under antitrust law would exceed $ 2.3 billion, and could be increased further by $ 2,500-a-day penalties sought under state unfair-competition laws. Most of the claimed losses were to the state, which uses tidelands oil money for school construction. The city of <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> gets a small fraction of the oil money. The 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> voted 3-0 to reinstate the suits, which had been dismissed by U.S. District Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. The suits accuse the six companies _ <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> _ of holding down the prices they paid for heavy crude oil while agreeing secretly to exchange oil among themselves at higher prices. A seventh defendant, <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Richfield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, settled in 1984 by paying $ 22.5 million. Still pending before the appellate court is an appeal by <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and four other states from a ruling by <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> dismissing a separate antitrust suit against the same seven oil companies, which accuses them of conspiring to create a gasoline shortage and fix gasoline prices in the early 1970s. In Monday's ruling, the court said the state and city had presented enough evidence to proceed to trial with claims that the oil companies conspired to keep artificially low the prices they paid to <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> for heavy crude oil. <PERSON> Royce </PERSON> <PERSON> Schulz </PERSON>, a lawyer for the city, said retail prices for oil products in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> were about the same as those elsewhere in the period, an indication that the companies' actions did n't help consumers. `` Refiners simply pocketed that profit,'' he said. The suits contend the companies agreed secretly in the early 1960s, at meetings involving all of them except <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>, to keep the posted price for heavy crude below its real value, while exchanging different grades of oil among themselves at higher rates. Lawyers for <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> said the elaborate exchange procedure, unique to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, was disclosed by a state auditor in 1973 but was being used as late as 1984. Types of oil `` were used as a currency _ a medium of exchange and a new value system _ reserved to the majors -LRB- oil companies -RRB- and kept secret from the state and the city,'' <PERSON> Schulz </PERSON> said in a `` background paper'' on the case. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Halling </PERSON>, another partner in <PERSON> Schulz </PERSON>'s firm, said the secrecy of the exchange system let the oil companies evade a provision of their contract with <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> that required them to pay the city the highest price they paid any other seller of oil. But <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Destino </PERSON>, a lawyer for <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>, said the exchange system simply allowed oil companies to move their product to market while guaranteeing that they would get equal value when trading the same grade of oil from different sources. The appeals court said the exchange system did not amount to price-fixing by itself but could point to the existence of a conspiracy. `` At various times, market conditions should have caused some of the companies to post higher crude prices,'' said the opinion by Judge <PERSON> Jerome </PERSON> <PERSON> Farris </PERSON>. `` Posted prices did not correspond to market value.'' <PERSON> Farris </PERSON> also rejected <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>'s conclusion that federal price controls and other regulations during the 1971-77 period made it impossible for the city and state to show any damages, even if they could prove a price-fixing conspiracy.
</TEXT>
