<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Nuclear Regulatory Commission on Monday gave a <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> nuclear plant permission to resume operations, two years after it was shut down because 33 control room operators slept on the job or neglected their duties. The <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> voted 3-0 to lift an order that had kept the Peach Bottom nuclear plant closed since March 31, 1987, when the commission said its continued operation Posed a threat `` to the health and safety of the public.'' In granting permission to restart the facility, the commission nevertheless warned the plant operator against complacency. `` We will be watching you very closely,'' said <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lando </PERSON> <PERSON> Zech </PERSON>. Plant officials must complete a checklist of technical items before bringing the plant to full power, which will take several months and be scrutinized by <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> inspectors. The vote followed a presentation by <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the plant operator, which said it had undergone radical changes since the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> issued its order following a tip about the sleeping that prompted an investigation. The changes successfully addressed the `` root causes'' of the problem, the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> staff said in recommending that the commission permit the plant to restart. Those problems had included a lax Peach Bottom `` culture'' in which plant problems either were ignored or unnoticed by top managers, the staff said. `` It would at least appear to me that management -LRB- before the shutdown -RRB- either was not aware of conditions or, if they were aware of it, they condoned it,'' <PERSON> Zech </PERSON> said before the vote. `` The operators must never again betray the special trust and countenance of the public,'' <PERSON> Zech </PERSON> said. `` We will be watching you very closely.'' <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> Commissioner <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Curtis </PERSON> was out of the country, and missed the vote. Commissioner <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> did not vote because he once served on the <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> board, the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> said. The shutdown cost the company about $ 250 million in plant modifications, purchases of replacement power and its share of a $ 1.25 million fine, the largest in <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> history. Many of the problems at Peach Bottom occured on the overnight, or `` graveyard'' shift. On at least two occasions, according to <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> testimony in 1987, three of the four control room employees responsible for running the plant were asleep at the same time. Another time, several of the operators were found huddled around a personal computer playing video games. Of 39 control room operators now at the plant, 24 were there at the time of the shutdown, and all have been retrained. To end catnaps by operators, plant officials also replaced comfortable, high-backed chairs in the control room with low-backed models. In another development, meanwhile, <PERSON> Zech </PERSON> indicated the committee would vote Thursday on awarding a full-power license to the <LOCATION> Shoreham </LOCATION> nuclear plant on <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, after hearing the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> staff report that the $ 5.5 billion reactor is safe and ready to operate. All indications are that the full-power license will be awarded, but whether it will ever be used is doubtful. The <ORGANIZATION> Long </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Island </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lighting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> is one step away from selling the plant to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state for $ 1 in exchange for a decade of annual rate increases of up to 5 percent. The state would then decommission and dismantle the plant. <ORGANIZATION> LILCO </ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors is recommending that shareholders approve the plan to shut the plant. The final step to ratifying the settlement is a vote by <ORGANIZATION> LILCO </ORGANIZATION> shareholders on or before June 15. In the meantime, <ORGANIZATION> LILCO </ORGANIZATION> has agreed not to operate the plant even if it receives a 25 percent or full-power license before then. Shoreham, which was completed in 1984, 13 years behind schedule, received a low-power testing license in 1985. But <ORGANIZATION> LILCO </ORGANIZATION> was thwarted in its quest for an operating license because the state and local governments refused to participate in emergency planning, contending that area around the plant could not be safely evacuated in the event of a nuclear emergency. In late 1987, the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> changed its rules to allow utilities to prepare their own evacuation plans assuming that in the event of a real emergency, state and local governments would live up to their responsibilities and participate. <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> finally removed <ORGANIZATION> LILCO </ORGANIZATION>'s last obstacles to a license _ the state and local governments _ by dismissing them as legal intervenors before the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION>.
