<HEAD>Last-Minute Deluge Of Tax Returns In Mail</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs grafs 9-10, `Actually...' with 6 to add other events and
CORRECT that Conn. and part of N.Y. also affected by Mass. holiday. Also
moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Monday's midnight deadline for filing federal income tax returns brought the usual deluge of last-minute mailings as people held onto their money as long as possible, or procrastinated until time ran out. The <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> took a tip from the fast food industry in <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, where traffic was directed through the front parking lot of the city's main post office so people could drive through and hand their completed returns to postal workers stationed outside. `` Any returns we get by midnight, we'll make sure they get postmarked on the 17th,'' said <PERSON> Debbie </PERSON> <PERSON> Rinehart </PERSON>, a mail processing clerk at the <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION> main post office. People making the mad dash to beat the mailing deadline were offered entertainment or moral support to improve their mood in some cities. At <LOCATION> Lawrence </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Lawrence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barnstorm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cloggers </ORGANIZATION> band was to perform at the post office from 10 p.m. until midnight, said spokeswoman <PERSON> Laurie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mackey </PERSON>. `` We just want to lift people's spirits,'' <PERSON> Mackey </PERSON> said. In <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, rock station <ORGANIZATION> KLSX-FM </ORGANIZATION> offered coffee and donuts at the downtown Terminal Annex, the city's main mail processing center, which posted buckets at curbside until midnight. `` We want to add some merriment and not make the people feel bad that they're procrastinators,'' said <ORGANIZATION> KLSX </ORGANIZATION> disc jockey <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Tilden </PERSON>. In <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, a performance art group called <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stimulus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Response </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> prepared a show for its fourth annual Tax-a-thon outside the city's main post office. `` At midnight, we release balloons and scream ` It's too late!''' said <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> George </PERSON>, one of the participants. `` It's a touching moment. The feeling that they've got your money and there's nothing you can do about it.'' In some cities, protesters used the day to demonstrate against the use of income tax money for military purposes. Members of the Northern California War Tax Resistance, based in <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>, distributed $ 6,000 to various charities, saying the money came from people who refuse to pay all or part of their federal taxes because the money is used for `` war and war preparations.'' Actually, not everyone had to have their returns in the mail by midnight Monday. Residents of <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, upstate <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> got an extra day this year because Monday was a holiday, Patriots' Day, in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. Residents of those states mail their returns to the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> office at <LOCATION> Andover </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>. But for the rest of the country, April 17 was the deadline because April 15 fell on the weekend. <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON> <PERSON> Drake </PERSON>, a district manager who oversees 18 <ORGANIZATION> H </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> R </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Block </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> offices in <LOCATION> Dayton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, said that when he assured worried clients that they had not missed the filing deadline, `` it was like people on death row finding out they had gotten a reprieve.'' Whatever the deadline, <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> Form 4868 _ request for a filing extension _ is the most-requested form this late in the season, said <PERSON> Roslyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> office in South Bend, <LOCATION> Ind </LOCATION>. Officials of the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> center at <LOCATION> Fresno </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, said they expected to receive the majority of the 11.4 million returns from central and southern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> regions by Wednesday. As of last week, the center had received 5.9 million returns. But the deluge of work does n't mean <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> workers do n't have time for an occasional smile. In the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arkansas </ORGANIZATION> offices, laughs have sprung from requests for Form 911, which is reserved for taxpayers who cite unusual circumstances in requesting a speedy refund or relief from paying taxes, said <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Hubenak </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION>. `` One person in particular was trying to get us to speed up the refund check because he had pawned his tools, and wanted us to call the pawnbroker and explain it to him,'' <PERSON> Hubenak </PERSON> said. `` Another asked that they call a grocery store and say the check was on the way.''
