<HEAD>State Ecologist Says Just Half of Crucial Beaches Can Be Cleaned
by Winter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 15 grafs to UPDATE with state officials demanding
more beaches added to list, better water clean-up, amount of oil on beaches,
other details; CORRECT cleaning method is `hot-water' rather than `steam'
and that Haavig made estimate after reading plan. Picks up 12th graf, `Meanwhile,
wildlife...' ADDS 1 graf with Exxon Valdez deemed sound enough to travel
to Oregon. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos VDX1,2,3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> will hire 4,000 people to scrub at least 305 miles of shoreline fouled by <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s worst oil spill, and says the job can be finished by the third week in August, according to a plan released Monday. The cleanup can be be completed by August if a hot-water cleaning method that can damge beach life is used aggressively, or by mid-September if environmentally safer methods play a larger role, the draft plan says. Those projections were disputed by a state ecologist, who said after reviewing the plan that only about 150 miles could be cleaned before winter. And the top state environmental official called for the plan to be broadened to include areas where the oil has spread outside Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>. `` It's a start,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelso </PERSON>. `` It needs more work.'' The plan estimates that by June 1 the company will have 2,500 Alaskans working on the shoreline, with 1,500 other people in support roles. It says 11 barges, 28 landing vessels, 150 utility ships, and six wash-vacuum ships will be used. According to the plan, the total shoreline in Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON> affected by the March 24 <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valdez </ORGANIZATION> wreck is 366 miles _ about the distance from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, or <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz </LOCATION>. Concentration of oil on the beach runs from 1,260 gallons to 12,600 gallons per mile, with an average of 4,200 gallons per mile, the oil company said. The plan said <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> so far has recovered 924,000 gallons, or 9 percent, of the spilled oil. The plan proposes to clean up 305 miles. It estimates that 54 miles are heavily oiled, 86 moderately oiled and 165 lightly oiled. It assumes that needed permits will be promptly issued and that no additional oil will wash ashore. But <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Haavig </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> estimated after reviewing the plan that crews would be able to scrape and spray greasy black sludge from only about one mile of beach per day. `` A mile a day is optimistic,'' <PERSON> Haavig </PERSON> said. At most, there are 150 days from the time workers and gear are mobilized, two or three weeks from now, until winter descends in September. <PERSON> Haavig </PERSON> said crews might make good time on lightly oiled beaches, but the more heavily polluted stretches will slow them. Asked for comment, <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanczuk </PERSON> said the company wanted to confer first with the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> commandant, Adm. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Yost </PERSON>, who was sent by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to hasten the cleanup. <PERSON> Kelso </PERSON>, in a letter to <PERSON> Yost </PERSON>, demanded that <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> improve its cleanup of oil still in the water. He said the company should come up with a plan by April 25 to clean beaches beyond Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON> in the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, where the oil has spread. He said he also wants data on how to manage and dispose of wastes. Meanwhile, wildlife officials brought grim reports from the <LOCATION> Nuka </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nuka </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> area on the <LOCATION> Kenai </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>, about 175 miles southwest of where the Exxon Valdez smashed into <LOCATION> Bligh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Reef </LOCATION>. `` They found a lot of dead birds and a lot of live, oiled birds,'' <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Seaman </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fish </ORGANIZATION> and Game said in Homer. `` There's otter tracks on every beach.'' Part of the herring grounds at the north end of the <LOCATION> Kodiak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> remained closed Monday because of oil sightings. It was feared the more important herring fishery at <LOCATION> Kamishak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> might not be able to begin as scheduled later this week. Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON> lies south of <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION>, the seaport where the trans-Alaska oil pipeline ends. Until the spill, its waters and islands had been among the most scenic in the nation, and few places in the world are richer in wildlife and fish. <PERSON> Yost </PERSON> spent part of Sunday at <LOCATION> Block </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> in the sound, where muck was puddled ankle-deep in places. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> had assembled state and federal officials and reporters for a demonstration of cleanup methods, including an environmentally risky steam-cleaning technique that sterilizes the shore. <PERSON> Haavig </PERSON> also was on <LOCATION> Block </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, checking the depth of the beach contamination. In some places, the oil had soaked in only an inch. In others, it was found several inches deep. `` They're never going to get it all,'' he said. In <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, meanwhile, state environmental chief <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> said the crippled <PERSON> Exxon </PERSON> <PERSON> Valdez </PERSON> appeared sound enough to make it to the Port of <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION> for evaluation. He said he expected <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> to agree to several conditions before officials allow the tanker to travel up the <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>.
