<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Stocks Off</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with Morning Nikkei, comments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar traded higher against the Japanese yen at midday Tuesday, while the key index on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> posted a moderate loss. The dollar, which opened at 132.23 yen, up 0.40 yen from Monday's 131.83-yen finish, was quoted at 132.20 yen at midday. The currency moved in a narrow range of 132.10-132 .27 yen The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained 157.89 points to close at a record-high 33,308.33 Monday, ended the morning session at 33,254.49, down 53.84 points or 0.16 percent. The index rose marginally in early morning trading but began falling as investors sold for profit taking, said <PERSON> Tsuneo </PERSON> <PERSON> Ishii </PERSON> with <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>. `` That's mainly because participants were concerned about the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> consumer price index report to be released later tonight and avoided buying,'' he said. Later Tuesday, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> was to announce the March <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> consumer price index, which measures changes in the retail prices of a constant market basket of goods and services. Investors also were discouraged by concerns over the Recruit bribery scandal, dealers said. Prosecutors are expected to make more arrests this week in connection with the affair. So far, prosecutors have arrested 14 people in connection with stock profiteering and suspected bribery linked to a major information services firm, <ORGANIZATION> Recruit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. In currency dealings, the dollar-yen rate was moving little as market players avoided making major moves ahead of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> CPI </ORGANIZATION> announcement, traders said.
